{Terminology The positional and tactical as well concept of the exchange sacrifice rook for a bishop or a knight is a very important topic, the exploration of which requires advanced skills and competitive experience.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – Explanation of the Concept"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734230112"]

{Explanation of the Concept There is ample testimony in the literature to the increasing importance of the exchange sacrifice in contemporary chess and to its role in the ever more dynamic and concrete nature of the game, particularly at the top level. GM John Watson was willing to put its increasing frequency as probably the most widely-acknowledged change in modern chess technique. In his book Chess For Zebras , Jonathan Rowson goes even further, claiming that ‘in my experience most GMs now think of exchange sacrifices as mainstream - no more exciting than exchanging bishop for knight, but this hasn't yet trickled down into other levels of the game’. Nonetheless, even armed with this insight there has surely been something striking and profoundly impressive about the wealth of fascinating examples generated by top players. GM Mihail Marin notices the fact that the psychological effects may not be all one way. He points out that ‘once the artistic feeling has been satisfied, the practical player starts thinking about the result. Being an exchange down, perhaps one should be happy with a draw’! In other words, compensation is great, but doubts can set in as there is still something a bit scary about being material down!} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – Dogmatic Rules"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734238305"]

{Dogmatic Rules The exchange sacrifice is a difficult subject to master, as the chess player is requested to overcome the dogmatic rules with which he has been brought up, in particular the quantitative evaluation of material. Here we will not concern ourselves with an exchange sacrifice if it is immediately followed by a mating attack or material gains. For this reason, the term 'positional exchange sacrifice' will be often used, in order to indicate that the exchange is given up in order to establish long-term advantages compensation, which the sacrificing side hopes will ultimately be repaid.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – First Steps"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734246498"]

{First Steps When we are taking our first steps in the process of learning and indeed mastering chess, we are taught that a rook's value is five pawns and that of a bishop/knight is three pawns. With this arithmetical preconception we move on to play our royal game for quite a long time. This is the correct approach to learning the game, as in these early stages it is quite difficult to master the more complicated methods that govern advanced chess strategies. When growing up chess-wise we note that, from time to time, a bishop/knight can be proven stronger than a rook. But in our minds we might come to the conclusion that this was just a coincidence, a rare phenomenon, and somehow think that the side with the rook didn’t handle his position with the required accuracy. But this is not entirely true! We have to reassess our chess thinking and discover a different approach to the rook vs. bishop/knight concept. To sum up, there is a strong case for approaching both exchanges and exchange sacrifices with a similar mentality; one that takes decisions according to the concrete value of the pieces rather than any generic value. As chess players improve, they come to rely less on preconceived notions of relative value. Consequently, an exchange sacrifice will, at least to some extent, raise fewer eyebrows.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – Frequency"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734254691"]

{Frequency Keep in mind that the increasing frequency of the exchange sacrifice is probably the most widely acknowledged change in modern chess technique! In many cases the idea of sacrificing the exchange is born out of necessity, prompted by the opponent's strong threats i.e., when there is no other acceptable way of meeting them. However, an exchange sacrifice of this kind, known as a passive exchange sacrifice, doesn’t guarantee positive results. Furthermore, its failure to meet one's aims something quite common in such cases affects the player psychologically and causes him to refrain from such actions in the future.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – Units"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734262884"]

{Units In the opening and the middlegame our pieces should be identified as units that, by cooperating harmoniously, shape our plans, which in turn are executed by means of moves. Each unit is an integral part of our position and we can determine our advantage or inferiority only by taking all units into account, and identifying and evaluating both their positive and negative aspects. Naturally, it is not easy to identify which of our pieces or even the opponent's pieces is carrying out the most significant function. We have to take several strategic elements into consideration, such as the centre, open lines, initiative, attack, etc. When carrying out such evaluations, the value of our rooks barely differs from that of our minor pieces, since an advantage is only conferred by their fruitful cooperation and not their individual, predetermined value. If we accept that, as a rule, the superiority of the rook is not realized until the endgame usually the rook is unstoppable in this part of the game, we naturally come to the conclusion that an exchange sacrifice is more likely to occur in the opening or the middlegame but sometimes in the endgame too! and can be justified in many different contexts, furthering several diverse aims.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – Primary Aims"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734271077"]

{Primary Aims Of course, the primary aim is to seize the initiative, the momentum of which very often shatters the opponent. This is because the sacrificing party is actually playing a 'piece ahead' for some time especially when sacrificing in the opening because the rooks have not yet come into the game. The exchange sacrifice is becoming even more routine nowadays and there are many standard positions in which exchange sacrifices are of a second nature, for example, ...[Rxc3] in various 'Sicilian Defence' opening schemes, or ...[Rxf3] in similar settings in the 'French Defence'. In both of these cases Black gains the advantage of split and doubled pawns in the enemy camp, as well as the initiative among others.} 1. Z0 *

