{Exchange Sacrifice Types Before we expand on the important reasons compensation for sacrificing the exchange, we must make an essential differentiation between the two main types there are many sub-cases of exchange sacrifices:} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – The Active Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734283367"]

{The Active Exchange Sacrifice Before the 1930s this was a rare occurrence. First Mikhail Botvinnik and then Tigran Petrosian as well as other famous Soviet masters employed the exchange sacrifice as a 'lethal weapon' and exploited its benefits. So, there is no doubt that the exchange sacrifice is part and parcel of modern chess, in a way that it never was before the 1930s. The ex-World Champion Tigran Petrosian gives us a clear 'description' of the exchange sacrifice: " I have gradually realised that the greatest difficulty presenting itself when sacrificing the exchange is entirely of a psychological nature.When a chess player decides about his move, knowledge of the material connection involuntarily eliminates from his mind moves by which valuable pieces become capturable. " But nowadays every top player looks for opportunities to benefit from an appropriate exchange sacrifice. Thus, the goals of making an exchange sacrifice include: To exploit a better development.To destroy the opponent's pawn structure.To open lines in order to attack.To control important squares individual ones or complexes.To control important diagonals.To assume the initiative.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – The Passive Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734295656"]

{The Passive Exchange Sacrifice As all the previous concepts were focused on the active exchange sacrifice, the reader might get the wrong impression that our subject has no passive side. Not every exchange sacrifice is made to create winning chances and obtain the initiative; there are also exchange sacrifices that are made with the purpose of defending. We call them 'passive', as was already described in the introduction. The passive exchange sacrifice is easier to play during a game, as in most cases, there is no better alternative. This type of sacrifice was much more common before the 1930s and is of course, still common today! and may serve the following aims among others: To repulse the opponent's attack.To repulse the opponent's initiative a more general interpretation of the first point.To destroy the coordination of the opponent's pieces.To assume the initiative. Of course, the list of aims, in both cases, can be wider.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction – The Right Moment"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463734303849"]

{The Right Moment As with all such advanced strategic and tactical concepts, one factor of great significance is the perception of the right moment to carry them out. The ambitious chess player must train himself to realise when a situation requires an exchange sacrifice, after properly evaluating the course of the game and the peculiarities specific to the position. The correct implementation of the exchange sacrifice requires an open mind and a proper qualitative evaluation of the position. But never forget: sometimes your opponent too may value a minor piece higher than his rook! In general, you must keep in mind that the exchange sacrifice is not always successful. Nobody guarantees a victory for the side that executes the exchange sacrifice, so do not start to give your rooks away in order to reserve a place in a future book dedicated to exchange sacrifices! Keep in mind that there is a reasonable balance, both between the 'positional' and 'dynamic' elements of exchange sacrifices and in considering the factors likely to determine success or failure for the player investing material. I believe that this concept continues to be one of the richest and most satisfying areas of the modern game. But still, my advice is to think twice before you proceed, because there is no way back…} 1. Z0 *

