1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Nbd2 f5 12. Nxe4 $2 ({Note from a tester: This careless move gives Black a strong advantage in the center and opens the f-file for his rook. It would have been better to take en passant:} 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Ng5 Qd7 14. Nxe6 Qxe6 15. Re1 {, and White is clearly better.}) 12... fxe4 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 a5 15. a4 c6 16. f4 Qd7 17. axb5 cxb5 18. g4 a4 {Note 2: This move has a small side benefit that makes it worthwhile: once the rook leaves the a-file, the Black a-pawn won’t be hanging as it would on [a5].} 19. Ba2 Bxg4 20. Bxd5+ Kh8 21. e6 ({Black could have simply played Qxd5} 21. Qxg4 Rf5 {with an advantage, but Spielmann made an interesting decision to sacrifice the exchange.}) 21... Bxe6 22. Bxa8 ({White had to try} 22. Bxe4 Ra6 {((Note 3: Black could play either 22...Rac8 or 22...Rae8 , options made possible by 18...a4. These choices reflect Black's thoughtful play earlier in the game. ))} 23. d5 Bf5 {∓ .}) 22... Rxa8 {[%csl Yg1,Be6,Be7,Bb5,Ba4,Rc4,Rh3,Rg4][%cal Ge6h3,Ge6g4,Ge6c4] His decision is based compensation on the following important compensating factors: 1. Control of the light squares. 2. The bishop pair. 3. Potential passed pawn on the queenside. 4. Strong attack on the white king. By combining all of the above, Black should be considered to be in the driver's' seat.} *

