{The Soviet masters were the first to develop a specific ‘feeling’ for the exchange sacrifice. They did study it in depth and they were the first to comprehend its value. Here follow two excellent games played by two famous players:} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Viktor Korchnoi – Efim Geller, Kiev 1954 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B64"]
[PlyCount "35"]
[GameId "2130463734586489"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. f4 e5 ({Note from a tester: 'This ambitious pawn push dropped out of popularity, perhaps partly due to Korchnoi's convincing play in this game. Black aims to weaken White's e-pawn by trading on f4, but things don’t go as planned.} 9... h6 {or 9...Nxd4 were better alternatives.'}) 10. Nf3 Bg4 11. h3 Bxf3 ({Note 2:} 11... Bc8 {would allow White to lock things up with} 12. f5 {, at which point Black suffers from the weakness of [d5]. Moreover, White has a ready-made kingside pawn storm with [g4], [h4], etc.}) 12. gxf3 Nd4 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Rg1 Nxf3 15. Qf2 Qb6 16. Be3 Nd4 {It seems that Black has correctly organised his defence and is ready to take action on the queenside. His strongly placed [d4]-knight in cooperation with his major pieces will do the job. But White had a different opinion:} 17. Rxd4 $1 {A strong exchange sacrifice.} ({Of course, not} 17. Bxd4 $2 exd4 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Rxd4 Bc5 {-+ .}) 17... exd4 18. Bxd4 {[%csl Rb6] Now White's forces are ready to harass the black king, while the black counterparts are simply silent observers… A sad reality for the proud Efim Geller…} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Korchnoi vs. Geller #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp2bppp/1q3n2/8/3BP3/2N4P/PPP2Q2/2K2BR1 b - - 0 18"]
[PlyCount "8"]
[GameId "2130463734615162"]

18... Qe6 {In the game, Efim Geller played an other queen move 18...Qd8 . 18...Qe6 contains the same idea of protecting both [e7] and [f6]. How do you respond?} 19. Nd5 {Note from a tester: 19.Nd5, is essential to White's compensation. The [g7]-square is severely weak, and White activates the light-squared bishop on [c4], creating a latent threat to Black's queen.} Ne8 20. Bc4 ({Note from a tester:} 20. Nc7 {doesn't help due to} Qh6+ 21. Kb1 Rd8 {.}) 20... Kh8 21. Kb1 {Preventing any ...[Qh6]} Rc8 22. Bb3 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gf2g3] Black seems to have run out of decent continuations.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Korchnoi vs. Geller #3"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp2bppp/1q3n2/8/3BP3/2N4P/PPP2Q2/2K2BR1 b - - 0 18"]
[PlyCount "8"]
[GameId "2130463734635643"]

18... Qd8 {18...Qd8 was played by Geller in the game. How did "Viktor The Terrible" replied?} 19. Nd5 $1 Ne8 {[%csl Ya8,Yd8,Ye8,Yf8,Bg7][%cal Ge8g7] Protecting [g7]. See how passive are the black pieces.} 20. Qf5 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf5e5,Ge5g7,Ge5e7] It is not an obvious move. We are threatening [Qe5], which would attack both the bishop and the [g7]-pawn.} Qd6 {Preventing [Qe5].} 21. Bc4 {Bringing our last inactive piece into action. Note that 4.Bb5 is appealing, but deceptive due to 4...g6 .} Kh8 22. Kb1 {[%cal Gc4d3,Ge4e5,Yd6h6] Black has no clear plan. White has active pieces and sufficient compensation for the exchange. GM Ramesh RB says we don't need to find a forced win for White to go for this and play something like [a3]. However, the engine seems to like the direct [Bd3], followed by [e5].} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Korchnoi vs. Geller #4"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2qnrk1/pp2bppp/8/3N4/3BP3/7P/PPP2Q2/2K2BR1 w - - 0 20"]
[PlyCount "11"]
[GameId "2130463734643836"]

20. Qg3 $2 ({After} 20. Qf5 $1 Qd6 21. Bc4 Kh8 22. Kb1 {, Black would have nothing to move...}) 20... f6 $2 ({Black should have tried} 20... Bh4 $1 21. Qf4 {(21.Qg4 g6 22.Bc5 Ng7 23.Bxf8 Kxf8 ⩲)} Kh8 22. c3 Be7 23. Bd3 {± .}) {It should be easy for you to find Korchnoi's reply to 20...f6?, but try to calculate a few moves ahead.} 21. Bc4 Rf7 ({The weakness of the diagonal a2-g8 is fatal:} 21... Kh8 22. Nf4 $1 Qa5 23. Bd5 Bd6 24. Ng6+ hxg6 25. Qh4# {.}) 22. Nf4 $1 Bd6 ({Another instance of the weak a2-g8 diagonal can be found in} 22... Qxd4 23. Bxf7+ Kxf7 24. Qb3+ Kf8 25. Ne6+ {+- .}) 23. Bxf7+ Kxf7 24. Qb3+ $1 Ke7 25. Bxf6+ $1 {[%csl Re6,Rg8][%cal Gb3e6,Gg1g8]} (25. Bxf6+ {Black resigned in view of} gxf6 26. Qe6+ Kf8 27. Rg8# {.}) 1-0

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Paul Keres – László Szabó, Budapest 1955 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B66"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[GameId "2130463734660221"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. f4 a6 10. e5 dxe5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. fxe5 Nd7 13. h4 Rb8 14. Qe3 Re8 15. Rh3 Qa5 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. Rg3 Re8 {Opposite-castled kings always lead to tense and lively play. One of the most important factors that rule the correct handling of the attack is tempi, and time in general.} 18. Rxd7 $1 {Black's [d7]-knight was his probably most active piece, as it was not only applying pressure on White's [e5]-pawn but could also be easily transferred to the defence kingside or to the offence queenside. A precious piece that was eliminated/exchanged for just a rook!} ({Editor's Note:} 18. Re1 {is stronger. It, as wrote a tester, 'stabilize the e-pawn, after which White can increase the kingside pressure without sacrificing the exchange.' But you are not studying a course entitled, Play Rock-Solid Chess.}) 18... Bxd7 19. Bd3 {[%csl Rh6,Rh7,Rg5][%cal Gd3h7,Ge3h6,Ge3g5]} ({White had no intention to opt for the draw with} 19. Rxg7+ Kxg7 20. Qg5+ {, but just to complete his development, 'allowing' yet another force to join the attack.}) ({Note: The counter-intuitive 19.b3 or the direct 19.Qg5 are even stronger:} 19. b3 Rb4 20. Qg5 g6 21. h5) (19. Qg5 g6 20. h5 {" 19.Bd3 seems to make complete sense, as it brings an additional piece into the attack – one that wasn’t playing a major role previously. This move also sets up the ideas behind 19.b3 and 19.Qg5. – Ramesh R. B. "}) *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Keres vs. Szabó #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1r2r1k1/3b1ppp/p1p1p3/q3P3/7P/2NBQ1R1/PPP3P1/2K5 b - - 0 19"]
[PlyCount "4"]
[GameId "2130463734692990"]

19... g6 {In this variation if Black plays 19...g6, what is the only winning move?} 20. h5 {Yes, you found it!} Rf8 21. Qf4 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gf4f6,Gh5h6] Ne4 will come with force. In general, I cannot find any proper defence for Black, but maybe this should be considered quite natural, as White attacks with queen, rook, bishop, knight and pawn, while Black's defence is entirely based on the poor [f8]-rook!} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Keres vs. Szabó #3"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1r2r1k1/3b1ppp/p1p1p3/q3P3/7P/2NBQ1R1/PPP3P1/2K5 b - - 0 19"]
[PlyCount "10"]
[GameId "2130463734701183"]

19... h6 {An alternative to the previous puzzle. This time, there are two winning moves. Can you spot them?} 20. Qe4 $1 ({Editor's Note: The author called} 20. Qe4 {a 'better continuation' than the game's 20.Qf4 , but both moves win.}) 20... Kf8 21. Rxg7 $1 Ke7 (21... Kxg7 22. Qh7+ Kf8 23. Qxh6+ Ke7 24. Qf6+ Kf8 25. Bg6 {+-}) 22. Rxf7+ $1 Kd8 (22... Kxf7 23. Qh7+ Kf8 24. Bg6 {+-}) 23. Qd4 Rb7 24. Qd6 $18 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gd3g6] The game saw a similar finish: 20.Qf4 Kf8?! ( Black should have tried 20...Qc5 21.Ne4 (( 21.Qf6? Qe3+! )) 21...Qg1+ 22.Kd2 Kf8 23.Qg4 Ke7 24.Qxg7 Kd8 25.Qxf7 Kc7 26.Rg7 +- . ) 21.Rxg7! A neat combination that leads to mate. 21...Kxg7 22.Qf6+ Kf8 23.Bg6 1-0} 1-0

