{The long-standing leading Hungarian player Lajos Portisch was closely following the developments in the ex-Soviet Union and copied the fruitful discoveries of the country's top players:} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Lajos Portisch – Győző Forintos, Budapest 1958 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D15"]
[PlyCount "27"]
[GameId "2130463734717569"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 b5 6. a4 Nd5 7. axb5 Nxc3 8. bxc3 cxb5 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. Rb1 a6 11. Bxc4 e6 12. O-O Nd7 {How can you keep the black king in the centre?} 13. Rxb5 $1 {Yes, this exchange sacrifice serves that purpose very well.} axb5 (13... Qc7 14. Rxb7 $1 Qxb7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Bb3 $1 Qc7 17. Ba4+ Kd8 18. e4 {± is the other option. Editor's Note: Is it really? As Steinitz said, 'A sacrifice is best refuted by accepting it'. In this case, the sacrifice can't be refuted but accepting it is still the only critical move.}) 14. Bxb5 {[%csl Rd7]} (14. Bxb5 {Editor's Note: Black now has the choice between hanging on to the piece with} Bc8 {or continuing development with 14...Bd6 (or 14...Be7 ) .}) *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Portisch vs. Forintos #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/1b1n1ppp/4p3/1B2N3/3P4/2P1P3/5PPP/2BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 14"]
[PlyCount "6"]
[GameId "2130463734738050"]

14... Bd6 {In the game, Forintos replied to the exchange with the best move 14...Bd6. The position is equal. We're tactically on the razor's edge. Find the only good move, and the possible answers by Black.} 15. Bxd7+ Ke7 16. Nc6+ Bxc6 17. Bxc6 {[%csl Ra8] It is time to take stock. White's exchange sacrifice gave him compensation, based on the following aspects: 1. Two pawns one might be lost. 2. The bishop pair. 3. Attack on the 'centralised' opponent king.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Portisch vs. Forintos #3"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2q3r/4kppp/2Bbp3/8/3P4/2P1P3/5PPP/2BQ1RK1 b - - 0 17"]
[PlyCount "8"]
[GameId "2130463734746243"]

17... Rc8 $6 ({Black had to go for} 17... Bxh2+ 18. Kh1 $1 Rc8 19. Bb5 Bd6 20. c4 Kf8 21. Qh5 {∞ .}) {The continuation of puzzle #2. 17...Rc8?! was Portisch's opponent's move. What did the Hungarian legend play in response?} 18. d5 $1 exd5 ({Returning the exchange is not helpful either:} 18... Rxc6 19. dxc6 Qc7 20. Qg4 g6 21. Qh4+ f6 22. c4 Qxc6 23. Bb2 e5 24. Ra1 {± .}) 19. Bxd5 Rxc3 20. Bb2 ({Editor's Note: starting with} 20. Qh5 {is the best} Rf8 21. Bb2 {.}) 20... Rc5 21. g3 $18 {[%csl Rf3,Rh5][%cal Gd1f3,Gf3h5,Ge3e4]} ({Editor's Note:} 21. e4 {was played in the game, but the engine slightly favors 21.g3 to take ...Bxh2+ out of the equation. 21...Bxg3 fails to 22.Ba3 Bd6 23.Bxc5 Bxc5 24.Qh5! with a strong attack. White's bishops are dominating.}) *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Portisch vs. Forintos #4"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/1b1B1ppp/3bp3/4N3/3P4/2P1P3/5PPP/2BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 15"]
[PlyCount "10"]
[GameId "2130463734754436"]

15... Kf8 {The other option. See the variation with 15...Ke7, played in the game, here.} 16. c4 {The move is thematic, taking advantage of Black's passive position.} Qc7 ({Better is} 16... Bxe5 17. dxe5 {.}) 17. Bb5 {Forward-looking the following move.} Bxe5 (17... g6 18. f4 Kg7 19. d5 {±}) 18. dxe5 Qxe5 {Not a bad move, but it lets the opponent queen infiltrate.} 19. Qd7 {[%csl Rb7,Ra3][%cal Gc1a3,Gd7b7] Creating some bank rank issues.} Qb8 20. Bb2 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc4c5] White develops the bishop to a powerful diagonal, the [g7]-pawn is a mid-term target and the center is under control. This move solidifies White's position and prepares to increase the pressure further, possibly with [Rd1] or [c5]. White's compensation is good.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Portisch vs. Forintos #4"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/1b1n1ppp/4p3/1B2N3/3P4/2P1P3/5PPP/2BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 14"]
[PlyCount "8"]
[GameId "2130463734762629"]

14... Bc8 {What if Black had mistakenly chosen to protect the attacked knight with 14...Bc8? There is only one crushing move.} 15. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7,Ra8] A strong double attack.} f6 16. Qxa8 fxe5 17. d5 $1 {This is the only winning move. It strikes at the center, taking advantage of Black’s exposed king and lack of piece coordination.} exd5 18. Qxd5 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ge3e4] The queen now threatens multiple weaknesses in Black’s camp. Black, whose counterplay is limited, is left with no decent reply to [Rd1], [e4] and maybe later [Bg5].} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Portisch vs. Forintos (Analysis)"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3q3r/4kppp/3b4/2rB4/8/4P3/1B3PPP/3Q1RK1 w - - 0 21"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[GameId "2130463734770822"]

21. e4 Bxh2+ (21... Qb8 $6 {is a worse continuation:} 22. Bd4 Bxh2+ 23. Kh1 Bd6 24. Qg4 {+- .}) 22. Kh1 $1 (22. Kxh2 $2 Qb8+ {∞ .}) 22... Qb6 23. Qd4 $2 (23. Qd2 $1 Bf4 24. Qxf4 Qxb2 25. Qxf7+ {is the correct way.}) 23... Rb5 $2 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gd4g7] Losing.} ({Good is} 23... Qh6 $1 24. Qxg7 {(24.Qxc5+? Bd6 + -+)} Qxg7 25. Bxg7 Rg8 26. Bd4 Bd6 27. Bxc5 Bxc5 {and Black has decent drawing chances. Returning material back in order to release the tension is a well-known tool used by strong players!}) 24. Qxg7 Rxb2 25. Qxf7+ $1 {Who really cares for a lonely rook on the [h8]-square? The bishops are more important!} Kd8 26. Kxh2 $6 ({White could immediately win with the simple} 26. Be6 Qd6 {(26...Rd2 27.Rc1 +-)} 27. Qf6+ {+- .}) 26... Qd6+ $6 ({Black should try to resist with} 26... Qh6+ 27. Kg1 Rf8 28. Qa7 Qb6 29. Qa8+ Qb8 30. Qa3 {± .}) 27. Kg1 Qe7 28. Qh5 $1 Rf8 29. Ra1 {[%csl Ra8] Now it's all over.} Rb8 30. Bc6 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gh5a5]} Qf7 31. Rd1+ Kc7 32. Qe5+ $1 {White handles the final assault with accuracy.} Kxc6 33. Rc1+ Kb7 34. Qb5+ Ka8 35. Ra1+ Qa7 36. Qd5+ $1 Rb7 37. Rxa7+ Kxa7 38. Qc5+ {[%csl Rf8,Ra7]} Ka6 39. Qxf8 1-0

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
