{Of course, no collection of examples with an attack on the king could be complete without some games of the extra-ordinary Bobby Fischer. The way he instructed the various attacking schemes, is still legendary:} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Bobby Fischer – Dragoljub Minić, Vinkovci 1968 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C33"]
[PlyCount "41"]
[GameId "2130463734807688"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Bc4 Ne7 4. Nc3 c6 5. Nf3 d5 6. Bb3 dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nd5 8. Qe2 Be7 9. c4 Nc7 10. d4 O-O 11. Bxf4 Ne6 12. Be3 Bb4+ 13. Kf2 Nd7 14. c5 Nf6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Rhf1 Nf4 17. Bxf4 Qxf4 18. g3 Qh6 19. Kg1 Bh3 {The black bishop pair seems to be a force, but the [f7]-square is also a vulnerable point.} 20. Ne5 $1 {A bolt from the blue!} Bxf1 {There is nothing to be done.} ({White gets a clear advantage after the decline of the sacrifice with} 20... Qd2 21. Qxd2 {(21.Qe4! Be6 22.Bxe6 fxe6 23.a3 +- seems to be even stronger. )} Bxd2 22. Rf3 $1 Be6 23. Bxe6 fxe6 24. Rb3 Rfd8 25. Nf3 Bh6 26. Re1 {and, although White will win a pawn, Black keeps some slim practical chances to save the game.}) 21. Rxf1 {[%csl Rf7,Yb4] This exchange sacrifice is fully justified, as the [f7]-square will come under heavy pressure and the [b4]-bishop seems to be out of play defence.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Fischer vs. Minić #2"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp3ppp/2p4q/2P1N3/1b1P4/1B4P1/PP2Q2P/5RK1 b - - 0 21"]
[PlyCount "6"]
[GameId "2130463734848649"]

21... Bd2 {What did the eleventh World Chess Champion played here?} 22. Rf3 $1 (22. Nxf7 $6 {would be too naive for Bobby Fischer:} Qe3+ 23. Qxe3 Bxe3+ 24. Kg2 Rxf7 25. Rxf7 Kh8 26. Rxb7 Bxd4 27. Ba4 Bxc5 28. Bxc6 Rf8 {± . The queens must be retained on the board, as Black's king is the more vulnerable.}) 22... Rad8 $6 ({This allows a neat combination, but also the relatively best continuation} 22... Kh8 23. Nxf7+ Rxf7 24. Bxf7 Bg5 25. Kg2 {(25.d5 cxd5 26.Bxd5 +-)} Rf8 26. d5 cxd5 27. Bxd5 {+- is curtains.}) 23. Nxf7 {[%csl Rh6,Rd8]} Rxf7 {[%csl Yf7]} 24. Qe7 $1 {[%csl Rd8,Yf7] The final detail! Black loses too much material, so he resigned.} (24. Qe7 Rb8 25. Qxf7+ Kh8 26. Qf8+ Rxf8 27. Rxf8#) 1-0

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Fischer vs. Minić #3"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp3ppp/2p4q/2P1N3/1b1P4/1B4P1/PP2Q2P/5RK1 b - - 0 21"]
[PlyCount "6"]
[GameId "2130463734860938"]

21... Qd2 {An alternative defence. Minić played 21...Bd2 see puzzle #2. Can you find the winning move?} 22. Qe4 $1 (22. Qxd2 $2 {Editor's Note: In the presence of opposite-coloured bishops, exchanging queens gives Black excellent drawing chances.} Bxd2 23. Nxf7 Rae8 24. Nd6+ Kh8 25. Nxe8 Rxe8 26. Kg2 {±}) 22... Kh8 23. Nxf7+ Rxf7 24. Rxf7 $18 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge4e5]} (24. Rxf7 {Editor's Note: The opposite-coloured bishops favour the attacking side, and given the activity of White's pieces, Black is dead lost. GM Grivas gives} Qxb2 25. Bc2 Qc1+ 26. Kg2 Qd2+ 27. Rf2 Qh6 28. Qe7 {+- .}) *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Bobby Fischer – Bent Larsen, Portorož 1958 #1"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "B77"]
[PlyCount "45"]
[GameId "2130463734869131"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. Bc4 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 11. Bb3 Qa5 12. O-O-O b5 13. Kb1 b4 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Rac8 16. Bb3 Rc7 17. h4 Qb5 18. h5 Rfc8 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. g4 a5 {What do typically play against the Sicilian Defence: Dragon Variation? Find Bobby's moves!} 21. g5 Nh5 22. Rxh5 $1 {And a typical reaction; the exchange sacrifice aiming to open the h-file.} gxh5 $2 {This loses without a fight.} ({Black had to defend with} 22... Bxd4 23. Qxd4 gxh5 24. g6 Rc4 $1 {(24...Qe5? 25.gxf7+ Kf8 (25...Kh7 26.Qd3 +-) 26.Qxe5 dxe5 27.Rg1 e6 28.Bxe6 Ke7 29.Bxc8 Rxc8 30.Rg5 +-)} 25. Qe3 fxg6 26. Qh6 Kf7 27. Qh7+ Kf6 28. f4 Qe8 29. Re1 e6 30. Bxc4 Rxc4 31. b3 Rc5 32. Rf1 Qf7 33. e5+ Ke7 34. exd6+ Ke8 35. d7+ Qxd7 36. Qxg6+ Kd8 {. Black is still alive, but with such an exposed king and worst pawn structure, he will not survive in the long run...}) 23. g6 $1 {[%csl Rf7]} (23. g6 {Editor's Note: Black has two defensive tries now,} e6 {and 23...e5 (the game's move both of which we will explore in the upcoming exercises)}) (23. g6 {Another continuation with best play,} Bxd4 24. gxf7+ Kf8 25. Qxd4 Qe5 26. Qg1 Qg7 {.}) 1-0

