[GameId "2130463734983830"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 7. Rc1 Ne4 8. cxd5 Nxc3 9. Qd2 Qxa2 10. bxc3 Qa5 11. Bc4 Nd7 12. Ne2 Ne5 13. Ba2 Bf5 14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. Nd4 Qxc5 16. Nxf5 gxf5 17. O-O Qa5 18. Qc2 f4 19. c4 fxe3 20. c5 Qd2 21. Qa4+ Kf8 22. Rcd1 Qe2 23. d6 Qh5 {An historical and famous game; the 2nd one of their FIDE Semi-final match for the World Championship 1972. Editor's Note: As pointed out the tester Matszhie, Tigran Petrosian was renowned for his mastery of exchange sacrifices. What did 'Iron Tigran' play in this position?} 24. f4 $1 {Editor's Note: the engine prefers:} (24. fxe3 Bxh2+ 25. Kf2 {; or,}) (24. dxe7+ Kg7 25. fxe3 Bxh2+ 26. Kf2 {.}) 24... e2 $2 ({Black shouldn't have accepted the exchange sacrifice and instead opt for} 24... Bf6 25. Rd5 Qg6 26. Qb3 Rg8 27. g3 Re8 28. Re1 {± .}) 25. fxe5 exd1=Q 26. Rxd1 {So, Black 'won' the exchange, but his king is in bad shape and his rooks passive.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Petrosian vs. Fischer #2"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r4k1r/pp2pp1p/3P4/2P1P2q/Q7/8/B5PP/3R2K1 b - - 0 26"]
[PlyCount "8"]
[GameId "2130463735004311"]

26... Kg7 {Instead of 26...Qxe5 , Black could have chosen to escape with 26...Kg7 too – how should White continue?'} 27. Rf1 {[%csl Rf7] The most precise move, attacking [f7].} Qxe5 (27... e6 28. Bxe6 {+-}) 28. Rxf7+ Kh6 29. Qh4+ Kg6 30. Rxe7 $18 {[%csl Re5] Black is busted.} ({A sample continuation:} 30. Rxe7 Qxc5+ 31. Kh1 Qc1+ 32. Re1 {. Black will either lose the queen or the game quickly.}) 1-0

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Petrosian vs. Fischer #3"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r4k1r/pp2pp1p/3P4/2P1P2q/Q7/8/B5PP/3R2K1 b - - 0 26"]
[PlyCount "12"]
[GameId "2130463735016600"]

26... Qxe5 {We have seen that, despite winning the exchange, Fischer has two problems: • his king is exposed; and, • his rooks are passive. Find the sequence of moves Petrosian used to conclude the game.} 27. Rf1 $1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf1f7] Attacking the pawn.} f6 (27... f5 28. Qb3 Kg7 29. Qf7+ Kh6 30. dxe7 {+-}) 28. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ga2f7] Threatening mate.} Kg7 {Black choses to run away.} 29. Qf7+ {[%csl Rg7]} Kh6 30. dxe7 {[%csl Be7,Rf6][%cal Gf1f6] Threatening Rxf6+ which would win the queen and the game. The advanced [e7] passed pawn is a liability for Black: this queening threat limits the activity of Black's pieces and hinders counterplay.} f5 31. Rxf5 Qd4+ 32. Kh1 (32. Kh1 {Black, with best play} Qd1+ 33. Rf1 Qh5 {, would lose their queen} 34. Rf6+ {and get mated.}) 1-0

