{The New Era The new generation of the ex-Soviet Union countries players were taught the subject of the exchange sacrifice in depth by their famous teachers. So, it was more than natural for them to use it in many of their games. See the next examples:} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Ivanchuk vs. Kramnik #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B66"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2130463735037082"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O h6 9. Be3 Be7 10. f4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. Qe3 Qc7 13. e5 dxe5 14. Bxe5 {Kramnik came up with a very interesting idea in this position. Can you match his choice?} Ng4 $1 {Black sacrifices an exchange in order to obtain a strong initiative, while White also loses some tempi with his queen. — Why did Black decide on the exchange sacrifice? — Well, one of the main aspects of the position in question is that there will probably be opposite flank attacks, in which as we have already explained every piece should be counted as a potential attacking unit. With this in mind, Kramnik evaluated probably not over the board but at home that his attacking possibilities are greater and that his minor pieces would prove stronger than White's rooks.} 15. Qf3 ({White must accept the offer, as otherwise, he would have to say goodbye to any opening advantage:} 15. Bxc7 Nxe3 16. Rd3 Nc4 {(16...Nxf1 17.Rxf1 Bb7 ⩱ T. Weber – J. Werle, Oropesa del Mar 1998. )} 17. Rd4 Ra7 18. Bb8 Rb7 19. Bxc4 Rxb8 {∓ .}) 15... Nxe5 16. Qxa8 ({Forced:} 16. fxe5 $6 Bb7 {∓ .}) 16... Nd7 $1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Ge8g8,Gc8b7,Ge7c5] Editor's Note: This is what Kramnik had to foresee when he played 14...Ng4. Black wants to finish his development with ...[O-O] and ...[Bb7], winning time on White's queen, and then launch an attack against White's king.} (16... Nc6 $2 17. Nxb5 $1 axb5 {(17...Qxf4+ 18.Kb1 O-O 19.Qxc6 axb5 20.Qxb5 +-)} 18. Bxb5 O-O 19. Qxc6 {+- .}) *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Ivanchuk vs. Kramnik #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "Q1b1k2r/2qnbpp1/p3p2p/1p6/5P2/2N5/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R w k - 0 17"]
[PlyCount "10"]
[GameId "2130463735057563"]

17. g3 $2 {A dubious move.} ({Also not good enough was} 17. Qf3 $6 Bb7 18. Qg3 b4 19. Ne2 {(19.Na4 O-O ∓ )} O-O 20. f5 e5 21. Qd3 Nc5 {(21...Rc8 22.Ng3 Nf6 23.Be2 Bxg2 -+ D. Gross – M. Borriss, Germany 1996. )} 22. Qc4 Rd8 23. h4 Rxd1+ 24. Kxd1 Qd8+ 25. Kc1 Ne4 26. Qd3 Qb6 27. Qf3 Qa5 {0-1 S. Mozaliov – S. Kiselev, Moscow 1996,}) ({but White had to play} 17. f5 Nb6 18. Qf3 exf5 19. Qg3 $1 {(19.Bd3 g6 ∓)} Qxg3 20. hxg3 Bb7 {⩱ .}) {Can you find the sequence of top moves played in the game?} 17... Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] Editor's Note: An important move, making sure Black gets to play ...[Bb7].} (17... O-O {?} 18. Bg2 {⩱ and White gains the control over the [h1]-[a8] diagonal, when Black's compensation shouldn't be strong.}) 18. Qf3 Bb7 19. Ne4 {[%cal Gf4f5]} f5 $1 {Editor's Note: White was preparing to play [f5], aiming to establish strong control over the light squares and significantly limiting Black's ability to capitalize on the pin along the long diagonal.} 20. Qh5+ (20. Bd3 $6 O-O 21. Qe2 fxe4 22. Bxe4 Bc8 {-+ .}) 20... Kf8 21. Nf2 (21. Bg2 fxe4 22. Rhe1 Qc4 {-+ .}) 21... Bf6 $1 {[%cal Gb6a4,Gf8e7,Gh8c8] Editor's Note: Kramnik shows his exceptional understanding of the game. The [b7]-bishop is stronger than the [h1]-rook. Black can create an attack against the white king with ...[Na4], ...[Ke7] and ...[Rc8]. Maybe it will still be possible to win the exchange back later.} ({A much better try than} 21... Bc5 $2 22. Nh3 Bxh1 23. Ng5 hxg5 {(23...g6? 24.Qxg6 Bd5 25.Rxd5 +-)} 24. Qxh8+ Kf7 25. Qh5+) ({Editor's Note:} 21... Bxh1 {is also possible. After} 22. Nxh1 Bf6 $5 {(22...Nd5? 23.Qe2 Kf7 24.Bg2 Rd8=)} 23. Nf2 Na4 24. Nd3 Ke7 {∓ , in the presence of opposite-coloured bishops, Black still has attacking chances with ...[Rc8] and ...[Na4].}) *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Ivanchuk vs. Kramnik #3"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "5k1r/1bq3p1/pn2pb1p/1p3p1Q/5P2/6P1/PPP2N1P/2KR1B1R w - - 0 22"]
[PlyCount "12"]
[GameId "2130463735069852"]

22. Bd3 ({The main alternative is} 22. Rg1 $2 Na4 $1 23. Nd3 Be4 24. Rg2 Nxb2 $1 25. Nxb2 Qc3 26. Nd3 Ke7 $1 {(26...Qa1+? 27.Kd2 Qc3+ 28.Ke2 ∞)} 27. Ne5 Bxe5 28. fxe5 Rc8 29. Bd3 Bxg2 {-+ .}) {Continuation of the previous variation and the game: Ivanchuk defends tooth and nail. How do you maintain the pressure on him?} 22... Na4 23. Rhe1 (23. b3 Bb2+ 24. Kb1 {(24.Kd2 Qa5+ 25.Ke2 Nc3+ 26.Ke1 Nxd1+ 27.Kxd1 Bxh1 28.Nxh1 Qxa2 -+)} Bd4 {-+ .}) 23... Bxb2+ 24. Kb1 (24. Kd2 Qb6 $1 {(24...Qa5+ 25.Ke2 Bg2 ∓)} 25. Nh3 Bc3+ 26. Ke2 Nb2 {-+ .}) 24... Bd5 $1 {A fourth black piece enters the attack. But where are White's defensive pieces?} 25. Bxb5 (25. Bxf5 Bxa2+ $1 26. Kxa2 Qc4+ 27. Kb1 Nc3+ 28. Kxb2 Qb4+ 29. Kc1 Na2# {is nice!}) 25... Bxa2+ $1 ({The most accurate, as bad would be} 25... Nc3+ $2 26. Kxb2 Nxd1+ {(26...Nxb5? 27.Re3 Qc5 28.Rdd3 ⩲)} 27. Nxd1 axb5 28. Re5 $1 {(28.Nc3? Qa5 29.Re3 Bc4 30.a3 b4! 31.axb4 Qxb4+ 32.Kc1 Ke7 -+)} b4 29. Ne3 {∞ .}) 26. Kxa2 axb5 27. Kb1 ({There is no sound alternative:} 27. Rxe6 $2 Qc4+ 28. Kb1 Nc3+ 29. Kxb2 Qb4+ 30. Kc1 Na2# {.}) 27... Qe7 $19 (27... Qe7 {This is a clear win:} 28. Re3 Nc3+ 29. Rxc3 Bxc3 30. Rd3 Qb4+ 31. Kc1 Ke7 {-+ .}) ({Kramnik played} 27... Qa5 $2 28. Nd3 $2 {and White missed the best defence, namely (28.c3! Nxc3+ 29.Kxb2 Na4+ 30.Ka2 Qb4 31.Rd8+ Ke7 32.Re8+! Rxe8 33.Rxe6+ Kxe6 34.Qxe8+ ∓ , when Black would have to work hard in order to prove his advantage. )}) *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Vassily Ivanchuk – Vladimir Kramnik, Dos Hermanas 1996 (Analysis)"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B66"]
[PlyCount "62"]
[GameId "2130463735086237"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O h6 9. Be3 Be7 10. f4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. Qe3 Qc7 13. e5 dxe5 14. Bxe5 Ng4 $1 {Black sacrifices an exchange in order to obtain a strong initiative, while White also loses some tempi with his queen. — Why did Black decide on the exchange sacrifice? — Well, one of the main aspects of the position in question is that there will probably be opposite flank attacks, in which as we have already explained every piece should be counted as a potential attacking unit. With this in mind, Kramnik evaluated probably not over the board but at home that his attacking possibilities are greater and that his minor pieces would prove stronger than White's rooks.} 15. Qf3 ({White must accept the offer, as otherwise, he would have to say goodbye to any opening advantage:} 15. Bxc7 Nxe3 16. Rd3 Nc4 {(16...Nxf1 17.Rxf1 Bb7 ⩱ T. Weber – J. Werle, Oropesa del Mar 1998. )} 17. Rd4 Ra7 18. Bb8 Rb7 19. Bxc4 Rxb8 {∓ .}) 15... Nxe5 16. Qxa8 ({Forced:} 16. fxe5 $6 Bb7 {∓ .}) 16... Nd7 $1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Ge8g8,Gc8b7,Ge7c5] Editor's Note: This is what Kramnik had to foresee when he played 14...Ng4. Black wants to finish his development with ...[O-O] and ...[Bb7], winning time on White's queen, and then launch an attack against White's king.} (16... Nc6 $2 17. Nxb5 $1 axb5 {(17...Qxf4+ 18.Kb1 O-O 19.Qxc6 axb5 20.Qxb5 +-)} 18. Bxb5 O-O 19. Qxc6 {+- .}) 17. g3 $2 {A dubious move.} ({Also not good enough was} 17. Qf3 $6 Bb7 18. Qg3 b4 19. Ne2 {(19.Na4 O-O ∓)} O-O 20. f5 e5 21. Qd3 Nc5 {(21...Rc8 22.Ng3 Nf6 23.Be2 Bxg2 -+ D. Gross – M. Borriss, Germany 1996. )} 22. Qc4 Rd8 23. h4 Rxd1+ 24. Kxd1 Qd8+ 25. Kc1 Ne4 26. Qd3 Qb6 27. Qf3 Qa5 {0-1 S. Mozaliov – S. Kiselev, Moscow 1996,}) ({but White had to play} 17. f5 Nb6 18. Qf3 exf5 19. Qg3 $1 {(19.Bd3 g6 ∓)} Qxg3 20. hxg3 Bb7 {⩱ .}) 17... Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] Editor's Note: An important move, making sure Black gets to play ...[Bb7].} (17... O-O {?} 18. Bg2 {⩱ and White gains the control over the [h1]-[a8] diagonal, when Black's compensation shouldn't be strong.}) 18. Qf3 Bb7 19. Ne4 {[%cal Gf4f5]} f5 $1 {Editor's Note: White was preparing to play [f5], aiming to establish strong control over the light squares and significantly limiting Black's ability to capitalize on the pin along the long diagonal.} 20. Qh5+ (20. Bd3 $6 O-O 21. Qe2 fxe4 22. Bxe4 Bc8 {-+ .}) 20... Kf8 21. Nf2 (21. Bg2 fxe4 22. Rhe1 Qc4 {-+ .}) 21... Bf6 $1 {Editor's Note: Kramnik shows his exceptional understanding of the game. The [b7]-bishop is stronger than the [h1]-rook. Black can create an attack against the white king with ...[Na4], ...[Ke7] and ...[Rc8]. Maybe it will still be possible to win the exchange back later.} ({A much better try than} 21... Bc5 $2 22. Nh3 Bxh1 23. Ng5 hxg5 {(23...g6? 24.Qxg6 Bd5 25.Rxd5 +-)} 24. Qxh8+ Kf7 25. Qh5+) ({Editor's Note:} 21... Bxh1 {is also possible. After} 22. Nxh1 Bf6 $5 {(22...Nd5? 23.Qe2 Kf7 24.Bg2 Rd8=)} 23. Nf2 Na4 24. Nd3 Ke7 {∓ , in the presence of opposite-coloured bishops, Black still has attacking chances with ...[Rc8] and ...[Na4].}) 22. Bd3 ({The main alternative is} 22. Rg1 $2 Na4 $1 23. Nd3 Be4 24. Rg2 Nxb2 $1 25. Nxb2 Qc3 26. Nd3 Ke7 $1 {(26...Qa1+? 27.Kd2 Qc3+ 28.Ke2 ∞)} 27. Ne5 Bxe5 28. fxe5 Rc8 29. Bd3 Bxg2 {-+ .}) 22... Na4 23. Rhe1 (23. b3 Bb2+ 24. Kb1 {(24.Kd2 Qa5+ 25.Ke2 Nc3+ 26.Ke1 Nxd1+ 27.Kxd1 Bxh1 28.Nxh1 Qxa2 -+)} Bd4 {-+ .}) 23... Bxb2+ 24. Kb1 (24. Kd2 Qb6 $1 {(24...Qa5+ 25.Ke2 Bg2 ∓)} 25. Nh3 Bc3+ 26. Ke2 Nb2 {-+ .}) 24... Bd5 $1 {A fourth black piece enters the attack. But where are White's defensive pieces?} 25. Bxb5 (25. Bxf5 Bxa2+ $1 26. Kxa2 Qc4+ 27. Kb1 Nc3+ 28. Kxb2 Qb4+ 29. Kc1 Na2# {is nice!}) 25... Bxa2+ $1 ({The most accurate, as bad would be} 25... Nc3+ $2 26. Kxb2 Nxd1+ {(26...Nxb5? 27.Re3 Qc5 28.Rdd3 ⩲)} 27. Nxd1 axb5 28. Re5 $1 {(28.Nc3? Qa5 29.Re3 Bc4 30.a3 b4! 31.axb4 Qxb4+ 32.Kc1 Ke7 -+)} b4 29. Ne3 {∞ .}) 26. Kxa2 axb5 27. Kb1 ({There is no sound alternative:} 27. Rxe6 $2 Qc4+ 28. Kb1 Nc3+ 29. Kxb2 Qb4+ 30. Kc1 Na2# {.}) 27... Qa5 $2 (27... Qe7 $1 {is a clear win:} 28. Re3 Nc3+ 29. Rxc3 Bxc3 30. Rd3 Qb4+ 31. Kc1 Ke7 {-+ .}) 28. Nd3 $2 ({White missed the best defence, namely} 28. c3 $1 Nxc3+ 29. Kxb2 Na4+ 30. Ka2 Qb4 31. Rd8+ Ke7 32. Re8+ $1 Rxe8 33. Rxe6+ Kxe6 34. Qxe8+ {∓ , when Black would have to work hard in order to prove his advantage.}) 28... Ba3 ({Also good is} 28... Bd4 29. Rxe6 Nc3+ 30. Kc1 g6 $1 31. Qf3 {(31.Qxg6 Qa1+ 32.Kd2 Qxd1)} Na2+ 32. Kb1 Nb4 33. Kc1 Bc3 {-+ .}) 29. Ka2 ({Spectacular mates follow after} 29. Rxe6 Nc3+ 30. Ka1 Bc1# {, or 29.c3 Qxc3 30.Qe2 Qb3+ 31.Ka1 Nc3 32.Rb1 Qa4 -+ .}) 29... Nc3+ 30. Kb3 Nd5 (30... Ne4 31. Rxe4 fxe4 {-+ .}) 31. Ka2 ({Or} 31. Rxe6 Qa4+ 32. Ka2 Nc3+ 33. Ka1 Bc1# {. The coordination of Black's queen, bishop and knight is amazing, as we have already noticed in a lot of variations.}) 31... Bb4+ (31... Bb4+ {There is no way to prevent mate after} 32. Kb1 Bc3 {, so White resigned.}) 0-1

