1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. a4 e6 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 dxc4 8. e3 b5 9. axb5 cxb5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nxb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Bb4+ 13. Ke2 Bb7 {Black has sacrificed the exchange, in return for better development, a weak white king and the bishop pair. Yes, White has the open a-file, but he can't do anything on it...} 14. Ra1 (14. Ra7 {is the alternative rook move:} Bd5 15. Ne1 Nc6 16. Ra6 Qc8 17. Rb6 c3 18. bxc3 Bxc3 19. f3 b4 20. Kf2 Qc7 21. Rb5 Qa7 22. Nd3 Rg8 23. Be2 Ke7 24. Nc5 Qa2 25. Qb1 Rxg2+ 26. Kxg2 Qxe2+ {0-1 A. Verzhansky – R. Popov, Novosibirsk 2006.}) 14... f5 ({Things can go wrong rapidly:} 14... Nd7 {Editor's Note: This move is inaccurate because Black loses the option of playing ...[Nc6].} 15. g3 $2 {Editor's Note: The engine wants to defend the light squares with [Ne1] and [Rg1]. Only after those moves, White can look to play [g3] and [Bg2].} Be4 $1 16. Qc1 Nc5 $1 {0-1 K. Allen – R. Williamson, Port Erin 2009.}) *

