20. Ra2 $2 {Losing an important tempo.} ({After} 20. g3 $1 Qb6 21. Ra2 Ke7 22. Bg2 Qb7 23. Qe2 {⩲ , White's position is preferable.}) {How did Topalov benefit from this loss of tempo?} 20... e5 $1 {Missed by White! The text opens files and diagonals, helping the attack.} 21. fxe5 ({There is not much to be done:} 21. Nxe5 Qh4+ 22. g3 Rxg3 $1 23. hxg3 Qxh1 {-+ .}) 21... f4 $1 22. Be2 ({Or} 22. exf4 Bxf3 $1 23. gxf3 {(23.Qxf3 Qxd4+ 24.Qe3 Qd5 -+)} Bd2 $1 24. Bxc4 Qxd4+ 25. Kf1 Qxc4+ 26. Qe2 Qc1+ 27. Kf2 Qc5+ $1 28. Kf1 Ba5 {-+ .}) 22... fxe3+ 23. Kxe3 Bd5 {Simple and effective.} (23... Qd5 $6 {was played in the game. Note from Chessable: it is far better to use the bishop to stops White's passed pawns from advancing further. — Why? — It dominates the board from [d5], and, instead of exposing the queen to attacks as 23...Qd5?! did, 23...Bd5 frees Her Majesty for more dynamic duties.}) 24. Kf2 Qb6 25. Rf1 Nxd4 $19 {Black's advantage is significant, and the game is poised to conclude with a tactical fireworks display. Two sample continuations:} (25... Nxd4 {A.} 26. Nxd4 Rxg2+ 27. Ke3 Qg6 {; or, with best play,}) (25... Nxd4 {B.} 26. Kg1 Nxe2+ {a nice double check} 27. Kh1 Nf4 28. Qxd5 {the best move, according to the engine, (( 28.g3 Qe3 29.gxf4 Rg1+ 30.Rxg1 Bxf3+ 31.Qxf3 Qxf3+ ))} Nxd5 29. Ra8+ {, and despite this skewer...} Kd7 30. Rxg8 {... Black still wins by a wide margin.}) *

