[GameId "2130463735278762"]

26. Kb1 {White felt 'uncomfortable' to play his best chance with [Kb1]. How Black retains an advantage?} Qxd3+ 27. Ka1 e5 $1 28. Qa8+ (28. dxe5 Qc4 29. Qa8+ Bf8 30. Qxa5 Nc2+ 31. Kb1 Nxe3 32. Rc1 {(32.fxe3? Qe4 + -+)} Qd3+ 33. Ka2 Nc2 {-+}) 28... Bf8 $17 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gd3b3,Gg7g6,Gb4c2] The black king sneezes under draughts. Two opposing pieces attack him, and another supports them from its back rank.} 29. Rc1 $1 (29. Qxa5 $2 exd4 30. Bf4 g5 {-+}) 29... exd4 30. Bf4 Qb3 31. Qxa5 Nd3 32. Rb1 g6 $17 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gd3b4,Gb4c2] The mate threat [Nb4], [Nc2] should not be neglected by White, as well as as the d-passer.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Erdogdu vs. Gurevich #3"]
[Result "0-1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "6k1/5pp1/3bp1qp/p7/1n1P4/3NBQP1/1PK2P1P/7R w - - 0 26"]
[PlyCount "16"]
[GameId "2130463735291051"]

26. Kb3 $2 {The move 26.Kb3? was played in the game. How do you punish it?} Qxd3+ 27. Ka4 {Now it is a fight of the white king versus three of the opponent's pieces, and this is too much for a lonely king.} Qc2+ $1 28. Kb5 (28. Kxa5 Nd5 $1 29. Bf4 Qc7+ 30. Kb5 Qb7+ 31. Kc4 Nb6+ {+ -+ ; or, (28.b3 Nd5 29.Rc1 Qa2+ 30.Kb5 Qxb3+ 31.Kc6 Ba3 -+ . )}) 28... Nd5 29. Bc1 Qc8 $19 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc8b7]} (29... Qc8 {Editor's Note: An elegant retreating attacking move, whose main threat is} 30. Z0 Qb7+ 31. Kc4 Nb6+ {, winning the queen. The exercise ends here because from this point on, 'every move wins'.}) (29... a4 30. Re1 Qc7 {-+ is also curtains.}) 30. Qd1 Nb4 31. Qf3 (31. Ka4 Qc6+ 32. Ka3 Nd3+ 33. Ka2 Qd5+ 34. Ka1 Nxf2 {-+ .}) 31... Qa6+ (31... a4 32. Kxa4 Nc2 {-+ .}) 32. Ka4 Nd5 33. Qb3 Nb6+ {A brutal game and a good example of the 'attacking units' concept.} 0-1

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Alexei Shirov – Teimour Radjabov, Linares 2004"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "E97"]
[PlyCount "131"]
[GameId "2130463735295148"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Nf3 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. b4 Nh5 10. Re1 f5 11. Ng5 Nf6 12. Bf3 c6 13. Bb2 h6 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. dxe6 fxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Rxe4 d5 18. cxd5 cxd5 {Here White decided for a sound exchange sacrifice.} 19. Rxe5 $1 Bxe5 20. Bxe5 Qb6 21. Bb2 $1 {Retreating the bishop and setting up a potential queen-led battery on the long diagonal. The white bishop pair dominates the field; especially the long diagonal is a permanent danger for the black king. Black's rooks also have some open lines, but decisive long diagonal invasions can certainly be avoided for the moment. Perhaps this is just another example of White being rather relaxed about his material investment, confident in slow, long-term pressure.} Kh7 $2 ({Black has a better continuation at his disposal, namely} 21... Rad8 $1 22. Qe1 d4 $1 23. Rd1 Rf6 24. Bg4 Rf4 25. Bh3 {∞ A. Lupor – G. Schmidt, Germany 2013.}) 22. Qe2 $1 d4 {Too late...} 23. h4 Rf6 24. Re1 Qxb4 25. a3 $1 ({The text seems to be better than} 25. h5 Rd8 $2 {(25...Rxf3! 26.gxf3 Rg8 ∞)} 26. Rd1 Qb6 27. hxg6+ Kg8 28. Bg4 {± J. Amatmat – R. Stone, Caldas Novas 2011.}) 25... Qd6 26. h5 Raf8 27. Qe4 Nc6 28. hxg6+ Kg7 {Black's rooks are only defending their king... The attack should be enforced!} 29. Bc1 $1 Qe7 30. Bxh6+ $1 Kxh6 31. Qh4+ Kxg6 32. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 33. Re5 {White's idea. Being a rook down, the opponent king should be his only target!} Qxe6 ({The other option is} 33... Rxe6 34. Qh5+ Kg7 35. Rg5+ Qxg5 36. Qxg5+ Rg6 37. Qe5+ Kg8 38. Qxd4 {± M. Casella – I. Zenyuk, San Diego 2004.}) 34. Rxe6 Rxe6 35. Qg4+ Kf7 36. Qxd4 a6 {The smoke has been cleared and White has emerged with a clear plus.} 37. g4 $1 Rg8 38. f3 Rf6 39. Kf2 Re8 40. Qc4+ Kg7 41. Qxa6 Ref8 42. Qd3 c5 43. a4 Ra8 44. Qc3 Kg6 45. Qxc5 Rfa6 46. Kg3 Rxa4 47. Qd6+ Kf7 48. g5 R8a6 49. Qd7+ Kg6 50. f4 Ra1 51. Qd3+ Kg7 52. Qd4+ Kg8 53. Kg4 R1a2 54. Qd8+ Kg7 55. Qc7+ Kg8 56. f5 Ra7 57. Qd8+ Kg7 58. f6+ Kh7 59. Qd3+ Kh8 60. Kf5 Ra8 61. Qh3+ Kg8 62. Kg6 R2a7 63. Qe6+ Kf8 64. Qd6+ Kg8 65. Qd5+ Kh8 66. Qh1+ 1-0

