1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7 11. g3 Qa5 12. exf6 b4 13. Ne4 Ba6 14. Be2 O-O-O 15. O-O Qf5 16. Qc2 Nb6 17. Rad1 Qh3 18. Bh4 {Here, Black decided to make an excellent exchange sacrifice, after which his position gained several positional advantages.} Rxh4 $1 19. gxh4 Bh6 {White's pawn structure is ruined and his king feels very exposed. One should not forget about Black's bishop pair and the possibility of a knight transfer to the dangerous [f4]-square. Of course, things are not all rosy for Black: White has extra material and plenty of defensive possibilities, while in an endgame his material superiority would tell.} *

