[PlyCount "12"]
[GameId "2130463735352496"]

20. Ng3 $6 ({White should have played} 20. h5 $1 {, aiming to keep the h-file closed:} Bb7 $2 {(20...Qf5! 21.f4 Bb5= ∞)} 21. Ng3 c5 22. d5 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 $1 exd5 24. Qh7 Bf4 25. Qxf7 Kb8 26. Qg7 Qe6 27. Bg4 Qe5 28. h6 Qe8 29. h7 Qf8 30. Re1 Bh6 31. Qxf8 Rxf8 32. f7 {1-0 J. Timman – E. Torre, Wijk aan Zee 1981.}) {How to take advantage of White's suboptimal move?} 20... Qxh4 21. Qe4 $2 (21. Qh7 $1 Qxf6 22. b3 Rh8 {∞ seems to be forced for White.}) 21... Bf4 $1 22. Qg2 ({The careless} 22. Qxc6+ $2 Kb8 {-+ would only open the long diagonal towards the white king.}) 22... Bb7 23. Bf3 Kc7 $1 ({An improvement over the game, where} 23... Nd5 $6 {allowed White to put up a stubborn defence with} 24. Nh5 $1 Nxf6 25. Nxf6 Qxf6 26. Bxc6 Ba6 27. h3 {∓ .}) 24. Rfe1 Rg8 25. Re4 Qxf6 $17 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gf4d6,Gb6d5,Ga5a4] Editor's Note: Black can gradually improve his position with moves like ...[a5], ...[Bd6] and ...[Nd5]/[a4] while White is so passive position that it’s hard to find moves that don’t weaken the position further.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Grivas vs. Pinter (Analysis)"]
[Result "0-1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "2kr4/pb3p2/1np1pP2/8/1ppP1b1q/5BN1/PP3PQP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 23"]
[PlyCount "53"]
[GameId "2130463735364785"]

23... Nd5 $6 ({A stronger continuation is by} 23... Kc7 $1 24. Rfe1 Rg8 25. Re4 Qxf6 {∓ .}) 24. Rfe1 $2 ({A much stubborn defence could be found in} 24. Nh5 $1 Nxf6 25. Nxf6 Qxf6 26. Bxc6 Ba6 27. h3 {∓ .}) 24... c3 $2 {The text looks strong, but in reality, it gives White good chances to save the game.} ({After} 24... Rg8 $1 25. Re4 Qxf6 {, it will be quite hard to find a decent defence...}) 25. bxc3 bxc3 26. Ne2 $2 ({White's only move was} 26. Re2 $1 Bd2 27. Rexd2 $6 {(27.Bxd5! exd5 28.Nf1 Ba6 29.Rexd2 cxd2 30.Rxd2 Qxf6 31.Qg3 ∞)} Nf4 $1 28. Qf1 cxd2 29. Rxd2 Nh3+ 30. Kg2 $2 {(30.Kh1 Qf4 31.Qe2 Rxd4 ∓)} Ng5 $1 31. Be2 Rh8 32. Qh1 Qf4 33. Rd3 c5+ 34. f3 c4 35. Rc3 Qd2 36. Rxc4+ Kb8 37. Qc1 Nxf3 $1 38. Qxd2 Rxh2+ 39. Kf1 Nxd2+ {0-1 J. Yrjola – P. Lukacs, Helsinki 1983.}) 26... Bd2 $2 {A careless move.} ({After} 26... Rh8 $2 27. Nxf4 $1 {(27.Bxd5? Bxh2+ 28.Kf1 cxd5 ∓)} Nxf4 28. Qg3 Qxf6 29. Re4 Rh4 {∞ , White would be still in the game.}) ({But after} 26... c2 $1 {he would be busted:} 27. Rc1 Bxc1 28. Rxc1 Nb4 {-+ .}) 27. Rxd2 $2 {The series of bad moves continues!} ({White could have played} 27. Bxd5 $1 exd5 {(27...cxd5?! 28.Qg3 Qh7 29.Rxd2 cxd2 30.Qc3+ Kb8 31.Qxd2 ∞)} 28. Qg3 Qh7 $1 29. Rxd2 $1 cxd2 30. Qg4+ $1 Kb8 31. Qf4+ Ka8 32. Qxd2 Rh8 33. Qf4 Re8 {⩱ .}) 27... cxd2 $2 ({The zwischenzug} 27... Ne3 $1 {is strong:} 28. Rc2 Nxg2 29. Bxg2 Rh8 {-+ .}) 28. Rd1 {Black has won the exchange back, retaining a clear plus.} Qh7 $2 ({Again,} 28... Qxf6 {is preferable:} 29. Rxd2 Ne7 30. Ng3 Rg8 31. Rd1 Qf4 {∓ .}) 29. Be4 $1 Qh8 30. Rxd2 Rg8 (30... Qxf6 {retains the dynamic balance.}) 31. Ng3 Nf4 $6 {An overreaction!} ({Black had to accept a more or less equal position after} 31... Qxf6 32. Qf3 Qxf3 33. Bxf3 f5 34. Bxd5 cxd5 35. f4 {.}) 32. Qf1 ({White should now have continued} 32. Qf3 $1 {, where Black has to be careful: A.} Qh6 $2 33. Rc2 {(33.Bxc6 Nh3+ 34.Kg2 Qxd2? 35.Bxb7+ Kb8 36.Kxh3 +-)} Nh3+ 34. Kf1 Ng5 35. Qf4 {+-}) (32. Qf1 {B.} Nd5 $2 33. Bxd5 exd5 {Qf5+ Kb8 Qd7 +-}) (32. Qf1 {C.} Qxf6 $6 33. Kh1 $1 {, threatening 34.Bxc6 or 34.Ne2,}) (32. Qf1 {D.} Nh3+ $1 33. Kh1 Ng5 {Qc3! Nxe4 Nxe4 Qh4! Qe3 c5} 34. f3 {Bxe4 Qxe4 Qxe4 fxe4} Rd8 35. Rc2 Rxd4 36. Rc5 Kd7 {.}) 32... Qh4 $1 (32... Qh4 {Threatening} 33. Z0 Nh3+ 34. Kh1 Rxg3 $1 {.}) 33. Qe1 Rh8 34. f3 Qxf6 $1 {The position is now highly unclear...} 35. Qc1 $1 Qg5 $1 36. Qe1 $2 ({There was no point for White in} 36. Qc2 $6 Nh5 $1 37. f4 $1 Qxf4 38. Rf2 Qc7 39. Ne2 f5 40. Bf3 Nf6 {⩱ .}) ({Likewise,} 36. Bxc6 $2 {leads to immediate disaster after} Ne2+ {+ -+ .}) ({But he should opt for} 36. Qc3 $1 Nd5 37. Bxd5 exd5 38. Rb2 {∞ .}) 36... f5 $1 37. Bc2 Qf6 $6 {Both opponents are in time trouble.} ({Good for Black was} 37... Rd8 38. Ba4 Kb8 {∓ .}) 38. Qc1 $2 ({No better is} 38. Kh1 $2 c5 $1 39. Bd1 cxd4 {-+ , but White should fight by 38.Bb3! Nh3+ 39.Kf1 Ba6+ 40.Kg2 Kb8 41.Qe5+ Qxe5 42.dxe5 Nf4+ 43.Kh1 Kc7 ∓ .}) 38... Qh6 $1 39. Qe1 Nh3+ 40. Kh1 Ng5 $6 ({A bit 'scary', but clear, was} 40... c5 41. d5 Bxd5 42. Rxd5 exd5 43. Bxf5+ Kb7 44. Qe7+ Kb6 {-+ .}) 41. Bd1 $6 (41. Nxf5 $1 exf5 42. Bxf5+ Kb8 43. Re2 {gives practical chances, although Black should prevail after} Qg7 44. Re8+ Rxe8 45. Qxe8+ Kc7 46. Qe3 Qf6 {∓ .}) 41... c5 $1 {Finally, the long diagonal is opened!} 42. Kg1 ({White's last practical chance was} 42. Qf1 {, which is not enough to avoid defeat but at least offers Black a chance to go wrong. Thus} Nxf3 $2 {is insufficient due to} 43. Bxf3 Qxd2 44. Bxb7+ Kxb7 45. Qb5+ {, when White draws by perpetual check. However, if Black calmly plays 42...Bd5! , he should win, as White lacks real counterplay, and is tied to the defence of his various weaknesses.}) 42... Bxf3 43. Qe5 Bxd1 44. Qxc5+ Kd7 45. Qb5+ ({Or} 45. Qxa7+ Ke8 46. Rb2 Nf3+ 47. Kf1 Qh3+ {+ -+ .}) 45... Ke7 46. Nxf5+ exf5 47. Qb7+ Kf6 48. Qc6+ Ne6 49. d5 Rg8+ (49... Rg8+ {White resigned, as he will be mated:} 50. Rg2 {(50.Kf1 Qh3 + -+)} Qe3+ 51. Kf1 Be2+ {+ -+ .}) 0-1

