1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Rb1 O-O 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Qd3 cxd4 12. cxd4 e6 13. Rd1 Qd7 14. Bg5 f5 15. exf5 Rxf5 16. Qe3 Bd5 17. Ne5 Qb7 18. Bg4 Rf8 {Black's position looks like a stable and good one, especially due to the strong [d5]-bishop. What is the best move for White?} 19. Rb5 $1 {White's threat to sacrifice the exchange, to remove a piece critical to both his opponent's positional plans and to the defence of his key [e6] weakness is obvious enough, but turns out to just about impossible to meet in any case!} Nc6 {...Nc6 not played in the game is easily refuted:} 20. Rxd5 exd5 21. Be6+ Kh8 22. Nxg6+ hxg6 23. Qh3+ $18 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Attack on the King Concept"]
[Black "Wells vs. Ledger #2"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "rn3rk1/pq4bp/1p2p1p1/1R1bN1B1/3P2B1/4Q3/P4PPP/3R2K1 b - - 0 19"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2130463735401651"]

19... Re8 ({The alternative} 19... Nc6 {loses to} 20. Rxd5 exd5 21. Be6+ Kh8 22. Nxg6+ hxg6 23. Qh3+ Bh6 24. Bxh6 {+- as seen in the previous variation.}) {What did Peter Wells play in this position?} 20. Rxd5 $1 exd5 21. Qh3 $18 {As often happens with weaknesses, the problem with the square outlives the 'dissolution' of the pawn weakness.} h5 (21... Bxe5 22. Be6+ Rxe6 23. Qxe6+ Qf7 24. Qc8+ {+- is also deeply unpleasant.}) 22. Be6+ Kh7 23. Nxg6 ({Good enough, but} 23. f4 Bxe5 24. dxe5 Nc6 25. Bf6 {+- would be a killer.}) 23... Rxe6 (23... Kxg6 $2 24. Qf5# {.}) 24. Qxe6 Qc6 25. Re1 ({The text should be OK for the win, but White had here a nice combination:} 25. Nf8+ $1 Bxf8 {(25...Kh8 26.Qf7 Na6 27.Ne6 +-)} 26. Qf5+ Kg8 {(26...Qg6 27.Qxf8 Qxg5 28.Re1 +-)} 27. Bf6 $1 Bg7 28. Bxg7 Kxg7 29. Re1 {+- .}) 25... Qxe6 26. Rxe6 {White has emerged with a good extra pawn.} Bxd4 (26... Na6 27. Nf4 Bxd4 28. Nxd5 {+- .}) 27. Ne7 $1 Bg7 28. Nxd5 Na6 29. Re7 Rf8 $2 30. Bf6 1-0

