1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. Nf3 Qa5 8. Bd2 c4 9. a4 Nd7 10. Be2 Nb6 11. O-O Nxa4 12. Nh4 Ng6 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Re1 Bd7 15. Bf1 b5 16. Qf3 Rb8 17. Reb1 Qc7 18. Bc1 a5 19. Ba3 {Understandably, Alexander Tolush sought to prevent the future sixth World Chess Champion from castling. How did Botvinnik respond?} Rb6 $1 {Black prepares to exchange the [b6]-rook for White's darksquared bishop. " Without his good bishop, White cannot prevent the exploitation of Black's pawn superiority on the queenside. – Mikhail Botvinnik "} 20. Qg3 Qd8 21. Bd6 $6 {And White falls for it!} ({He should have waited with} 21. h3 Qh4 22. Qe3 {∞ .}) 21... Rxd6 $1 22. exd6 Bc6 {White is finally deprived of all counterplay at least for the moment and his rooks are passively moving on his first rank, unable to participate in the battle.} *

