25. Qe5 Qf6 26. Qg3 Rh4 $17 {" With this manoeuvre Black parries the transfer of the white rook to [f3] and, in addition, prepares to advance his pawn to [b4], which, in conjunction with the attack on the d-pawn, becomes decisive. – Mikhail Botvinnik "} 27. Re3 Rf4 (27... Qf4 $5 28. Rf3 Qxg3 29. Rxf7+ Kxd6 30. fxg3 Re4 {∞ .}) 28. Be2 Qh4 29. Bf3 b4 $2 {Now it seems that the black queenside pawns can roll, but this would be a misconception.} ({Black should have opted for} 29... Qxg3 30. fxg3 Rf6 {∓ .}) 30. Qxh4 $2 ({Alternatives like} 30. Bxd5 $2 exd5 31. Re7+ Kxd6 {-+ ,}) ({or} 30. Qh2 $2 Qf6 31. cxb4 axb4 32. Rb1 Qxd4 {∓ ,}) ({or, finally,} 30. cxb4 axb4 31. Rb1 Qxg3 32. fxg3 Rxd4 33. Rxb4 Kxd6 {∓ , fail to impress.}) ({But White could go for} 30. Bg4 $1 Qxg3 31. fxg3 Rxg4 {(31...Rf6? 32.cxb4 axb4 33.Rb1 ±)} 32. hxg4 Nxc3 33. Rxc3 bxc3 34. Rxa5 Kxd6 35. Kf2 {.}) 30... Rxh4 {Back to business!} 31. g3 ({White is lost after} 31. cxb4 axb4 32. Rb1 Rxd4 33. Rxb4 Rd2 34. Re2 Rd1+ 35. Kh2 Rc1 {-+ .}) 31... Rh8 $1 ({Black wisely avoided the decoy:} 31... Rxh3 $2 32. cxb4 axb4 33. Rb1 {∞ .}) 32. cxb4 axb4 33. Rb1 Rb8 {In this specific pawn structure Black's [a4]-knight is worth at least as much as a white rook. White's rooks stand miserably and wait for the end.} 34. h4 Rb7 35. Kh2 Kxd6 36. g4 Nc3 37. Ra1 (37. Rb2 f6 38. Kg3 e5 {-+ .}) 37... Nb5 $1 38. Rd1 Ra7 39. h5 g5 $1 (39... gxh5 40. gxh5 {might give White some counterplay, by [Rg1], when the passed h-pawn might be dangerous.}) 40. Kg2 Ra2 41. Be2 {The sealed move, but Tolush resigned, as more material will be lost.} 0-1

