17. Be3 $6 {There is no point for White to give up a pawn.} ({Bad is} 17. Bc7 $2 Rb7 18. Bxd6 bxc4 19. Ba3 Be6 20. Nc3 Rd7 21. Qf2 Nd4 {∓ ,}) ({or} 17. c5 $2 Rb7 $1 18. Nc1 Qf8 {∓ ,}) ({but he should opt for} 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Bf2 Be6 19. Nc3 d5 $1 20. exd5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Rd8 22. Bd3 Rxd5 23. Qe3 {, where Black would have still to prove his compensation.}) 17... bxc4 {Now Black has got a pawn and pressure along the b-file added to his compensation.} 18. Nc3 Be6 19. Be2 $6 {Too passive.} ({White should go for} 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 c3 $5 {(20...Nd4 is another option when after 21.Bxc4 Nf5 22.O-O e4= ∞ Black is active. )} 21. bxc3 Ne7 22. Bc4 Qa4 23. Qd3 Nf5 24. Bf2 e4 {∞ .}) 19... Nd4 20. O-O d5 $1 {A well-timed central break, which ensures Black at least equal play, in an unclear position.} 21. exd5 Nxd5 22. Nxd5 Bxd5 {Black has achieved an excellent, active position, as his pieces are certainly much better placed than White's. White's rooks are still 'out of play'.} 23. Rf2 ({Not} 23. f4 $2 Nxe2+ 24. Qxe2 exf4 25. Rxf4 Rxb2 {-+ .}) 23... h5 24. Rc1 Qe6 25. Bf1 h4 ({Also nice is} 25... Nf5 {.}) 26. Re1 Qc6 27. Bh6 ({White should grab his chance and become active with} 27. f4 $1 Nf5 28. fxe5 Nxe3 29. Rxe3 Bh6 30. Qd4 {(30.e6!? Qc5 31.exf7+ Bxf7 32.Re8+ Rxe8 33.Qxh6 Re4 34.Qd2=)} Bxe3 31. Qxe3 {.}) 27... Bh8 *

