29. Rd1 Be6 $2 (29... e3 $1 {should end the game quite fast:} 30. Qxe3 Nf5 31. Qd2 Bd4 {-+ .}) 30. f5 {Trying for some activity, but it is too late.} ({The other option was} 30. Bg5 Nf5 31. Qa5 Kh7 32. Rd8 Rxd8 33. Qxd8 e3 34. Re2 Qe4 {-+ .}) 30... Nxf5 31. Qf4 Re8 32. Rfd2 Qc5+ $1 33. Kh1 Be5 {Black's pieces are dominating the board.} 34. Qg5 Kh7 $1 35. Rd8 Rxd8 36. Rxd8 Qf2 ({Or} 36... Nxh6 37. Qxh4 Bxb2 {-+ .}) 37. Rd1 Nxh6 (37... Bd4 $1 38. Bxc4 Bxc4 {-+ was easier. Sooner or later, White will lose more material…}) 38. Qxe5 e3 39. Qc3 h3 40. Qe1 Ng4 $1 (40... e2 41. Rc1 exf1=Q+ 42. Qxf1 hxg2+ 43. Qxg2 Qd4 {(would have been a nice touch. Anyway, after the text move White has nothing left to play for either, so he resigned. The probably greatest player of all times was fully aware of the nice possibilities and chances offered by an exchange sacrifice.)}) 0-1

