1. Nf3 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 d6 4. Nc3 e5 5. e4 Nc6 6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Nd4 a6 8. Be2 c5 9. Nc2 Be6 10. Nd5 Bxd5 11. exd5 Ne7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rb1 Nf5 14. b4 cxb4 15. Rxb4 Qc7 16. Bb2 Rfe8 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Nd7 19. Be3 {It seems that Black has gained a quite comfortable position out of the opening. His pieces are nicely placed and he has gained the outpost [c5]-square for his knight. White has the bishop pair but here it is not a strong asset, as the centre is somewhat blocked and his lightsquared bishop has no real scope. But maybe he can pose some pressure on the b-file and in a certain time he could exchange his darksquared bishop for the black knight, achieving an opposite-coloured bishops’ drawish ending.} Rxe3 $1 {It seems that Petrosian didn't really like his rooks! But this exchange sacrifice is fully justified he would dominate on the dark squares and also establish an excellent knight on [c5]. Surely he will have plenty of compensation, while White has fallen into a passive position without any concrete plan or counterplay.} 20. fxe3 Nc5 {So, Black has gained quite a lot of compensation factors: 1. A strong knight on [c5]. 2. Weak pawns on [e3] & [c4]. 3. Full domination on the dark squares. 4. Absence of a real white plan. But of course, he is not winning!} *

