1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 d6 4. Nc3 g6 5. e4 Bg7 6. f4 O-O 7. Nf3 e6 8. Be2 exd5 9. cxd5 Re8 10. e5 dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4 12. Bg5 Qb6 13. O-O Bf5 14. d6 Nxe5 15. Nd5 Qxb2 16. Rc1 {A wild, theoretical position of the 'King's Indian Defence – Four Pawns Attack Variation'. In such tactical positions, knowledge of various tactical mechanisms are rather important.} Nbc6 ({Worse is} 16... Nbd7 $6 17. Nc7 Qxa2 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Bc4 {⩲ K. Kluss – H. Schaffer, Germany 2015.}) 17. Nc7 ({White, more or less, has to go for the exchange, as alternatives weren't proven satisfactory:} 17. Kh1 Ng4 18. Nd2 Qe5 19. Bxg4 Qxd5 20. Bxf5 gxf5 21. Nc4 Nd4 22. a4 Re2 23. Ne3 Qe4 24. Rc3 h6 25. Bf4 Rd8 26. Rd3 Ra2 {0-1 D. Dumitrache – M. Marin, Bucharest 1993,}) ({and} 17. Ne7+ Nxe7 18. dxe7 h6 19. Bf4 Rxe7 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Bxh6 Bd4+ {0-1 T. Menyhart – R. Csolto, Hungary 2008.}) 17... h6 $1 18. Nxe8 Rxe8 {Black sacrificed an exchange for good compensation: two pawns, a solid position and active pieces.} *

