19. Bh4 $2 (19. Bf4 $1 Ng4 20. Bc4 {was the only way for White to stay in the game.}) 19... Nd4 $2 ({After} 19... Ng4 20. Bc4 Ne3 21. Qe2 Re4 {-+ , things seems clear for Black.}) 20. Nxd4 cxd4 21. Be7 $2 ({White could fight only be returning the exchange by} 21. Rxf5 $1 gxf5 22. Qc2 $1 Qxc2 23. Rxc2 Re6 {(23...d3? 24.Bxd3 Nxd3 25.d7 +-)} 24. Rc8+ Kh7 25. d7 $1 Nxd7 26. Bd3 {∞ .}) 21... d3 22. Bf3 Bf8 {The dangerous white d-pawn must be captured, as otherwise it remains a constant source of counterplay.} 23. Rc7 Bxe7 24. Rxe7 Qd4+ 25. Kh1 Rd8 26. Re1 $1 Nxf3 27. Re8+ Rxe8 28. Rxe8+ Kg7 29. gxf3 Qxd6 {After a series of forced moves, it seems that Black wins...} 30. Qa1+ $1 {Weakening the black king.} f6 (30... Qf6 $2 31. Rg8+ {is, of course, out of the question.}) 31. Qd1 $1 h5 $1 32. Qd2 h4 33. Re3 {Black's position is excellent, with three pawns for the exchange and a much safer king. These advantages should normally suffice for the win.} h3 34. Kg1 a5 35. Re1 g5 $6 ({After the correct} 35... Kf7 $1 {, Black would avoid the queen exchange, which allows White to involve his king in the fight against the black pawns.}) ({But also, after} 35... b5 36. Qe3 b4 {-+ , Black should cash the point.}) 36. Qe3 $1 Qd7 $2 {Panic!} ({Good enough was} 36... Kh6 $1 37. Qe8 d2 {(37...Qc5+ 38.Kh1 d2 39.Rd1 Kg7 -+)} 38. Qh8+ Bh7 39. Rd1 Qc5+ 40. Kf1 Qe3 {-+ .}) 37. Qe7+ Qxe7 38. Rxe7+ Kf8 39. Re1 b5 40. Kf2 b4 {Black appears to have an easy win thanks to his great material plus. However, one should not be fooled by this; with extremely accurate play White can pose a lot of problems and tricks, making full use of the great power of the rook in the endgame.} 41. Rc1 $1 Be6 $1 42. Rc5 $1 a4 $2 (42... d2 $1 {was an easy win:} 43. Ke2 a4 44. Ra5 Bxa2 45. Kxd2 {(45.Rxa4 d1=Q+ 46.Kxd1 Bb3 + -+)} a3 {-+ .}) 43. Rb5 $1 (43. Ra5 $6 {was making things easier for Black:} a3 44. Rb5 b3 45. axb3 a2 46. Ra5 Bxb3 47. Ke3 Bc4 48. Kd2 {(48.Ra7 f5 49.Kd2 g4 -+)} Ke7 49. Kc3 f5 {-+ .}) 43... Bxa2 44. Rxb4 Bb3 $2 ({Black missed his last chance. He could prevail by} 44... a3 $1 45. Ke3 {(45.Ra4 Bb3! 46.Ra8+ Kg7 47.Ke3 a2 48.Kxd3 f5 -+)} Bf7 46. Ra4 a2 47. Kxd3 f5 {-+ .}) 45. Ke3 Bc2 46. Rb7 ({Or} 46. Rb6 Kf7 47. Rb7+ Ke6 48. Rb6+ Ke5 49. Rb5+ {.}) 46... f5 $1 47. Rh7 $1 ({The alluring} 47. Rb5 Ke7 $1 {could be tricky:} 48. Ra5 $1 {(48.Rxf5? would lose instantly to 48...d2 -+ . )} Ke6 49. Kd2 {.}) 47... g4 48. fxg4 fxg4 49. Rh4 $2 {White stumbles at the last hurdle.} ({He could have achieved his aim with the following line:} 49. Kd2 $1 a3 {(49...g3 50.hxg3 a3 51.Rxh3 a2 52.Rh8+ Kg7 53.Ra8=)} 50. Ra7 g3 51. Rxa3 g2 {(51...gxh2 52.Ra1=)} 52. Ra1 Kf7 53. Ke3 Kf6 54. Kf4 $1 d2 55. Ke3 d1=Q 56. Rxd1 Bxd1 57. Kf2 {, reaching a theoretically drawn endgame. Admittedly, this was very hard to find over the board and required extensive knowledge of endgame theory and exceptional positions, such as this one.}) ({Also good was} 49. Rh8+ Kf7 50. Ra8 g3 51. hxg3 Kg6 52. Ra6+ Kg5 53. Ra8 d2 54. Kxd2 Be4 55. Rh8 Kg4 56. Rxh3 Kxh3 57. Kc3 {. Great variations, full of concrete and deep ‘endgame knowledge’.}) 49... a3 $1 50. Rh8+ (50. Rxg4 {is not of much help due to} a2 51. Rg1 Bb1 {-+ .}) 50... Kg7 51. Ra8 g3 $1 52. Rxa3 gxh2 53. Ra1 d2 $1 (53... d2 {White resigned. After} 54. Kxd2 Be4 55. Ke3 h1=Q 56. Rxh1 Bxh1 57. Kf2 Bg2 58. Kg1 Kg6 {-+ , the absence of the white [h2]-pawn denies White the theoretical draw mentioned in a previous comment.}) 0-1

