[PlyCount "38"]
[GameId "2130463735573700"]

22. c3 $2 ({In fact, White cannot accept the offer:} 22. Bxd4 $2 Rxd4 23. Nb3 Rxd3 $1 24. cxd3 Qb6+ 25. Rf2 Qxb3 26. Nf6+ gxf6 $1 27. Qxa8 Bb7 28. Qa7 Qd5 {-+ .}) ({Probably the best is} 22. Rb1 f5 $1 23. gxf5 Nxf5 24. Bf2 Rb8 {∞ .}) {How do you respond to the move played in the game?} 22... Nb3 $1 23. Nxb3 Rxd3 24. Bd4 ({White could again try to win material, but the consequences would be catastrophic:} 24. Nf6+ $2 Bxf6 25. Qxa8 Bb7 26. Qa7 {(26.Qe8? Bc6 -+)} Qc6 {-+ .}) ({No better is} 24. Nec5 Rxe3 $1 25. Rxe3 Bxc5 {.}) 24... Bb7 25. Nc1 Rxd4 $15 (25... Rxd4 {The black rook has finally managed to achieve its aim! If we examine the position after} 26. cxd4 {(in detail, we will observe that Black has obtained some very important gains as compensation for his slight material investment: he has a very solid and sound position, a better pawn structure, two strong bishops, and good attacking possibilities, particularly down the [h1]-[a8] diagonal. Moreover, White's admittedly slight initiative has been extinguished, while his pieces are badly coordinated and with no obvious targets. Overall, White's position is very difficult and the practical chances of survival are close to zero.)}) 26. cxd4 Rd8 {Black must not rush.} ({The immediate} 26... f5 $2 27. gxf5 exf5 28. Qa2+ $1 Kh8 29. Ng5 Bxg5 30. fxg5 Qc6 $2 {(30...Ng6 ∞)} 31. d5 {± would turn out to be a big mistake. But now the pawns on [a3] and [d4] are attacked, while the 27...f5 is on the cards.}) 27. Qb2 f5 $6 ({Logical, but Black could think of} 27... Ba8 28. Re3 h6 {∞ .}) 28. gxf5 exf5 29. Ng3 $6 ({Not, of course,} 29. Qa2+ $2 Bd5 {-+ ,}) ({but White should opt for} 29. Qc3 $1 Qb6 30. Ng3 Rxd4 31. Qb3+ Qxb3 32. Nxb3 Rd7 33. Nxf5 Bd8 {∞ . It is true that the open character of the position makes decisions more difficult and harder to go after the very best. But this is the nature of the beast…}) 29... Bf6 30. Re5 $2 ({No salvation was offered by either} 30. Nxf5 $2 g6 {-+ ,}) ({or} 30. Rd1 Ne6 {∓ .}) ({But he should opt for stubborn defence by} 30. Nce2 $1 Ne6 31. Rb1 Ba8 {∞ . White returns the extra material in an effort to reduce the force of Black's assault. From a practical viewpoint, this decision is interesting, but it cannot avert loss as White's weaknesses remain.}) 30... Bxe5 31. fxe5 (31. dxe5 {also loses to} Qc5+ 32. Qf2 Rd2 $1 33. Nce2 {(33.Qxc5? Rg2+ 34.Kh1 Rxg3 + -+)} Qd5 34. Rb1 h5 {-+ .}) 31... g6 $1 {Consolidation! White's weak king will soon be proven a decisive factor.} 32. Nce2 Ne6 33. Rb1 Bc6 ({Even better is} 33... Ba8 34. Qb6 Qe7 {-+ .}) 34. Qb6 Qd7 35. Qxa6 $6 ({White should have tried} 35. Rc1 Ba8 36. Qd6 Qxd6 37. exd6 Rxd6 {-+ , although it would also fail to save the game.}) 35... Qd5 36. Kf2 f4 $1 37. Nf1 Nxd4 38. Nxd4 Qxd4+ 39. Ke1 Qe4+ 40. Kf2 Qc2+ $1 {White is losing the house, so he resigned.} 0-1

