1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 cxd4 6. exd4 O-O 7. a3 Be7 8. d5 exd5 9. cxd5 Bc5 10. Nd4 d6 11. Be2 a6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Be3 Ne5 14. h3 Re8 15. b4 Bb6 16. Qb3 Bd7 17. a4 Rc8 18. Rac1 Ng6 19. Rfd1 {19.Rfe1 would have been solid, unlike the move played, 19.Rfd1 . How can Black take advantage of this mistake?} Rxe3 $1 {A beautiful resolution of the tension, by which Black shows that his superiority on the dark squares is not so latent after all.} 20. fxe3 Qe7 {Of course, we must also take stock of where Black's compensation lies: 1. The bishop pair.2. Full control of the dark squares.3. Initiative.} (20... Qe8 {is also possible, eyeing [a4] and thus preventing the defence in the game. However, White can still struggle on with} 21. Kf2 Nh4 $1 {(21...Rxc3? 22.Rxc3 Bxa4 23.Rc8! Qxc8 24.Qxa4 Nxd5 25.Bg4 Qd8 26.Qd7 ∞)} 22. Bf3 Qe5 23. Nce2 Re8 {∓ .}) 21. Na2 Re8 $19 ({Editor's Note: A significant improvement over the game, surprisingly not mentioned by GMs Grivas or Ramesh. When playing with an exchange down, it's crucial to keep your last rook on the board – it is often essential for defending the back rank. Additionally, Black's bishops are far more effective when they have two enemy rooks to target. In the game, Topalov opted for a questionable combination with} 21... Rxc1 22. Nxc1 Bxa4 $2 {, giving up most, if not all, of his advantage. Just three moves later, White was nearly winning. I believe this stems from the fundamentally mistaken 21...Rxc1? , which made his task significantly harder.}) ({Editor's Note:} 21... Rxc1 22. Nxc1 Bxa4 $2 23. Qxa4 Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 {is the starting point of the next exercise, this time viewed from White’s perspective – the first and only instance where we 'switch sides' in this course.}) *

