1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 cxd4 6. exd4 O-O 7. a3 Be7 8. d5 exd5 9. cxd5 Bc5 10. Nd4 d6 11. Be2 a6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Be3 Ne5 14. h3 Re8 15. b4 Bb6 16. Qb3 Bd7 17. a4 Rc8 18. Rac1 Ng6 19. Rfd1 Rxe3 $1 {A beautiful resolution of the tension, by which Black shows that his superiority on the dark squares is not so latent after all.} 20. fxe3 Qe7 {Of course, we must also take stock of where Black's compensation lies: 1. The bishop pair.2. Full control of the dark squares. 3. Initiative.} (20... Qe8 {is also possible, eyeing [a4] and thus preventing the defence in the game. However, White can still struggle on with} 21. Kf2 Nh4 $1 {(21...Rxc3? 22.Rxc3 Bxa4 23.Rc8! Qxc8 24.Qxa4 Nxd5 25.Bg4 Qd8 26.Qd7 ∞)} 22. Bf3 Qe5 23. Nce2 Re8 {∓ .}) 21. Na2 Rxc1 ({Editor's Note:} 21... Re8 {-+ was a significant improvement over the game, surprisingly not mentioned by GMs Grivas or Ramesh. When playing with an exchange down, it's crucial to keep your last rook on the board - it is often essential for defending the back rank. Additionally, Black's bishops are far more effective when they have two enemy rooks to target.}) ({In the game, Topalov opted for a questionable combination with} 21... Rxc1 22. Nxc1 Bxa4 $2 {, giving up most, if not all, of his advantage. Just three moves later, White was nearly winning. I believe this stems from the fundamentally mistaken 21...Rxc1, which made his task significantly harder.}) 22. Nxc1 Bxa4 $2 {The text is not the most accurate.} (22... Nh4 $1 23. Bf3 g5 {∓ seems to be quite strong!}) 23. Qxa4 Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 Ne4 $2 {Unnecessary sophistication!} ({The simple} 24... Bxd4 $1 25. b5 Ba7 26. Bf3 {(26.bxa6? Ne4 27.axb7 Nc3 28.Qc2 Nxd1 29.Qxd1 Qb6 -+)} axb5 27. Qxb5 Ne5 {⩱ would have been good for Black.}) 25. Nf5 $2 ({White could have taken advantage by Black's optimism with} 25. Qe8+ $1 Nf8 26. Ne6 $1 fxe6 27. dxe6 Nf2+ 28. Kh2 Qxe6 29. Qxe6+ Nxe6 30. Re1 {± . With the text move, White is even losing! Editor's Note: This resource, 25.Qe8+ followed by 26.Ne6, is no coincidence – Black shouldn't have exchanged his last rook on move 21!}) 25... Nf2+ 26. Kh2 Qe5+ $1 27. Ng3 (27. g3 Nxd1 {-+ .}) 27... Ne4 $1 (27... Nxd1 $2 28. Bxd1 Bf2 29. Nce2 {.}) 28. Qb3 Bf2 29. Rd3 h5 $1 ({Black can also win with the 'simple' manoeuvre} 29... Ne7 $1 30. Bg4 h5 31. Bxh5 Nxg3 32. Rxg3 Qxh5 {-+ .}) 30. Bxh5 Nxg3 31. Rxg3 Qxh5 $1 ({And not} 31... Bxg3+ $2 32. Qxg3 Qxh5 33. Qxd6 {∞ .}) 32. Rxg6 ({Forced, as the rook cannot run away, since, thematically enough, Black would then penetrate on the dark squares:} 32. Rf3 Qe5+ 33. g3 Qe1 {-+ .}) 32... Qxg6 {The smoke has cleared, and Black has emerged with a sound extra pawn and an excellent minor piece. So, everything is a matter of time now…} 33. Qf3 Bd4 34. Nd3 Qg5 35. Qe4 Qe3 $1 36. Qxe3 Bxe3 37. Kg3 g6 38. Kf3 Bd4 39. Ke2 (39. Ke4 Bc3 40. g4 Kg7 41. h4 Kh6 42. Kf4 b6 {-+ .}) 39... Kg7 40. Ne1 Kf6 41. Kd3 Bf2 42. Nf3 Kf5 43. Ke2 Ba7 {White resigned, as there is no hope anymore, not only to save the game but also to pose some kind of trap...} 0-1

