1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 O-O 7. e3 c5 8. dxc5 Nbd7 9. Rc1 Qa5 {A theoretical position, which has been played many times. It seems that Black will regain his pawn and in the meantime, White will have to complete his development and see how to play against the isolated d-pawn.} 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. Rxc3 Ne4 12. b4 Nxc3 13. Qa1 $1 (13. bxa5 $4 Nxd1 14. Kxd1 Nxc5) 13... Qa4 ({The alternative is} 13... Qc7 $2 14. Qxc3 a5 15. Bb5 axb4 16. axb4 b6 17. c6 Ba6 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 19. O-O {± .}) 14. Qxc3 {For the sacrificed exchange, White's compensation is based on: 1. A central pawn. 2. The bishop pair. 3. Weak black d-pawn. 4. Control of the dark squares. 5. Initiative.} *

