15... Nxc5 $1 {An active continuation. At the cost of a piece, Black opens files for his rooks.} ({He could have tried} 15... b6 16. c6 Nc5 {,}) ({or} 15... Re8 16. Be2 Nf8 17. Nd4 Ne6 18. Nxe6 Rxe6 19. O-O Bd7 20. Qb2 {. In both cases, White keeps ample compensation for the sacrificed exchange, but Black may fight!}) 16. Qxc5 Be6 $2 {A bad move.} ({Best was} 16... Bd7 $1 17. Be2 Rfc8 18. Qxd5 Rc1+ 19. Bd1 Qxb5 20. Qxb5 Bxb5 21. Nd4 Ba4 $1 {(21...Bd7? 22.O-O ±)} 22. Ke2 Ra1 23. Re1 Rxa3 24. Bxa4 Rxa4 25. Rb1 {⩲ ,}) ({but not} 16... Bf5 $2 17. Qc3 Rac8 18. Qa1 Bb1 19. Qxb1 Qxa3 20. Kd2 {+- .}) 17. Qc1 $1 Rfc8 18. Qa1 Qc2 19. Be2 $1 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Rc8c1,Ge2d1]} ({Things wouldn't be that clear after} 19. Nd4 Qc1+ 20. Qxc1 Rxc1+ 21. Kd2 Ra1 22. Nc2 {⩲ .}) 19... Qc1+ 20. Qxc1 Rxc1+ 21. Bd1 Ra1 22. a4 $18 {Editor's Note: Topalov easily managed to consolidate his position, with a material lead of two minor pieces for a rook, a solid position, and no weaknesses. This renders Black's rooks ineffective, as they have no attacking targets. Black's bishop is really bad too, and he has an IQP.} Rc8 23. Nd4 Rc4 $6 {A decisive mistake.} ({Black's chances to save the game, by driving White to a mistake, would increase after} 23... Rcc1 $1 24. Kd2 Rc4 25. Bd8 Ra2+ {(25...Rcxa4 26.Bxa4 Rxh1 27.b6 +-)} 26. Kd3 Ra3+ {(26...Rxf2 27.Bb3 +-)} 27. Ke2 $1 {(27.Bb3? Bf5+! (27...Rcxa4? 28.Rb1 +-) (27...Rxd4+? 28.Kxd4 Rxb3 29.Ra1 +-) 28.Nxf5 Rxb3+ 29.Ke2 Rxa4 30.Bb6 Kf8= ∞)} Bg4+ {(27...Ra2+ 28.Kf3 +-)} 28. f3 {+- .}) 24. O-O f6 ({Not helpful was} 24... Rcc1 25. Nb3 Rxd1 26. Nxa1 {+- ,}) ({or} 24... Rb1 25. Bd8 Rcc1 26. Be2 Rxf1+ 27. Bxf1 Ra1 28. Bxa5 Rxa4 29. Bc7 {+- T. Reich – A. Kabatianski, Germany 2008.}) 25. Bf4 Bf7 26. h4 {Black resigned as White's pieces are about to win more material. And Black cannot pose any threats at all... A strong opening idea, which served White at the outmost; typical of Veselin Topalov’s aggressive play, which helped him to become World Champion.} 1-0

