20. Rc4 $2 {White plans to exchange rooks, but this costs too much time.} (20. Rc7 {was called for:} Bd4 {(20...Nxa2 21.d6 ∞)} 21. Re7 Nxd5 {( Michał Krasenkow proposes 21...Bf5! 22.Rd1! Bc5 23.d6 Nxa2 when he believes that in this sharp position, Black keeps better prospects after all. ) ( The alternative 21...Nxa2 is interesting: 22.Re8+ Kg7 23.d6 Nc3 24.Kf2! Nd5 25.d7 Bxe3+ 26.Rxe3! (26.Kg3? Bxd7 (26...Bf4+? 27.Kf2 Be3+=) 27.Rxa8 Nf4 28.Bc4 b5 ∓) Bxd7 27.Rd3 Be6 28.Rd4 a2 29.Ra1 Kf6= ∞)} 22. Re8+ Kg7 23. Kh1 Nxe3 24. Rc1 Nd5 25. Rcxc8 Rxc8 26. Rxc8 Nc3 27. Rxc3 Bxc3 {. Well, of course, 'this is the computer line. Good luck finding that!' – GM Alejandro Ramírez.}) 20... Nxa2 21. Ra4 $2 {But this is the real mistake.} (21. Nc2 $1 {offers far more resistance as the a-pawn can be kept under control:} Nc3 22. Bd3 a2 23. Ra1 Kf8 24. Rc7 Nxd5 25. Rxc8+ Rxc8 26. Rxa2 {and Black has a dangerous initiative, but probably not more.}) 21... Rxa4 22. bxa4 Bd4 $1 *

