1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O {One of the most famous positions in chess history and a typical 'Catalan' one!} dxc4 7. Na3 ({Not the most usual, at least compared to} 7. Qc2 a6 {, when White can choose in-between} 8. a4 {and 8.Qxc4 .}) 7... Bxa3 {Practically forced.} ({After} 7... c5 8. Nxc4 Nc6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. a3 a5 11. Qc2 {Indjic,A-Rodriguez Portela,D Internet 2015, White scores heavily.}) 8. bxa3 {Well, this is what we call today 'modern chess'! White is a pawn down, and he has shattered his queenside pawn structure as well, but he is on the right track! The main question is if he will be able to regain his pawn without any commitments. Then, he will have the bishop pair and semi-open files to play on the queenside. The doubled a-pawns are not that bad, as they will be helpful to attack twice the black [b5]-pawn, which sooner or later Black will/can push to this square.} Bd7 ({The main alternative is} 8... b5 9. a4 a6 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Ne5 Nd5 12. e4 Nf6 13. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 14. e5 Nd5 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Be4 g6 17. Bxg6 Re7 $1 {(17...hxg6? 18.Qxg6+ Kh8 19.Rfe1 ± Krasenkow,M-Arbakov,V Moscow 1989. )} 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Bxh7+ Qxh7 20. Qe8+ Kg7 21. Qxc8 Qg8 22. Qb7 Nd7 23. axb5 N7b6 24. bxa6 Qe8 25. Rfb1 Rb8 26. Qa7 Ra8 27. Qb7 Rb8 28. Qa7 Ra8 29. Qb7 {½-½ Maliush,A-Strybuk,A Grodno 2021.}) 9. a4 ({The text is more 'complicated' than} 9. Ne5 Bc6 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Rc1 c5 $1 15. dxc5 Qb2 16. Rxc4 Qxa2 {Xiong,J-Radjabov,T Khanty-Mansiysk 2019.}) 9... Bc6 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Qc2 ({A logical follow-up, although White has tried as well} 11. Rc1 Bd5 {(11...Nbd7 12.Rxc4 Bd5 13.Rc1 Rc8 14.Qc2 c6 15.Rfd1 Qa5 16.Nd2 Bxg2 17.Nc4 Qd5 ∞ Kutynec,V-Karasek,L Pardubice 2014 )} 12. Ne5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Qd5+ 15. Kg1 Qxc6 16. Qc2 c3 {Kutynec,V-Lugovskoy,M Pardubice 2015.}) 11... Nbd7 ({A natural novelty to} 11... Bd5 12. Rfe1 Nbd7 $6 {(12...Ne4? 13.Ne5 +-) (12...a6! 13.e4 Bc6 ∞)} 13. e4 Bc6 14. Nd2 {(14.Bf1 ±)} a5 15. Nxc4 Nb6 16. Nxb6 cxb6 17. Bb2 {⩲ Cordova,E-Slade,T Saint Louis 2019.}) 12. Rac1 a6 {Black will lose his c-pawn, but he will exert pressure on White's a-pawn.} ({He could also think of} 12... Nb6 13. a5 Be4 14. Qb2 Nbd5 15. Rxc4 Rb8 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 {⩲ ,}) ({or, even better, of} 12... Bd5 13. Rfe1 a5 14. Rcd1 Nb6 15. Ne5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Nfd5 17. Nxc4 Nf4+ 18. gxf4 Qd5+ 19. e4 Qxc4 20. Rc1 {∞ .}) 13. Qxc4 Nb6 $1 14. Qc3 ({A fair alternative is} 14. Qb4 a5 15. Qb1 {∞ .}) 14... Nxa4 15. Qb3 Qd5 {White has sacrificed a pawn, which is compensated by the bishop pair and the pressure in the centre and on the queenside.} (15... Nb6 {looks more logical, when it seems that Black will hold:} 16. Rxc6 $1 bxc6 17. Ne5 Qxd4 18. Nxc6 Qg4 19. Ne7+ Kh8 20. Bxa8 Rxa8 21. Qd3 Nbd5 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Be7 Qe6 24. Bxf6 gxf6 25. Rc1 c6 26. Rc5 {∞ .}) 16. Rxc6 $1 {This exchange sacrifice is the logical follow-up for White, as his pieces will be more active and the tactics seem to favour him.} Qxc6 (16... Qxb3 $2 17. axb3 bxc6 18. bxa4 {+- is the end of the story for Black.}) 17. Ne5 $1 Qb5 18. Qc2 {Aiming for 19.Rb1.} Nd5 $2 ({The text is obviously a blunder, while} 18... Nb6 $1 {should preserve the balance:} 19. Bxb7 Nc4 20. Bxa8 Nxa3 21. Qc6 Qxe2 $1 22. Bb7 Qxa2 23. Qxc7 Rf8 24. Bxa6 Qb2 {(24...Nc2 25.Bc4 Qa4 26.Nxf7! Nd5 (26...Rxf7? 27.Bxe6 Qe8 28.Bxf7+ Qxf7 29.Qxc2 +- White is winning with the extra material. ) 27.Bxd5 exd5 28.Ne5 Nxd4 29.Qd6 Qb3 30.Kg2 ⩲ The game should be roughly balanced but White has a more compact structure. )} 25. Bd3 Qxd4 26. Rc1 {∞ .}) 19. Rb1 Qa5 {White has got the upper hand, as now the black edged pieces queen & knight are not of a help for Black.} 20. Bxd5 $2 ({Also bad was} 20. Nc4 $2 Qc3 $1 21. Qxa4 b5 {-+ ,}) ({but White could play} 20. Be4 $1 g6 {and only now} 21. Bxd5 $1 {(21.Nc4? Qc3 -+)} exd5 {(21...Qxd5 22.Qxa4 f6 23.Ng4 +-)} 22. Rxb7 {(22.Bb4 also leads to an advantage. 22...Qb6 (22...Qb5 23.Be1 +-) 23.Bc3 Qxb1+ 24.Qxb1 Nxc3 25.Qxb7 Nxe2+ 26.Kg2 Nxd4 27.Qxc7 Rf8 28.Ng4 +-)} Nc3 23. Bb4 Qxa2 24. Qxc3 Qb1+ 25. Kg2 Qe4+ 26. Nf3 {+- (. The main difference when forcing Black to move his g-pawn, are the weak dark squares around the black king mainly the [f6]-square; a rather important fact in nearly all the variations.)}) 20... exd5 $2 ({Good or bad, Black had to opt for} 20... Qxd5 21. Qxa4 f6 22. Nd3 Qxa2 23. Rb2 Qd5 24. Nf4 {⩲ .}) 21. Rxb7 {Strongly threatening 22.Bb4. Black is in trouble, as White is far more active.} ({Wrong would be the direct} 21. Bb4 $2 Qb6 22. Bc5 {(22.Qxa4? f6 23.Nd3 a5 -+) (22.Bc3 Qxb1+ 23.Qxb1 Nxc3 24.Qxb7 Nxe2+ 25.Kg2 Nxd4 26.Qxd5 Ne6=)} Qa5 {.}) 21... c5 $6 {Black tries to avoid the 22.Bb4 threat, but the text loses the game.} ({A 'better' try was} 21... Nc3 22. Bb4 Qxa2 23. Qxc3 Qb1+ 24. Kg2 Qe4+ 25. Nf3 Rec8 26. Rxc7 Rxc7 27. Qxc7 Qxe2 28. Qb7 {± .}) 22. Qf5 $1 {Just take a look on the queenside black edged pieces and you can easily understand why White's attack is rather strong... There is always a good reason behind anything in chess - and in life too!} Rf8 23. Nxf7 $1 {An easy tactic to gain clearly the upper hand.} Qd8 24. dxc5 {White adds the c-passer to his pluses.} (24. Nh6+ Kh8 25. Rf7 {+- was good as well.}) 24... Qf6 {Trying to ease the pressure, but there is no really any good move left for Black...} 25. Qxf6 gxf6 26. Nh6+ Kh8 27. c6 $1 Rfc8 28. c7 {The c-pawn is ready to 'win' material; the end should be near for Black...} Nc3 29. Bb2 d4 (29... Nxe2+ {loses to} 30. Kf1 Kg7 31. Nf5+ {+- .}) 30. Nf7+ $1 ({Accurate and better than} 30. e3 $2 Nd5 31. Bxd4 Kg7 32. Nf5+ Kg6 33. e4 Rxc7 34. Rb3 {± .}) 30... Kg7 31. Nd6 {White wins the exchange back and still retains his assets.} Kg6 32. Kf1 ({White had an alternative win by} 32. Nxc8 Rxc8 33. e3 Nd5 34. Bxd4 Rxc7 35. Rxc7 Nxc7 36. Kf1 {+- .}) 32... Nb5 33. Nxc8 Rxc8 34. a4 $1 Nxc7 ({Or} 34... Rxc7 35. Rxc7 Nxc7 36. Bxd4 {+- .}) 35. Bxd4 Ne6 36. Be3 {Black decided to throw the towel in, as two pawns deficit is quite a lot...} 1-0

