[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Open File Concept"]
[Black "Alexey Selezniev – Alexander Alekhine, Triberg 1921 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A47"]
[PlyCount "44"]
[GameId "2130463735844053"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 b6 3. g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 d6 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Bf4 h6 7. Nc3 c5 8. d5 b5 9. Ne1 a6 10. a4 b4 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 g6 13. c4 bxc3 14. bxc3 Bg7 15. Rb1 Rb8 16. c4 O-O 17. Qc2 a5 18. Nf3 Qc7 19. Bd2 Ba6 20. Bd3 {As a series of rook exchanges along the b-file is expected, it seems that there is not much to think about.} Rb4 $1 {Alekhine shared so many characteristics with the modern players that we must not be surprised by his offer of the exchange.} 21. Bxb4 {White is forced to accept the sacrifice as the coming ...[Rfb8] and ...[Rb2], is hard to meet otherwise.} cxb4 {Now White is an exchange up, with even pawns. But, as compensation, Black has gained important positional advantages: 1. A strong passed and protected [b4]-pawn. 2. The bishop pair. 3. An excellent [c5]-outpost for his knight. 4. Bad white pieces Bd3 and pawns a4 and c4.} 22. Nd2 Rc8 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gg7c3] Best is ...[Rc8], with ...[Nb6] or ...[Bc3], to follow.} (22... Nc5 $6 23. Nb3 $1 {A good reaction, 'forcing' Black to lose an important tempo.}) *

