22... Nc5 $6 ({Best is} 22... Rc8 {, with ...[Nb6] or ...[Bc3], to follow.}) 23. Nb3 $1 {A good reaction, 'forcing' Black to lose an important tempo.} Nd7 ({Black had missed that after} 23... Nxa4 {((A tester noted 'in the spirit of the course, White might have met 23...Nxa4 with an exchange sacrifice of his own: 24.Qa2!? Nc3 25.Qxa5 Qxa5 26.Nxa5 Nxb1 27.Rxb1 Bc3 28.Nc6 . The position remains approximately equal, but White's side looks easier to play. The knight is annoyingly well-placed on [c6], pressuring the pawn on [e7] and preventing Black's rook from joining the queenside battle on [b8].'))} 24. Ra1 Nc5 25. Nxa5 Bxa1 26. Rxa1 Rb8 27. Bxg6 b3 28. Qb1 fxg6 29. Qxg6+ {, the game would end in a draw.}) 24. c5 $1 {Well played. White frees his bishop and his game with a slight material sacrifice. Remember: " Rooks are desperately in love with open files and targets on them! "} Bxd3 25. exd3 $1 ({White could have achieved his aim with} 25. Qxd3 Nxc5 26. Nxc5 Qxc5 27. Rfc1 Bc3 {, but the text looks nice anyway.}) 25... dxc5 26. Rfe1 ({After} 26. Qc4 Qd6 $1 27. Nxa5 Ne5 {, Black would be quite active.}) 26... Ne5 27. Re3 (27. Qxc5 $6 Nf3+ 28. Kg2 {(28.Kf1 Qxc5 29.Nxc5 Nd2+ 30.Ke2 Nxb1 31.Rxb1 Rd8 32.Nb7 Rxd5 -+)} Nxe1+ 29. Rxe1 Qxc5 30. Nxc5 Rd8 {⩱ . Such lines reinforce the impression that Black has adequate compensation and that White has to react properly in order to keep his chances alive.}) 27... Rc8 $2 ({An equal position arises after} 27... Rd8 28. Qxc5 Qxc5 29. Nxc5 Rxd5 30. Rc1 Nc6 31. Na6 Nd4 32. Rxe7 b3 33. Rc8+ Kh7 34. Rb7 b2 35. Rcb8 Nc6 36. Rxb2 Nxb8 37. Rxb8 Rxd3 38. Rb7 Rd4 39. Rxf7 Rxa4 40. Nc5 {.}) 28. Rc1 Qd7 (28... Qd8 29. Qe2 {(29.d4? Ng4 30.Re4 Nf6 31.dxc5 Nxd5! 32.Rd1 e6= ∞)} Qxd5 30. d4 {, transposes.}) 29. d4 $2 ({White missed a good chance with} 29. Qe2 $1 Qxd5 30. d4 Nd7 31. dxc5 Bc3 32. Nxa5 Nxc5 33. Rxe7 {± .}) 29... Ng4 30. Re4 $2 (30. dxc5 $2 Nxe3 31. fxe3 Qxa4 {-+ .}) (30. Ree1 $1 Qxd5 31. h3 Nxf2 $1 32. Kxf2 c4 33. Rxe7 Qd8 34. Re2 h5 {∞ .}) 30... c4 $1 ({Better than} 30... Nf6 31. Nxc5 Nxe4 32. Nxd7 Rxc2 33. Rxc2 Bxd4 {.}) 31. Nc5 (31. Nxa5 Qxd5 32. Rxg4 Qxa5 {-+ .}) 31... Qf5 $1 32. Qe2 (32. Rxe7 $6 {should lose to} Qh5 $1 33. h4 Bxd4 {-+ .}) 32... b3 $2 {Too optimistic.} ({Correct is} 32... Nxf2 $1 33. Qxf2 {(33.Rf1 Nxe4 34.Rxf5 gxf5 35.Nxe4 fxe4 -+)} Qxd5 {(, and, although Black is a rook down, his multiple threats ...[f5], ...[Rd8] will win material back with interest.) (33...Qxf2+? 34.Kxf2 f5 35.Re3 Bxd4 36.Rxc4 +-)}) 33. Rxg4 (33. Qxg4 b2 34. Rb1 Qxg4 35. Rxg4 c3 36. Nd3 Rc4 37. Nxb2 Rb4 38. Re4 cxb2 39. Kf1 Kf8 40. Ke2 {.}) 33... b2 34. Qxb2 Qxg4 35. Rxc4 h5 36. Qc2 $2 (36. h4 Rd8 37. Kg2 {.}) 36... h4 $1 {Material equality has been almost restored, but Black keeps a rather annoying attack against the white king and finally wins the game. The rest of the game is presented with light notes:} (36... Bxd4 $2 37. Kg2 Rxc5 38. Rxc5 Bxc5 39. Qxc5 {.}) 37. Qd3 Rd8 (37... h3 38. f3 Qh5 39. Qe4 Qh6 40. Rc2 {.}) 38. f3 Qh5 (38... Qh3 39. g4 Rb8 40. Ne4 Rb2 41. Rc8+ Bf8 42. Nf2 Rxf2 43. Kxf2 Qxh2+ 44. Ke3 {∞ .}) 39. Qe4 hxg3 40. hxg3 Qg5 $1 41. Kg2 Qd2+ $1 (41... Rxd5 $2 42. f4 Qh5 43. Nd3 {.}) 42. Kh3 Bf6 43. Rc2 (43. Qd3 Qxd3 44. Nxd3 Rxd5 45. Ne5 Bxe5 46. dxe5 Rxe5 {∓ .}) 43... Qh6+ $1 (43... Qxd4 44. Qxd4 Bxd4 45. Nb3 Rxd5 {∓ .}) 44. Kg2 Kg7 45. g4 (45. f4 Rh8 46. Rc1 Qh2+ 47. Kf3 Rh3 48. Qe1 Qa2 {∓ .}) 45... Rh8 46. Kf2 Rb8 47. Ke2 Rb4 48. Rd2 Qh2+ 49. Ke3 (49. Kd3 Qg1 50. Ke2 Qg2+ 51. Ke3 Qf1 {-+ .}) 49... Qg1+ 50. Ke2 Bxd4 51. Nd3 Rb1 (51... Bc3 52. Nxb4 Qg2+ 53. Kd3 Qxd2+ 54. Kc4 axb4 {-+ .}) 52. Nc1 Bc3 (52... Qf2+ 53. Kd3 Qf1+ 54. Kxd4 Rb4+ {+ -+ .}) 53. Qxb1 Qg2+ 54. Kd3 Qxd2+ 55. Kc4 Qd4+ 56. Kb3 Ba1 57. Ka3 (57. Nd3 Qxd5+ 58. Ka3 Bf6 59. Qd1 g5 60. Qe2 Qc4 61. Qd1 Qc3+ 62. Ka2 e6 {-+ .}) 57... Qc5+ 58. Ka2 Bf6 59. g5 Qxd5+ 60. Nb3 Qxg5 61. Qe1 Qg2+ 62. Qd2 Qxf3 63. Qxa5 g5 64. Qe1 Qc3 65. Qxc3 Bxc3 66. a5 Bxa5 $1 67. Nxa5 g4 68. Nc4 g3 69. Nd2 Kg6 70. Kb2 Kf5 71. Nf3 Kf4 72. Ng1 Ke3 73. Kc2 Kf2 74. Nh3+ Kf1 0-1

