[GameId "2130463735893207"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Bxc6 bxc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. d4 Nd7 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. O-O Bd6 10. Ne2 O-O 11. Ng3 Rb8 12. b3 Re8 13. Be3 g6 14. c3 a5 15. Qc2 Qe7 16. Rfd1 Nc5 17. Ne1 Ne6 18. Nd3 Nf4 19. f3 Ba6 20. c4 c5 21. Qd2 Nxd3 22. Qxd3 Red8 23. Ne2 c6 24. Nc3 Bc7 25. Qc2 {Black has the bishop pair, which is not something to make him happy here. His bishops have no prospects and he is full of weak doubled & isolated queenside pawns. White simply ‘threats’ to exchange all four rooks and then harvest the black queenside pawns by means of [Qf2] and [Na4].} Rd4 $1 {The position requires radical decisions and the text is an active exchange sacrifice. Otherwise, it is difficult to survive with his weak queenside pawns in a simplified position. If White accepts the sacrifice, the closed nature of the position will not be appealing to his rooks, while the black bishop pair can help to organise an initiative on the kingside and the white king.} 26. Ne2 ({In such positions, it is nearly always better to retain a knight than a bishop, as the knight can offer blockading opportunities against the opponent's future passed pawn and cooperates harmoniously with the rest of its army. Thus, White had to go for} 26. Bxd4 cxd4 27. Na4 c5 28. Nb2 Bb7 29. Nd3 f5 30. Re1 Rf8 {, with an unclear game.}) {Note from a tester: 'The computer evaluates White's position as having a large, even winning, advantage. Perhaps, if Stockfish played itself, White would win. From a practical standpoint, however, a human might hesitate to open the position with queenside pawn breaks, fearing the bishops could become much stronger than they currently are. Given that Black was already in serious trouble before 25...Rd4 and had no active play without the exchange sacrifice, achieving a practically unclear position is a significant improvement for Black.'} 26... Bc8 27. Nxd4 $6 cxd4 28. Bf2 $2 {A passive move.} ({Rooks need open files, so White should have tried to be active with} 28. Bd2 $1 {, planning to open files with an eventual b4:} c5 29. a3 f5 30. Rdb1 Kh8 {(30...f4 31.b4! axb4 32.axb4 cxb4 33.Qb3 ∞)} 31. Rb2 {, retaining his own share of success in an unclear position.}) 28... c5 {Black's compensation for the exchange sacrifice lies in: 1. Passed and protected d-pawn. 2. The bishop pair. 3. Lack of open files for the white rooks. 4. Possibilities of attack against the white king.} 29. Rf1 f5 $1 30. Bg3 Bd7 31. Rad1 $6 ({White's last chance to fight could be found in} 31. exf5 gxf5 32. Rfe1 Qf6 33. Rad1 {. Although his position seems to be rather passive, it is not easy for Black to release the force of his pawn phalanx successfully with an eventual ...[e4].}) 31... f4 $1 {Now Black's attack with ...[g5]-[g4] would be quite strong.} 32. Bf2 g5 33. g4 $6 ({Maybe White should have stayed passive, moving his king away from the battlefield with} 33. Rfe1 {and [Kf1]-[e2].}) 33... fxg3 $1 34. Bxg3 (34. hxg3 Bh3 35. Rfe1 g4 36. Rd3 Rf8 37. fxg4 Bxg4 38. Qd2 Qg7 {∓ .}) 34... Bh3 35. Rf2 h5 36. Rfd2 h4 37. Bf2 Rf8 38. Rd3 Rf4 ({Good enough was} 38... g4 39. fxg4 Bxg4 40. Kh1 Bxd1 {∓ , but Black has the luxury of not being in a hurry due to White's lack of counterplay.}) 39. Kh1 Kh7 40. Rg1 Bd8 41. Qe2 Qf7 42. Qd1 ({White cannot be saved any more:} 42. Be1 g4 $1 43. fxg4 Bxg4 44. Rxg4 {(44.Qg2 Bh5 45.h3 Bg6 -+)} Rxg4 45. Qxg4 Qf1+ 46. Qg1 Qxd3 47. Qg4 Qf1+ 48. Qg1 Qe2 {,}) ({or} 42. Be3 dxe3 43. Rxd8 Rxf3 44. Rxg5 Rf1+ 45. Rg1 Rxg1+ 46. Kxg1 Qg6+ 47. Kh1 Qxe4+ 48. Kg1 Qg6+ 49. Kh1 Bf5 {-+ .}) 42... Qh5 43. Be3 Qxf3+ (43... dxe3 44. Rxd8 Qxf3+ 45. Qxf3 Rxf3 46. Rdd1 g4 {-+ .}) 44. Qxf3 Rxf3 45. Bxg5 Rxd3 46. Bxd8 Re3 (46... Rd2 47. Bf6 Rxa2 48. Bxe5 d3 {-+ .}) 47. Bb6 (47. Bxa5 Rxe4 48. Re1 Rf4 {-+ .}) 47... Rxe4 48. Bxc5 Re2 49. Rd1 Bg4 $1 50. h3 Bxh3 51. b4 Bf5 52. Bd6 d3 53. bxa5 h3 0-1

