[White "4) The Open File Concept"]
[Black "Anatoly Karpov – Boris Gelfand, Linares 1993 (Analysis)"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "D43"]
[PlyCount "89"]
[GameId "2130463735934170"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ c6 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 Bb7 8. e4 b4 9. Na4 Nbd7 10. Bg5 Qa5 11. b3 c5 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Be2 O-O-O 14. O-O Kb8 15. d5 Nb6 16. Nxb6 Qxb6 17. Rad1 Bh6 18. Qc4 Rd6 19. dxe6 Rxe6 {A very double-edged position is on the cards. Black's pawn structure is wrecked on the kingside, but his possession of the bishop pair, the pressure on the [e4]-pawn and the activity down the g-file should offer him ample compensation.} 20. Rd5 $1 {An interesting way to go here is by offering the exchange!} Rhe8 ({After} 20... Bxd5 21. exd5 Re7 22. Rd1 {(, White's compensation will be based on: 1. Stopping Black's activity. 2. Control of the light squares. 3. Bad [h6]-bishop. 4. Passed d-pawn. 5. Wrecked black kingside pawn structure the [c4]-queen can come to the [h4]-square.)}) 21. Bd3 $1 {Please, take it!} Rd8 22. Rd1 $1 ({Unclear is} 22. Rxd8+ $6 Qxd8 23. Qc2 Bf4 $1 {.}) 22... Red6 23. Be2 $1 {Forcing Black to accept the offer finally. Note that Black was trying to avoid being an exchange up, as he understood the problems.} Bxd5 (23... Bf8 $2 24. Rxd6 Rxd6 25. Rxd6 Qxd6 26. Qxf7 Qe7 27. Qxe7 Bxe7 28. Nd2 {± .}) 24. exd5 Qb7 25. Qh4 $1 {A tactical way to protect the important [d5]-pawn.} Bf8 ({The alternatives were} 25... Rxd5 $2 26. Rxd5 Qxd5 27. Qxh6 Qd1+ 28. Bf1 {+- ,}) ({and} 25... Bg5 26. Qg3 $1 Qc7 27. Bc4 {± .}) 26. Bc4 Rxd5 $6 {Black decides to return the exchange in order to create some counterplay and temporarily win a pawn.} ({After} 26... h6 27. Qe4 Qd7 28. Nh4 {, with [Nf5] to come, he would be tied up for good, but at least he would have some extra material to compensate for his suffering.}) 27. Bxd5 Rxd5 28. Re1 $1 {But now Black has no pressure on anything, while he also no longer possesses the bishop pair. On the other hand, the disadvantage of his inferior kingside pawn structure remains.} Rd8 29. Qxf6 {The material is now equal, but only on the quantity scale and not the quality one.} Qc7 30. g3 $1 (30. Ng5 $6 {would have reduced White's advantage:} Be7 $1 31. Qf5 Qd7 $1 32. Qe5+ Bd6 33. Qe3 {⩲ .}) 30... Bd6 (30... h6 $6 31. Ne5 {+- .}) 31. Ng5 $1 Rd7 32. Re8+ ({Or} 32. Nxh7 c4 33. Qg5 Qc6 34. bxc4 Qxc4 35. Rc1 {+- .}) 32... Kb7 33. Ne4 Be7 34. Qf5 (34. Qxf7 $1 {was possible and good.}) 34... Qc6 35. Kg2 {The way White controls and uses the light squares throughout the game is impressive.} Rc7 36. Rh8 {Time for the harvest. The rest is not difficult.} Qg6 (36... c4 37. bxc4 Qxc4 38. Rxh7 {+- .}) 37. Qd5+ Qc6 38. Qxc6+ Kxc6 39. Rxh7 Kd5 40. Nd2 $1 Bf6 41. Nc4 Kd4 42. Rh6 Rc6 43. g4 Re6 44. h4 Kd5 45. g5 {And Black decided to throw the towel in, as there isn’t much to hope for…} 1-0

