1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. b3 Bb7 6. Bg2 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 a5 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Qc2 Nbd7 11. Rfe1 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Be4 13. Qb2 c6 14. Rac1 h6 15. Bf1 b5 16. Bd2 bxc4 17. bxc4 Re8 18. Red1 Qc7 19. Qa3 c5 20. dxc5 dxc5 21. Ne1 Bb7 22. f3 e5 23. e4 Nf8 24. Ng2 Ne6 25. Ne3 Nd4 26. Nd5 Qd6 27. Kg2 Nd7 28. Rb1 Reb8 29. Kf2 Bc6 30. Bc3 {White can take the [b8]-rook or the knight on [d4]. What is Black's best answer?} Rb4 $1 {A beautiful exchange sacrifice, which stops all White's ideas on the queenside.} 31. Bxb4 $2 ({White shouldn't accept the sacrifice; the accurate} 31. Bd3 {would retain a balanced position.}) 31... axb4 32. Qb2 Bxd5 ({Worthy of consideration was} 32... f5 $5 {. ( Note: if 33.exf5 Nf6 34.Nxf6+ Qxf6 , White has no good way to defend the weaknesses on [f3] and [f5]; or, ) ( if 33.Rbc1 fxe4 34.fxe4 Bxd5 , White's king's safety is compromised, to say the least. )}) 33. cxd5 (33. exd5 Nb6 {∓ was even worse for White. Note from a tester: The knight is heading to [c3] via the [a4]-square. White would almost certainly have to return the exchange, and all of the defects of his position – the bad bishop and the weak pawns on [f6] and [a2] – would remain.}) 33... Nb6 $17 {Black has full control all over the board.} 34. Rbc1 Na4 ({Again} 34... f5 {was an interesting alternative.}) 35. Qd2 Nc3 $2 {This allows White to sacrifice the exchange back, equalising the game. Here, we have one of those examples where Black's knight was more valuable than White's rook.} ({The calm} 35... Qf6 $1 36. Be2 g5 $1 {would keep a lot of pressure on White's position.}) 36. Rxc3 $1 bxc3 37. Qxc3 Rxa2+ 38. Rd2 Rxd2+ 39. Qxd2 Qb6 40. Bc4 g5 41. Kg2 1/2-1/2

