{One final example of sacrificing the exchange on semi-open files – a relatively uncommon feature – will conclude this section. It was played by a well-known advocate of the exchange sacrifice, GM Veselin Topalov.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Open File Concept"]
[Black "Veselin Topalov – Peter Svidler, Nanjing 2008 (Analysis)"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D87"]
[PlyCount "47"]
[GameId "2130463736003809"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Bd7 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. Bd3 Rfd8 13. h3 Be8 14. d5 Ne5 15. c4 e6 16. Nf4 Rab8 17. Be2 Rd6 18. Qc2 Ra6 19. Rb5 $5 {An invitation to an exchange sacrifice.} Bxb5 (19... Bf8 $1 {was played in the game, correctly declining the offer.}) 20. cxb5 Rd6 (20... Ra3 21. Bc1 {±}) 21. Qxc5 Qxc5 22. Bxc5 Rd7 23. dxe6 fxe6 24. Nxe6 {White has more than enough compensation for the exchange: 1. Two central pawns. 2. Active minor pieces. 3. Initiative.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Open File Concept"]
[Black "Topalov vs. Svidler #1"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1r2b1k1/ppq2pbp/r3p1p1/1RpPn3/2P1PN2/4B2P/P1Q1BPP1/5RK1 b - - 0 19"]
[PlyCount "8"]
[GameId "2130463736007906"]

19... Bf8 $1 {Correctly declining the offer.} ({After} 19... Bxb5 20. cxb5 Rd6 {(20...Ra3 21.Bc1 ±)} 21. Qxc5 Qxc5 22. Bxc5 Rd7 23. dxe6 fxe6 24. Nxe6 {(, as seen in a previous variation White has more than enough compensation for the exchange: 1. Two central pawns. 2. Active minor pieces. 3. Initiative. White will almost certainly swap the Knight for Black's Bishop on [g7] within the next couple of moves. In the resulting position, the imbalance of two Bishops vs. Black's Rook and Knight often favors the Bishops, particularly on an open board. Here, with the addition of White's healthy extra e- and f-pawns, only White is playing for a win.)}) 20. a4 $1 ({Unclear is} 20. Rfb1 Bxb5 21. cxb5 Rb6 {∞ , so White prepares the possibility of [a5].}) 20... Bxb5 $2 {Black could not resist the temptation!} ({Correct was} 20... Rc8 $1 21. Qa2 {⩲ .}) 21. cxb5 $1 Rd6 ({There is hardly any sense for Black to insert} 21... Rb6 22. a5 {.}) 22. Qc3 $1 ({Indeed, not} 22. Bxc5 $2 Nd7 {-+ ,}) ({or} 22. Qxc5 $6 Qxc5 23. Bxc5 Rdd8 24. Be3 {⩲ .}) 22... Bg7 ({Forced:} 22... Rdd8 23. dxe6 {± .}) 23. Qxc5 $14 (23. Qxc5 Qd8 24. Qxa7) (23. Qxc5 Qxc5 24. Bxc5 Rdd8 25. dxe6 fxe6 26. Nxe6) *

