{This is the case where the sacrificing side obtains somewhat more 'concrete' compensation. Thus, the idea is to destroy the opponent's pawn structure by doubling (weakening) the enemy pawns (usually on a semi-open file) , aiming (among other compensating factors) simply to win these weak pawns in the future. Of course, the sacrificing side is not 'satisfied' just with winning the pawns, but he also tries to find good compensation in other important positional factors, such as weak squares, bishop pair, attack on the king, etc... The first five examples present a common structural theme, coming from (more or less) the same pawn structure:} 1. Z0 *

