15... Qd6 $6 ({Bad was} 15... Qd5 $2 16. Bb3 {+- ,}) ({but Black should have played} 15... Qb6 16. Qe2 Nh5 $1 {(16...Bh6?! 17.Nxe6 Bxc1 18.Nxf8 Bxb2 19.Nd7! Nxd7 20.Bb3+ Kf8 21.Qxb2 ±)} 17. Nxe6 Bxd4 18. Nxf8 {(18.Nxd4!? Qxd4 19.Bb3+ Kh8 20.Be3 ⩲)} Rxf8 19. Bb3+ Kh8 20. Be3 Bxe3 21. Qxe3 Qxe3 22. fxe3 {⩲ .}) 16. Qe1 $1 ({Editor's Note:} 16. Qe2 $6 {was played in the game and was inaccurate because it made White vulnerable to ...[Nf4].}) ({After} 16. Qe1 Kh8 17. Nxe6 Nd5 {, White can continue to play for the initiative with} 18. Bg5 {followed by [Bb3].}) ({With the queen on e2, so after} 16. Qe2 Kh8 17. Nxe6 Nd5 {, the 'same'} 18. Bg5 {allows} Nf4 $1 {with a dead drawn position after the exchanges on f4} ({Bxf4} 18... Rf4 19. Nxf4 Qxf4)) ({. Because White plays Qxe6+ next, and therefore it doesn't matter whether the queen came from e1 or e2, I made} 16. Qe1 {the trainable move.}) 16... Nd5 17. Qxe6+ {This simple move gives White an advantage.} Qxe6 18. Nxe6 Rf6 19. Bb3 $1 {Black faces grave problems on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} *

