16. Qe2 $6 ({Editor's Note:} 16. Qe2 $6 {was played in the game and was inaccurate because it made White vulnerable to ...[Nf4].}) ({After} 16. Qe1 Kh8 17. Nxe6 Nd5 {, White can continue to play for the initiative with} 18. Bg5 {followed by [Bb3].}) ({With the queen on e2, so after} 16. Qe2 Kh8 17. Nxe6 Nd5 {, the 'same'} 18. Bg5 {allows} Nf4 $1 {with a dead drawn position after the exchanges on f4} ({Bxf4} 18... Rf4 19. Nxf4 Qxf4)) ({. Because White plays Qxe6+ next, and therefore it doesn't matter whether the queen came from e1 or e2, I made} 16. Qe1 {the trainable move.}) 16... Nd5 (16... Bh6 $6 {fails to} 17. Ne4 {(17.Nxe6 Bxc1 18.Rxc1 Rfc8 19.Re1 a5 20.a3 ±)} Nxe4 18. Bxh6 Nf6 {(18...Nxf2 19.Qe3 +-)} 19. Bxf8 Rxf8 20. Re1 {± .}) 17. Nxe6 $6 ({White can get an advantage with the simple} 17. Qxe6+ Qxe6 18. Nxe6 Rf6 19. Bb3 $1 {, as Black faces grave problems on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.}) 17... Rf6 18. Nxg7 Kxg7 19. Bg5 Rf7 20. Bb3 {Still, White can preserve the initiative and the more pleasant position add to his afore-mentioned compensation also a pawn.} Nf4 21. Qe3 e6 22. Re1 Rf5 23. Bh4 (23. Bxf4 $6 Qxf4 24. Bxe6 Qxe3 {and Black is in no danger any more.}) 23... Qc6 24. d5 $6 ({White should play the simple} 24. f3 Qc7 25. Kh1 {⩲ , with [Bg3] to come.}) 24... Nxd5 (24... exd5 $1 {is best:} 25. g4 Rf7 26. Bg5 Qc7 {(26...Raf8? 27.Qe5+ Kg8 28.Bxf4 Rxf4 29.Bxd5+ +-)} 27. Qd4+ Kg8 {∞ .}) 25. Qd4+ (25. Qxe6 Qxe6 26. Rxe6 g5 27. Bg3 {∞ is also possible, but White wanted to retain the queens on the board in order to create threats against the black king.}) 25... Kg8 26. g4 $5 Nf4 27. Re4 $1 Rf7 28. Kh2 (28. Rxf4 $2 Qc1+ 29. Kg2 Qxf4 {-+ is too naive.}) 28... Raf8 ({After} 28... Nd5 29. Rxe6 $5 Qxe6 30. Bxd5 Qd7 31. Bg5 h5 32. gxh5 gxh5 33. Bd2 $1 Re8 34. Bxf7+ Qxf7 35. Bc3 Qg6 {, a quite interesting position would arise. White is not worse, but can he prove an advantage?}) 29. Qe5 {White could also think about} (29. Bg3 Nd5 30. Qxa7 {∞ .}) 29... h6 ({Exchanging queens doesn't help Black to release the tension:} 29... Qc7 30. Qxc7 Rxc7 31. Bg5 Nd3 32. Rxe6 Kg7 33. Be3 {∞ .}) 30. Bg3 Qb6 (30... g5 31. Bxf4 Rxf4 32. Bxe6+ Kh7 33. Rxf4 Rxf4 34. Kg1 {∞ .}) 31. h4 $6 {Too optimistic.} ({White should play} 31. Kh1 {∞ , as it is important to avoid Black capturing the [f2]-pawn with check.}) 31... Kh7 $1 32. h5 $2 (32. Bc4 {∞ should have been tried.}) 32... gxh5 $1 33. Rd4 (33. Rxf4 $2 Rxf4 34. Bxf4 Qxf2+ {+ -+ ,}) ({or} 33. gxh5 $2 Rf5 {-+ .}) 33... h4 $2 {A blunder.} ({Black could emerge on top after} 33... Ng6 34. Bc2 hxg4 {∓ , but of course, with so many pieces on the board and the lethal white bishop pair operating, anything could happen.}) 34. Bxf4 $1 {Black forgot that his queen's route to the [f2]-square has been blocked!} Qc6 35. Bd1 (35. Bxe6 Rxf4 36. Rd7+ {+- was easier.}) 35... h3 36. f3 Qb6 37. Bc2+ Kg8 38. Bxh6 Qxb2 39. Qe4 $1 Rc8 40. Qg6+ Kh8 41. Rd2 (41. Bg7+ $1 Rxg7 42. Qh6+ Kg8 43. Qxe6+ {+- .}) 41... Qe5+ 42. f4 Qe3 (42... Qe3 {Black resigned:} 43. Qxf7 $1 Qxd2+ 44. Kxh3 Rc3+ 45. Kh4 Qf2+ 46. Kg5 Rc5+ 47. Kg6 {+- .}) 1-0

