{A plan can be to exploit Black's slightly passive setup, starting with a kingside infiltration, playing [Qg4] and considering a potential attack with [Nxh7] followed by [Qxg6], while remaining flexible to transition to the queenside or central play if necessary.} 1. d4 g6 2. e4 c6 3. h3 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 5. Nf3 Nh6 6. Bf4 dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nf5 8. c3 O-O 9. Bd3 Nd6 10. O-O Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Nd7 12. Re1 Nf6 13. Bc2 Be6 {The opening is nearly over and White should be satisfied as he has achieved a good space advantage, with play down the semi-open e-file. Well, on the other hand, Black doesn’t have any obvious weakness, and although he doesn’t seem to have any ‘annoyed’ plan at his disposal, his position seems to be perfectly playable.} 14. Rxe6 $1 {Note from NM ZukertortsGhost, tester: 'The real difficulty with this sort of 'good' position is that apart from the exchange sacrifice, White lacks a clear plan. A computer will suggest a plan with [Qd2], perhaps [Bh6] to follow, and then some queenside pawn moves like [a4] and [b3]. From a human point of view, this plan doesn't seem to have much of a point. But after the exchange sacrifice, White will have definite targets and clear plans. His position almost plays itself.'} fxe6 {So, here's what White has achieved as compensation for his exchange sacrifice: 1. The destruction of Black's pawn structure i.e. weakening of Black's king. 2. The bishop pair. 3. Better placed and more active pieces. 4. Potential pressure along the e-file and the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. So, there are a lot of compensative factors; of course, White is an exchange down, but the endgame is far away and there is plenty of good play before it.} 15. Ng5 (15. Qe2 $5 {is another way to proceed:} Qd7 16. Ne5 Qc8 17. Nd3 {.}) 15... Nd5 $6 (15... Qd7 {is not helpful:} 16. Qe2 Nd5 17. Bh2 Bh6 18. Nxe6 Rf7 {(18...Rxf2 19.Kxf2 Be3+ 20.Ke1 Qxe6 21.c4 Nb4 22.Bb1+–)} 19. Nc5 Qc8 20. Nd3 {,}) ({but Black should consider} 15... Qc8 16. Qe2 Nd5 17. Bg3 Bh6 18. Nxe6 Rf6 19. Nc5 {.}) 16. Bg3 $1 {[%cal Gg5e6,Gd1g4] " You need at least one minor piece in front of your king. – Ramesh RB "} ({Better than} 16. Nxe6 $6 Qc8 17. Nxf8 Nxf4 {∞ .}) *

