13... b5 $6 {How did Grischuk respond to Riazantsev's counterattack?} 14. Bb3 ({White could grab the pawn as well:} 14. Bxb5 $5 Nb4 15. Ba4 {± .}) 14... a5 15. a4 $3 ({White is in no hurry take the poor e6-pawn with} 15. Qxe6+ {as it gives up the advantage} Kh8 $1 {(( 15...Qxe6 16.Nxe6 Rfc8 17.a4! ))} 16. Nde4 Qxe6 {(( 16...Nxe4 17.Qxe4 c6 ⩲ ))} 17. Nxe6 {.}) ({Better than taking with the queen is} 15. Nxe6 Ng4 {(( 15...a4 16.Bxd5 Nxd5 17.Nxf8 Rxf8 18.Nf3 Rxf3!? 19.gxf3 Bxd4 20.Qe4 Be5 21.f4 ± ))} 16. Nxf8 Rxf8 17. Nf3 Bxd4 18. Qe4 Bxf2+ 19. Kf1 {± is also promising, but White quite rightly feels he doesn't need to allow any complications at all.}) 15... bxa4 ({If instead} 15... c6 {, then simply} 16. Ndf3 {± and [Nxe6].}) 16. Nc4 (16. Rxa4 Nb6 17. Nc4 {± was OK as well.}) 16... Qc6 17. Rxa4 $18 Ra6 {Black must stop [Nxe6].} ({The alternative was} 17... Ng4 18. Nxa5 Qd6 19. Qxe6+ Qxe6 20. Nxe6 Rxf2 21. h3 {+- .}) 18. Rxa5 (18. Nxa5 $5 Qd7 {(18...Qb6 19.Nc4 +-)} 19. c4 Nb6 20. Ra3 Rfa8 21. c5 Nbd5 22. Bc4 R6a7 23. Bb5 Qc8 24. Bd2 {± , planning [Nxe6], [b4] and [Bc6] and Black is almost paralysed. (24.Bc6 Rb8 25.Nxe6 Nb4 ∞)}) 18... Rfa8 (18... Ng4 19. Rxa6 Qxa6 20. Nxe6 Rxf2 21. Nxg7 Kxg7 22. h3 {+- ,}) ({or} 18... Rxa5 19. Nxa5 {and [Nxe6], also weren't helpful to Black's cause.}) 19. Bd2 ({Good was} 19. Rc5 $1 Qd7 20. Ne5 Qd8 21. Bc4 Rb6 {(21...Rd6 22.Nef7 +-)} 22. Nxg6 $5 hxg6 23. Nxe6 {+- .}) 19... Bh6 20. h4 $1 Bxg5 $6 {Exchanging the bishop is a positional mistake, which seriously weakens the dark squares.} ({Maybe better was} 20... Qb7 21. g3 {± .}) 21. hxg5 Nd7 22. Rxa6 $6 ({Here White had a pretty immediate win:} 22. Ba4 $1 Qxc4 23. Bxd7 Rxa5 {(23...Kf7 24.Bb5! Rxa5 25.Bxc4 Ra1 26.Bc1 Rb1 27.Kh2 Raa1 28.Qe4 Rxc1 29.Bb5 +- , with the threat [Qf3]+ and [Be8]. )} 24. Bxe6+ Kf8 {(24...Kh8 25.Qe5+ Nf6 26.Bxa5 Rxa5 27.Bxc4 Rxe5 28.dxe5 +-)} 25. Qe5 $1 {, with a mating attack.}) 22... Qxa6 $6 ({Black should try to defend with} 22... Rxa6 23. Na5 Qd6 {(23...Qb6 24.c4 Rxa5 25.Bxa5 Qxb3 26.Qxe6+ +-)} 24. Ba4 $5 {(24.c4 Nf4 25.c5 Qxd4 26.Bxf4 Nxc5 (26...Qxf4 27.Bxe6+ +-) 27.Be5 ±)} Nf8 25. Bb5 Ra8 26. Nc6 {± .}) 23. Na5 $1 {Not only planning [c4] and [Ba4] but also stops any counterplay on the a-file and enhances his threats.} c5 $6 {Desperation.} ({More resilient was} 23... Nf8 24. c4 Qb6 {(24...Nb6 25.Bc3 +-)} 25. Bd1 $1 {(25.cxd5 Rxa5 26.Bxa5 Qxb3 27.Bxc7 Qxb2 ⩲)} Nf4 26. Nb3 Nh5 27. Bc3 {± .}) ({Other tries were} 23... Qd6 24. c4 Nf4 25. c5 {+-}) ({and} 23... Qb6 24. c4 Nf8 25. Bd1 Nf4 26. Nb3 Nh5 27. Bc3 {± .}) 24. Ba4 Ra7 (24... Nf8 25. dxc5 {+-}) ({and} 24... Qd6 25. Nb7 {+- .}) 25. Bxd7 Rxd7 26. dxc5 {With the extra pawns on the queenside, combined with the weak dark squares on the [a1]-[h8] diagonal, Black's position is beyond hope.} Nc7 (26... Kf7 27. c4 Nc7 28. b4 {+- , or 28.Bc3 +- .}) 27. c4 Qa8 (27... e5 28. c6 Rd3 {(28...Rd6 29.Bc3 +-)} 29. b4 {(29.Qxe5!? Rxd2 30.Qxc7 Qa8 31.Qxe7 (planning b4) 31...Qxa5 32.c7 Qf5 33.Qd8+ +-)} Qc8 30. b5 {+- .}) 28. c6 ({Here White already has a wide and pleasant choice, for example} 28. Bc3 {+- .}) 28... Rd3 29. Bc3 Qf8 (29... Kf7 30. Qe5 Ne8 31. Qh8 {+- .}) 30. Qe5 $1 Rd1+ 31. Kh2 (31. Kh2 {Black resigned, as} Na6 32. Qh8+ Kf7 33. Qxh7+ Ke8 34. Qxg6+ Qf7 {(34...Kd8 35.Be5 +-)} 35. Qxf7+ Kxf7 36. b4 {+- was too much for him.}) 1-0

