[PlyCount "69"]
[GameId "2130463736143088"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h3 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nd7 7. Bc4 Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Bf5 11. Ne5 Be4 12. Bg5 Bd5 13. Bd3 Be6 14. c3 Nd7 15. Nf3 Re8 {This is already a well-known position...} 16. Rxe6 $1 {As you have already understood, this is not a real sacrifice, but mainly a matter of chess culture...} fxe6 17. Qe2 (17. Bc4 Nf8 18. Qe2 Qa5 19. Qe3 {∞ was also strong.}) 17... e5 {Black should try to be active and this justifies this concept.} 18. Bc4+ Kh8 19. dxe5 $18 {Now White has won a pawn for the exchange. Adding to that, the bishop pair and the initiative, and you can easily understand why his position is preferable.} Qc7 20. Bf7 $6 (20. Re1 e6 21. h4 $1 {looks great.}) 20... Rf8 ({The 'defender' should always think about returning the extra material to ease his position. Here, Black should have tried} 20... Nxe5 {. White still stands better after} 21. Bxe8 Rxe8 22. Rd1 Nxf3+ 23. Qxf3 {, but Black would have more chances to survive.}) 21. e6 $1 Nf6 (21... Ne5 {doesn't solve Black's problems:} 22. Nxe5 Bxe5 {(22...Qxe5? 23.Qxe5 Bxe5 24.Bxe7 +-)} 23. Qe3 {± .}) 22. Qc4 $1 {The queen is transferred to the kingside, ready to launch an attack! In the meantime, the black rooks are staring from their back rank...} Qa5 23. Re1 Qd5 24. Qh4 {Threatening [Bxg6] or [Ne5], winning.} Rxf7 {Too late...} 25. Ne5 $1 (25. exf7 Qxf7 26. Qb4 {was winning as well, but the text move is stronger.}) 25... Nh5 ({What else? If} 25... Rff8 26. Nxg6+ Kg8 27. Nxe7+ {.}) 26. Nxf7+ Kg8 27. Bxe7 {White has 'won' the exchange back and remains with two extra pawns. The rest is easy...} Re8 28. Nd6 (28. Qb4 $1 b5 29. Qd6 {seemed much easier.}) 28... Bf6 $1 29. Bxf6 Qxd6 30. Bg5 (30. Bd4 c5 31. Be3 Rxe6 32. Qc4 {+- .}) 30... Rxe6 31. Qc4 Ng7 32. Qb3 Kf8 33. Rd1 $1 Qe5 34. Bh6 Rd6 35. Rxd6 (35. Rxd6 {Black resigned due to} Qxd6 36. Qxb7 {+- .}) 1-0

