[PlyCount "10"]
[GameId "2130463736167666"]

19... e5 {How should White now continue his attack? Obviously, he needs a break on the kingside, so the next move comes naturally...} 20. h4 $1 exd4 21. h5 gxh5 $2 {Hard to criticise, but allowing the white queen in spells danger, especially against M.Tal.} ({Instead, after} 21... dxc3 $2 22. hxg6 hxg6 {(22...Qb6 23.Nf6! Bxf6 24.Qh5 +-)} 23. Qg4 {, mate is coming with [Qh4]:} e6 24. Nf6 Bxf6 25. Bxf6+ Kg8 26. Qxg6+ {+- .}) ({Thus} 21... Qb6 $1 {was the last chance to defend, but, of course, this would not be easy to work out even in a slowplay game, which this most certainly was not:} 22. Qg4 Rc7 23. Qh4 d3 {(23...dxc3 24.Nf6 +-)} 24. Rd1 gxh5 25. Rxd3 {± .}) 22. Nf6 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ge1e8,Gf6e8]} (22. Qxh5 $2 {was the game's move. Natural for a blitz game, but 22.Nf6 was winning on the spot.}) 22... Nf7 23. Nxe8 Rxe8 24. Bxf7 $18 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) The Doubled Pawns Concept"]
[Black "Tal vs. Karpov (Analysis)"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "2rnr2k/ppq1p1bp/8/6Bp/3pN3/1BP5/P3QPP1/4R1K1 w - - 0 22"]
[PlyCount "17"]
[GameId "2130463736184051"]

22. Qxh5 $2 ({Natural for a blitz game, but} 22. Nf6 $1 {was winning on the spot:} Nf7 23. Nxe8 Rxe8 24. Bxf7 {+- .}) 22... Rf8 23. Bc2 {Changing direction to hit the new target on [h7]. This is surprisingly hard to defend.} Qe5 24. Ng3 $1 {A fantastic idea, sacrificing the other rook as well with check!.} ({The alternative was} 24. Nf6 {, but after} Qxe1+ 25. Kh2 Bh6 $1 {(25...h6? 26.Qg6 +-)} 26. Qxh6 Rf7 {, White doesn't have more than a draw:} 27. Bxh7 {(27.Nxh7? Qe5+ 28.f4 Qg7 29.Qh5 Qxh7! 30.Bxh7 Rxh7 31.Bh6 Nf7 32.Kg1 Nxh6 -+)} exf6 28. Bxf6+ Rxf6 29. Qxf6+ {(29.Bg6+? Kg8 30.Qh7+ Kf8 -+)} Kxh7 {.}) 24... Qxe1+ 25. Kh2 h6 $2 ({How to parry the attack? Amazingly, there was a saving continuation for Black, but it was so hard to find it:} 25... Bh6 $1 26. Bxh6 Rf7 27. Bxh7 Rc6 $1 {and despite the apparent danger, amazingly Black is just about OK here. (27...Rc5? 28.Bg7+! Rxg7 29.Bf5+ Kg8 30.Qe8) Indeed, after} 28. Bc2 Rxh6 29. Qxh6+ Kg8 30. Qg6+ Kf8 {, there is nothing better than a draw by repetition:} 31. Qh6+ Kg8 {(31...Ke8 32.Ba4+ Nc6 33.Bxc6+ bxc6 34.Qxc6+ Kf8 35.Qc8+ Kg7 36.Qg4+=)} 32. Qg6+ Kf8 33. Qh6+ {.}) 26. Bxh6 Kg8 ({Of course,} 26... Bxh6 $4 27. Qxh6+ Kg8 28. Qh7# {.}) 27. Bxg7 Rxf2 ({Or} 27... Kxg7 28. Qg6+ Kh8 29. Qh7# {.}) 28. Qh7+ Kf7 29. Qg6+ Kg8 30. Bh6+ {And as mate follows, Black resigned.} 1-0

