20. Qh2 $2 {Losing a crucial tempo.} ({Obligatory is} 20. h6 g6 21. Rhf1 f6 {∞ .}) 20... Bd6 21. Qh3 Nxd3 $1 22. cxd3 (22. Rxd3 $2 dxe4 23. Rxd6 {(23.fxe4 Bxe4 -+)} Qxd6 24. h6 g6 {-+ .}) 22... b4 $19 ({Kasparov handles the position in an excellent way:} 22... Nxc3+ $2 23. Nxc3 Qxc3 24. Bb2 Qb4 25. g6 Be5 {(25...dxe4? 26.h6! Be5 27.d4 +-)} 26. d4 Bf4 27. gxf7+ Kxf7 28. Qg4 {± .}) 23. cxb4 (23. c4 dxc4 {(23...Nc3+ 24.Nxc3 bxc3 -+)} 24. h6 g6 25. dxc4 Be5 {-+ .}) 23... Rc8 24. Ka1 (24. Qf1 dxe4 25. fxe4 Qc2+ 26. Ka1 Be5+ 27. d4 Bxe4 28. Ba3 Bd5 {-+ .}) 24... dxe4 ({Not good is} 24... Qc2 $2 25. Rd2 Be5+ 26. d4 Bxd4+ 27. Rxd4 {(27.Nxd4? Qxc1+ 28.Rxc1 Rxc1)} Qxe2 28. Qf1 Qc2 {∞ ,}) ({but Black can play} 24... Bxb4 $1 25. Qh2 Qc2 26. Rde1 {(26.g6 Nc3 -+)} Bxe1 27. Rxe1 Nc5 {-+ .}) 25. fxe4 (25. dxe4 $2 Be5+ 26. Nd4 Bxd4+ 27. Rxd4 Qxc1+ 28. Rxc1 Rxc1# {.}) 25... Bxe4 $1 {Even to an untrained eye, it becomes clear that Black is achieving success in his attack much faster than his opponent.} 26. g6 (26. dxe4 Be5+ {+ -+ ,}) ({or} 26. Rhg1 Qc2 27. Nd4 Be5 28. Qe3 Bd5 {-+ .}) 26... Bxh1 27. Qxh1 Bxb4 {The smoke has been cleared, and Black has come out on the top.} 28. gxf7+ Kf8 $1 (28... Qxf7 29. Bd2 Bxd2 30. Rxd2 Nb6 {∓ .}) 29. Qg2 Rb8 $1 {Game over. Black handled the attack in a superb way.} 30. Bb2 (30. Bd2 Ba3 31. Bc1 Bxc1 32. Rxc1 Qb6 33. Nc3 Nxc3 {-+ .}) 30... Nxb2 31. Nd4 (31. Kxb2 Bd2+ 32. Ka1 Bc3+ {+ -+ .}) 31... Nxd1 $1 {The final combination is simple but aesthetically very pleasing.} 32. Nxe6+ Kxf7 (32... Kxf7 {As White saw the winning continuation after} 33. Qxg7+ {(33.Nxc7 Bc3+)} Kxe6 34. Qxc7 {(34.Qh6+ Kf5)} Bc3+ {+ -+ , he resigned.}) 0-1

