1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 Bd7 7. Qd2 Rc8 8. f4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Qa5 10. O-O-O {By castling long, the 'Chess Queen' made the strongest move, but the follow-up was not that good...} Rxc3 {A typical exchange sacrifice in the 'Sicilian Defence'. Black destroys White's pawn structure and, in general, can employ some nice attacking motifs. Of course, we must keep in mind that White has the material advantage!} 11. Qxc3 $2 {White seemed frightened to play a middlegame with her king exposed and the queens on the board.} ({But her decision was wrong:} 11. bxc3 e5 12. Qb4 $1 Qxb4 13. cxb4 Nxe4 14. Bh4 g5 15. fxg5 Be7 16. Bc4 h6 17. Rhf1 Be6 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. c4 hxg5 {∞ (K. Alekseenko – A. Suleymenov, St. Petersburg 2018. Also, what I can understand from the game is that Kosteniuk forgot her home preparation if any, going for a suspicious position…)}) 11... Qxc3 12. bxc3 Nxe4 {Now Black has added a healthy central pawn to her compensation, which now consists of: 1. A pawn. 2. Superior pawn structure. 3. Active pieces.} *

