[FEN "4kb1r/pp1bpppp/3p4/8/4nP1B/3R4/P1P3PP/2K2B1R w k - 0 15"]
[PlyCount "44"]
[GameId "2130463736245499"]

15. Be2 (15. Rb3 Nc5 16. Rb1 g6 17. Bf2 b6 {∓}) ({and} 15. Re3 Nc5 16. Bc4 e6 17. Bd5 Be7 18. Bxe7 Kxe7 {∓ , are other options for Black.}) 15... g6 ({Or} 15... e6 16. Bf3 Bc6 17. Re1 f5 {∓ T. Ashid – J. Tan, Jiaxing 2016.}) 16. Re1 Bc6 $17 {The material is arithmetically equal, but Black's pieces are much better placed than White's and can coordinate in order to help her advance her pawns. On the other hand, White's rooks are not doing much, and they are still looking for potential targets.} 17. Rb3 a6 {There is no need to allow an exchange with [Bb5].} 18. Bf3 f5 19. Bxe4 $6 {Although Black's [e4]-night was rather strong, now Black also gets the bishop pair advantage.} ({Something like} 19. g4 {, trying to open files, was a much more logical try.}) 19... fxe4 $1 ({After the light-hearted} 19... Bxe4 $2 20. Rxe4 $1 fxe4 21. Rxb7 {, White's activity is compensating her small material disadvantage.}) 20. Rh3 h5 21. Rc3 d5 {White's rook is hanging around while Black prepares an effective plan: the advance of her pawns.} 22. Bf2 Bh6 23. Be3 Rf8 (23... O-O {looks like a natural move but, as the endgame approaches, Black will need her king to be centralised.}) 24. g3 Bg7 25. Ra3 d4 26. Bd2 Rf5 $1 {Activating her last piece!} 27. Ra5 Kd7 28. Bb4 (28. Rxf5 gxf5 29. Rd1 Ke6 30. Ba5 Kd5 {-+ .}) 28... e5 $1 {The last detail. But anyway, this is a one-sided game, as White could not present a single threat throughout the game!} 29. Kb1 (29. fxe5 Ke6 30. Rd1 Bxe5 31. Rxe5+ Kxe5 32. Bc5 e3 33. Bxd4+ Ke4 {-+ .}) 29... Ke6 30. fxe5 Bxe5 31. Rd1 e3 32. Re1 Rf2 {Do you also share the feeling that the white [a5]-rook is worse than any of the black bishops?} 33. c3 Be4+ 34. Kc1 Rxh2 35. cxd4 Bxd4 36. Rg1 Rc2+ {An important game of the 38th Olympiad.} 0-1

