1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 d6 8. f3 O-O 9. Qd2 Bd7 10. h4 h5 11. O-O-O Rc8 12. Bb3 Ne5 13. Bg5 Rc5 14. Kb1 Re8 15. Rhe1 Qc8 16. Bh6 Bxh6 17. Qxh6 {How do you react to this infiltration by the opposing queen? Tip: Try to see lines that involve both sides of the board, taking into account White's attack and your attempt to counter-attack.} Rxc3 $5 {That was Black's idea – to sac the exchange on [c3]. Quite a typical sacrifice in this particular variation; Black nearly always gets some good compensation and mostly a pawn as well!.} 18. bxc3 Qxc3 19. Re3 $1 ({After} 19. Qd2 Qc5 {, Black would be ready to push his queenside pawns.}) 19... Qb4 20. c3 $2 {White thought that it is important now to create a kind of defence around his king. Otherwise the black attack will easily tell.} ({But it seems that after} 20. g4 $1 {, he would have the upper hand.}) 20... Qb6 21. Ka1 $1 {Black had to organise his defence.} (21. Re2 a5 22. Rb2 Qc5 {∞ looks very passive for White - his rook is doing nothing on [b2]...}) 21... e6 (21... Rc8 $2 {is natural but bad!}) 22. g4 a5 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) The Doubled Pawns Concept"]
[Black "Grischuk vs. Giri (Analysis)"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "4r1k1/pp1bpp2/1q1p1npQ/4n2p/3NP2P/1BP1RP2/P5P1/K2R4 b - - 0 21"]
[PlyCount "21"]
[GameId "2130463736261885"]

21... Rc8 $2 {Natural but bad!} ({Black had to organise his defence by} 21... e6 22. g4 a5 {∞ .}) 22. g4 $1 {Activity is welcomed. White cannot just stay back and defend; he is obliged to try to open files for his rooks.} hxg4 $6 ({The other capture with} 22... Bxg4 23. Rb1 $1 {(23.fxg4 Nfxg4 24.Bxf7+! (24.Qf4 Nxe3 25.Qxe3 Qc5 ∞) 24...Kxf7 25.Qh7+=)} Qa6 24. Qg5 Bd7 25. Nf5 {± is also great for White, but it should have been followed...}) 23. f4 $2 ({Opening lines for the rooks is an important feature when on the attack, so White should have gone for} 23. h5 $1 gxh5 {(23...Nxh5 24.Nf5! gxf5 25.exf5! Bxf5 26.fxg4! Bxg4 27.Bc2 f5 28.Bb3+ d5 29.Bxd5+ Nf7 30.Qg5+ Kh8 31.Bxf7 Qf6 32.Qxf6+ Nxf6 33.Rh1+ Kg7 34.Rxe7 Ne4 35.Bd5+ Kf6 36.Re6+ Kg5 37.Bxe4 fxe4 38.Rxe4 +-)} 24. f4 Nc4 25. e5 $1 {(25.Bxc4? Rxc4 26.e5 dxe5 27.Rxe5 Nh7 28.Qxh5 Rxc3 is very unclear but always near to equality... )} dxe5 26. Rxe5 $1 Nh7 27. Qxh5 Qg6 28. Qxg6+ fxg6 29. Rxe7 {+- .}) 23... Nc4 24. e5 (24. h5 Nxh5 25. f5 {should be still preferable.}) 24... Nd5 $2 {Black overdoes it!} (24... dxe5 $1 25. Bxc4 Rxc4 26. fxe5 Nd5 27. e6 Nxe3 28. exf7+ Kxf7 29. Qh7+ {is simply a draw with perpetual check.}) 25. e6 $2 ({White missed the very strong continuation} 25. h5 $1 dxe5 26. Rxe5 $1 {, which wins in all cases - the black king gets stripped of cover and comes under heavy attack.}) 25... Ndxe3 26. exd7 $6 {And he even makes it difficult...} (26. exf7+ Kxf7 27. Qh7+ {is a perpetual check draw.}) 26... Rd8 27. f5 $6 {A move that could cost the game. It is true that the position is extremely complicated, and the time available is limited this was a blitz game, by the way, so it is not easy to find the right path.} (27. Ne6 $2 {was losing to} Nf5 28. Nxd8 Nxh6 29. Nxb7 Qe3 $1 {(29...Qxb7 30.d8=Q+ Kg7 31.Bxc4 Qf3 32.Bb3 Nf5 ∞)} 30. d8=Q+ Kg7 31. Bxc4 Qxc3+ 32. Kb1 Qxc4 33. Nxd6 Qb4+ $1 {(33...exd6? 34.Qxd6 Qe4+ ∓)} 34. Kc2 Qc5+ 35. Kb3 exd6 36. Rxd6 Qe3+ 37. Rd3 Qe6+ 38. Kb2 Nf5 {-+ .}) ({But White could preserve the balance by} 27. h5 $1 d5 28. Rh1 Qa5 29. Rc1 Qa3 30. Rb1 Qa5 31. Rc1 {.}) 27... Qa5 ({Critical is} 27... d5 $1 {, when White should play with care:} 28. Re1 $1 {(28.Ne6? Nxf5 29.Nxd8 Nxh6 30.Nxb7 Qxb7 31.d8=Q+ Kg7 -+)} Qf6 29. Rxe3 Nxe3 30. fxg6 e5 31. Qxe3 exd4 32. Qe8+ Kg7 33. gxf7 g3 34. Bxd5 dxc3 35. Qg8+ Kh6 36. Kb1 Qf5+ 37. Kc1 Qf4+ 38. Kb1 g2 39. Qxg2 Qd2 40. Qg5+ Qxg5 41. hxg5+ Kxg5 42. Bxb7 Kf6 43. Bd5 Ke7 44. Kc2 {.}) 28. Rc1 Qa3 $6 {Black decided to repeat moves and accept the draw.} ({He could think of} 28... Nxf5 29. Nxf5 Qxf5 30. Bxc4 e6 {, as only he could have some chances to get the full point:} 31. Qd2 Rxd7 32. Be2 $1 Qh5 33. Rg1 Qxh4 34. Rxg4 Qh2 35. Kb2 Rc7 {⩱ .}) 29. Rb1 Qa5 30. Rc1 Qa3 $6 31. Rb1 Qa5 1/2-1/2

