1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bb5 Nd4 5. Bc4 Bc5 6. Nxe5 Qe7 7. Nf3 d5 8. Bxd5 Bg4 9. d3 O-O-O ({Note from a tester: 'Simpler is} 9... c6 {, with approximate equality, though the line gets pretty wild as White sacrifices his queen to hold the balance:} 10. Bb3 Nd7 11. Be3 Ne5 12. Nxd4 Bxd1 13. Nf5 Qf8 {, etc. But then, we would have been deprived of an exchange sacrifice!'}) 10. Be3 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 {Now Black starts a 'combination', which finally ends in a draw.} Rxd5 $1 {Good and forced, by the way!} 12. exd5 Re8 {The rest of Black's army is well placed…} 13. c3 ({After this, it's pretty much best play. Time, practice or, most likely, a good deal of computer analysis will determine whether} 13. O-O {is a viable alternative. It looks very risky, but there isn't a clear route to an advantage for Black after} Bxf3 {(13...Nxf3+!? 14.gxf3 Bh3 15.Bf4! Qe2 16.Bg3 Bxf1 17.Qxf1 f5= ∞)} 14. gxf3 Qh4 (14... Bd6 15. f4 {, as White holds:}) 15. f4 Bd6 16. Kg2 Nxc2 17. Qxc2 Qg4+ {.}) 13... Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 Qh4 $1 {All engines agree – here a draw is the right result!} *

