1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 h6 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. Nf1 Bd7 13. Ng3 a5 14. Bd2 a4 15. Bc2 Na5 16. b3 axb3 17. axb3 c6 18. Be3 Qc7 19. Nd2 c5 20. d5 b4 21. cxb4 cxb4 22. Bd3 Rec8 23. Qe2 Qb7 24. Ra2 Be7 25. Rea1 Bd8 26. Nh5 Nh7 27. Qf3 Nf8 {A rather 'innocent' position at first sight, where both players seem to have concentrated on the queenside. But this was not the case!} 28. Rxa5 $1 {An exchange sacrifice, which aims to draw the defending [d8]-bishop away from its kingside defence. Black would have no chance to defend after:} Rxa5 ({The best answer,} 28... Bxa5 {is covered in the following variation .}) 29. Rxa5 Bxa5 30. Bxh6 Bd8 31. Nxg7 $18 {[%cal Gg7h5,Gh5f6,Gg1h2,Gd2c4,Rc8c3]} ({or} 31. Bxg7 {.}) ({After} 31. Nxg7 {(: Both sides are bound to realise that White's knight is highly pesky. It should be relocated on [h5] and [f6]. The bishop pair on [h6] and [d3] dominate key diagonals. The queen on [f3] is well-placed, centralised, and ready to join any attack. White's king on [g1] is relatively safe, unlike his counterpart.) ( ➢ Despite some possible counterplay with 31...Rc3 , for instance, nothing should prevent White to win. )}) *

