1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. d4 a6 8. d5 Na5 9. Nd2 c5 10. Qc2 e5 11. b3 Ng4 12. e4 f5 13. exf5 gxf5 14. Nd1 b5 15. f3 e4 16. Bb2 exf3 17. Bxf3 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Ne5 19. Be2 f4 20. gxf4 Bh3 {The position looks quite complicated, but White's perfect placement of his queen and the edged black [a5]-knight should give him the advantage, at least at first sight. But of course, nobody can underestimate Black’s threats.} 21. Ne3 $1 ({A forced and good exchange sacrifice, as the alternative} 21. Rf2 $2 Rxf4 $1 22. Qc3 Qg5+ 23. Qg3 Qxg3+ 24. hxg3 Rd4 {∓ , cannot be satisfactory. White's compensation is based on his attack and the edged black knight, which should construct satisfying assets.}) 21... Bxf1 $2 ({Black shouldn't accept the exchange sacrifice, so he could go for} 21... Rxf4 $1 22. Rxf4 Qg5+ 23. Rg4 $1 {(23.Kh1 Qxf4 24.Rg1+ Kh8 ∞)} Nxg4 24. Nxg4 Bxg4 25. Bxg4 Qxg4+ 26. Kh1 Qd4 $1 27. Rg1+ Kh8 28. Qxd4+ cxd4 29. Rg4 bxc4 30. bxc4 Re8 31. Rxd4 Re1+ 32. Kg2 Rd1 {∞ .}) 22. Rxf1 {[%csl Ya5,Yg8,Be2][%cal Gd2e4,Ge3g2] For the exchange sacrifice, White has got: 1. A pawn. 2. Better placed pieces the [a5]-knight is awfully placed. 3. Light square control. 4. Potential attack on the black king.} *

