22... Ng6 (22... Nd7 23. Ne4 Qe7 24. Bd3 {± .}) 23. Bg4 Nxf4 (23... Rxf4 $2 24. Be6+ Kf8 25. Rxf4+ Nxf4 26. Qh8+ {+- is also bad, but Black should go for 23...Qf6! 24.Be6+ Kh8 25.Qxf6+ Rxf6 26.f5 Ne5 27.Ne4 ± .}) 24. Rxf4 $1 {The second rook, on the same file! The [f4]-knight was guarding many important squares and so had to be eliminated! The compact force of the white queen and the remaining minor pieces cannot be contained any more.} Rxf4 25. Be6+ Rf7 ({The alternative} 25... Kf8 {fails to impress:} 26. Qh8+ Ke7 27. Qxh7+ Ke8 (27... Kf6 28. Qf7+ Ke5 29. Qg7+ Qf6 30. Qg3 Qf8 31. Ng4+ Kd4 32. Qe3#) 28. Qh5+ Kf8 29. Qh6+ {.}) 26. Ne4 $18 {[%csl Rg5,Rd6][%cal Ge4g5,Ge4d6] Editor's Note: White has several threats: winning the pinned rook with Ng7; capturing the free pawn after 26...Qh4 with 27.Nxd6; and, delivering checkmate on [g7] with the queen after Nf5.} (26. Nf3 {is the other good move.}) *

