1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. b3 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Be7 7. Bg2 c6 8. Bc3 d5 9. Ne5 Nfd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. O-O Nf6 13. e4 b5 14. exd5 exd5 15. Re1 Rb8 16. c5 Bc8 17. Nf3 Ne4 {This is one of the most beautiful and impressive games I have ever seen! In my opinion, the FIDE World Champion Veselin Topalov was the world’s best player in the years 2005-2007…} 18. Rxe4 $1 {Note an interesting tendency: all the noisy novelties lately are somehow connected with exchange sacrifices; maybe we should re-evaluate the relative strengths of knight/bishop and rook?} dxe4 19. Ne5 {White's idea is very logical: the pawn on [d5] was a key defender of the [h1]-[a8] diagonal, and now all of Black's queenside is compromised, along with the centre, of course.} Qd5 $1 ({No help is provided by a passive defence like} 19... Qc7 20. Bxe4 b4 21. Bd2 Bd7 {(21...Bxc5 22.Nxc6 ± , or 21...f5 22.Bg2 Bb7 23.Qe2 Bf6 24.Qc4+ Kh8 25.Bf4 ± . )} 22. Bf4 Qb7 23. Qd3 {± . It's hard to see why the [b8]-rook should be stronger than the [e5]-knight, but even if one manages to see the 'why', White can win the exchange back with [Nxd7].}) 20. Qe1 $1 (20. Qc2 $2 f5 21. f3 $2 Bxc5 $1 22. dxc5 Qxc5+ 23. Kh1 b4 {-+ .}) 20... Bf5 $1 (20... f5 $2 21. f3 $1 Bxc5 22. dxc5 Qxc5+ 23. Kh1 Re8 24. b4 {± was seen in the game A. Onischuk – W. Browne, Stillwater 2007.}) 21. g4 $1 Bg6 22. f3 $1 ({It's still too early to snatch material:} 22. Nxg6 hxg6 23. Qxe4 Qxe4 24. Bxe4 b4 25. Bb2 Rbc8 {∞ .}) *

