22... b4 $6 {The position is extremely complicated and demands concrete treatment. The text allows White to control the centre.} (22... Bxc5 $1 23. dxc5 Qxc5+ 24. Kh1 b4 25. Bb2 exf3 26. Bxf3 Rfe8 {∞ is a forced try for Black.}) 23. fxe4 Qe6 24. Bb2 Bf6 ({(It must be noted that Black can try instead of the text move)} 24... f6 $2 25. Nxg6 hxg6 26. Qg3 {± .}) ({Or} 24... Rfd8 $2 25. Rc1 $2 (25. Qg3 {±}) 25... Bf6 26. Nxc6 Qxc6 27. e5 Qa6 28. exf6 Re8 29. Qf2 Be4 30. Bf1 {∞ R. Leitao – A. Fier, Santos 2006.}) 25. Nxc6 (25. d5 {was possible:} Qe8 26. Qg3 $1 (26. Nxg6 $2 Bxb2 27. Nxf8 Bxa1 28. Qxa1 cxd5 29. exd5 Qe3+ 30. Kh1 Kxf8 {-+}) 26... Rb5 27. Rc1 Ra5 28. g5 Bxe5 29. Qxe5 Qxe5 30. Bxe5 Rxa2 31. Bf3 {⩲ .}) (25. Nc4 $5 {is an untested and rather interesting alternative:} Rbd8 (25... Qxg4 26. Qg3 Qxg3 27. hxg3 Rfc8 28. e5 Bd8 29. Nd6 Rc7 30. Bc1 {∞}) 26. e5 Be7 27. Qg3 {∞ .}) 25... Qxc6 26. e5 Qa6 27. exf6 Rfe8 $6 ({After} 27... Qxf6 $2 28. Qf2 $1 Qg5 29. d5 Qxg4 30. Qd4 Qxd4+ 31. Bxd4 {+- , Black's position is totally hopeless.}) ({Probably best was} 27... Rbe8 $1 28. Qf1 Bd3 $1 29. Qf3 (29. Qf4 $2 Re2 {-+}) 29... Be4 30. Qf1 Bd3 {.}) 28. Qf1 $1 ({If White snoozes with} 28. Qf2 Re2 29. Qg3 Rbe8 30. Bf1 Qc8 31. Bxe2 Rxe2 {, he suddenly finds himself in danger of losing. As Black is seeking counterplay against the white king, it is logical to exchange the queens, allowing the white pawn phalanx to move forward.}) 28... Qe2 $1 ({If now} 28... Bd3 $6 {, then} 29. Qf4 {± , as the [b8]-rook is hanging, stopping} Re2 {.}) 29. Qf2 $1 ({Again best. Not much is promised by} 29. Qxe2 $6 Rxe2 30. Bc1 Re1+ (30... Be4 31. Bf1 Rc2 32. Bf4 Rd8 33. Be5 gxf6 34. Bxf6 Re8 35. g5 Bd5 36. Be5 Rxe5 37. dxe5 Rxc5 {H. Banikas – A. Sokolov, Ermioni}) 31. Kf2 Rbe8 {∞ .}) 29... Qxg4 $6 (29... Qd3 $2 {should be bad after} 30. Re1 $1 (30. Bf1 Qe4 31. h3 {±}) 30... Rxe1+ 31. Qxe1 {± .}) ({But Black had to opt for} 29... Qa6 $1 30. Bf1 Qe6 31. Qf4 Rbd8 32. h3 {⩲ .}) 30. h3 $1 Qg5 (30... Qh5 31. Re1 $1 {and the pawns will start to roll.}) 31. Bc1 $1 {Transferring the bishop to a better position, after which it will be virtually impossible for Black to cope with White's passed pawns.} (31. d5 $2 Be4 {∓ would have been a blunder.}) 31... Qh5 ({Black could have tried} 31... Qxf6 32. Qxf6 gxf6 33. Bf4 Rbc8 34. Bb7 Rcd8 35. d5 Be4 36. Rd1 {, although his position would not be that attractive.}) 32. Bf4 Rbd8 $6 (32... Re2 $2 {cannot hold after} 33. Qf1 $1 Rxg2+ 34. Qxg2 Re8 35. Rf1 gxf6 36. c6 {+- .}) ({But Black's only option was} 32... Rbc8 $1 33. Re1 $1 Bf5 34. Re3 {± .}) 33. c6 $1 Be4 (33... Re2 34. c7 Rc8 35. Qf3 Qxf3 36. Bxf3 Rc2 37. Re1 gxf6 38. Re7 {, with a triumphant d-pawn march.}) 34. c7 Rc8 35. Re1 *

