18... Kg7 $2 {A mistake played by Van Wely, after which his position is beyond salvation.} 19. e5 $1 {A beautiful and thematic (liberating the [g2]-bishop, which wins the game! Threats like [Qxf6]+ or [Ne4], or simply the use of the [e4]-square for his [g2]-bishop) (which is absolutely crucial for the success of his brilliant attack) (, just fuel White's attack.)} ({Continuations like} 19. Qh4 $2 Rh8 20. Bd4 Qd8 21. g5 hxg5 22. Qxg5+ Kf8 23. Bxf6 Qb6+ 24. Kh1 Rh7 {are good only for Black.}) 19... fxe5 (19... Qe7 20. exf6+ Qxf6 21. Bd4 {+- , or 19...dxe5 20.Bxh6+! and mate follows.}) 20. Bxh6+ $1 {A final, impressive sacrifice, signifying the culmination of White's attack.} Kg6 ({The bishop's capture leads to mate in six:} 20... Kxh6 21. Qf6+ Kh7 22. Be4+ Bf5 23. Bxf5+ Kg8 24. Qg5+ Kh8 25. Qh6+ Kg8 26. Qh7# {.}) 21. Qh4 $1 (21. Qh4 {The final subtlety. After the queen thrust, White creates manifold mate threats:} Rg8 {(21...f5 22.Qh5+ Kh7 ( 22...Kf6 23.Qg5+ Kf7 24.Qg7+ +- ) 23.Bxf8+ Kg8 24.Bh6 +-)} 22. Be4+ f5 23. Bxf5+ Kf7 (23... Bxf5 24. Qh5+ Kf6 25. Nd5+ {+-}) 24. Qh5+ Ke7 25. Bg5+ Kf8 {(25...Kd7 26.Qf7+ Kc6 27.Be4+ Kb6 28.Be3+ +-)} 26. Bxe6 {+- . Black resigned.}) 1-0

