31. Kg1 Bd5 $6 ({The simplest was} 31... Bxa2 $1 {and then ...[Bd5], with an extra pawn compared to the game.}) 32. Qe2 Qd7 33. a3 {Black's position seems to be quite nice, but still, he has to find an acceptable plan. Attacking the white king cannot be a bad one!} Ne6 $1 {Threatening ...[Ng5]-[h3]+.} 34. Qe3 f6 35. h4 Ng7 $1 36. Kh2 Nf5 {What would you prefer: the black [f5]-knight or the white [d1]-rook?} 37. Qf4 Qe6 $1 {Threatening ...[Qe2]+.} 38. Qd2 Bc6 39. Re1 Qd6 $1 40. Qf2 Qxd3 ({Another winning line was} 40... Nxh4 41. Be5 fxe5 42. gxh4 e4+ {+ -+ .}) 41. h5 Nh6 $2 ({Black would win easily with} 41... Qd5 {, intending ...[Ne3]! With his last move, he believed that the win was very near. However, he had overlooked White's next move, after which a queen exchange is forced and results in an endgame where White holds the draw without much effort.}) 42. Qe2 $1 Qxe2+ {So Black was forced to exchange queens, losing his most valuable weapon: the attack against the white king.} 43. Rxe2 Kf7 44. Rc2 Be4 45. hxg6+ hxg6 46. Rc7 a6 47. Bd4 b5 48. Bc5 Ng8 49. Ra7 {White is winning back one of his less three pawns, achieving equality as the black kingside pawns lack activity.} Bd3 50. Bb4 Bc4 51. Rxa6 e5 52. Rc6 Bd3 53. Rd6 Bc4 54. Rc6 Bd3 55. Kg1 Nh6 56. Kf2 Ng4+ 57. Ke1 e4 {There is no way for either side to try for something more. A truly sad end to a very interesting game with two exchange sacrifices on [d4] and [d5]!} 1/2-1/2

