27... Qxa6 (27... Rxa6 28. Qe7+ Kh8 (28... Kg8 29. Rxd4) 29. Rxd4 cxd4 30. Qf6+ Kg8 31. Qxg6+ Kf8 32. Ng5 Ra7 33. Qf6+ Kg8 34. Bd5+ {.}) 28. Rxd4 $1 {Here comes the second exchange sacrifice the third in the game!.} Rxd4 (28... cxd4 29. Qf6+ {+- .}) 29. Qf6+ Kg8 (29... Kh6 30. Qh8+ Rh7 31. Qf8+ Rg7 32. Nf6 {+- .}) ({And} 29... Kh7 30. Ng5+ Kg8 31. Qxg6+ Kf8 32. Qe8+ Kg7 33. Ne6+ Kf6 34. Nxd4 cxd4 35. Qf8+ Rf7 36. Qd6+ Kg7 37. Qxd4+ {+- is also winning for White.}) 30. Qxg6+ Kf8 ({There are hardly any acceptable alternatives for Black, so this simply means that his position is beyond repair:} 30... Kh8 31. Nf6 {+- .}) ({Or} 30... Rg7 31. Qe8+ Kh7 32. Nf6+ Kh6 33. Qh5# {.}) 31. Qe8+ Kg7 32. Qe5+ $18 {The white pieces are dancing around the black king, while the black rooks are unable to participate and defend. Yes, two minor pieces can be better than two rooks, especially when cooperating with their queen against the opponent's king.} Kg8 (32... Kf8 33. Qh8+ Kf7 34. Ng5+ Ke7 35. Qe5+ {+- .}) ({Or} 32... Kf7 33. Ng5+ Kg8 34. Qe8+ Kg7 35. Ne6+ Kf6 36. Nxd4 cxd4 37. Qf8+ Rf7 38. Qh8+ Ke7 39. Qe8+ Kd6 40. Qxf7 Qxc6 41. Qg6+ Kc7 42. Qxc6+ Kxc6 43. Kf1 {+- .}) 33. Nf6+ Kf7 34. Be8+ Kf8 (34... Kg7 35. Nd7+ Kg8 36. Qg5+ Kh8 37. Qh5+ Kg7 38. Qf7+ Kh6 39. Qf8+ Kh7 40. Nf6+ Qxf6 41. Qxf6 {+- .}) 35. Qxc5+ Qd6 (35... Rd6 36. Ne4 Kxe8 37. Nxd6+ {+- .}) 36. Qxa7 Qxf6 (36... Rd1+ 37. Kg2 Rg1+ 38. Kh3 (38. Kxg1 $2 Qd1+ 39. Kg2 Qh1+) 38... Rh1+ 39. Kg4 {+- .}) 37. Bh5 Rd2 38. b3 Rb2 39. Kg2 {Black resigned, as a bishop and five pawns are too much for a rook!} 1-0

