1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. c4 dxc4 9. Qe2 Nf6 10. dxe5 Nd5 11. Bc2 Bc5 12. Rd1 Nce7 13. Nc3 Be6 14. a4 Qc8 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Ng5 Bb6 17. Rxd5 $1 {This positional sacrifice is an excellent one. Black's light squares become weak, and White gains some important tempos to continue his attack on the black king.} Nxd5 18. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7]} Qd7 19. Bf5 $1 Qc6 ({Judging by the outcome of the game, Black should have preferred} 19... Qe7 20. Qxd5 Rd8 (20... O-O 21. Bxh7+ Kh8 22. Bc2 {+-}) 21. Qc6+ Kf8 22. Bf4 {, but this can be considered a slow but sure death.}) 20. axb5 (20. Be4 {is stronger.}) 20... Qxb5 (20... axb5 21. Rxa8+ Qxa8 22. Be4 {+- is not an option either.}) 21. Nxf7 $1 {The [f7]-pawn is of minor importance as a material gain, but the further light squares weaknesses that are created around the black king and its presence in the centre are decisive factors.} Rf8 ({Unfortunately, the black king cannot find a safe shelter:} 21... O-O {Kxf7 Bd7+ +-} 22. Be6 Rae8 23. Bxd5 c6 24. Bxc6 Qb4 25. Qe4 $1 Rxf7 26. Bxe8 Rxf2 27. Be3 Bxe3 28. Qxe3 {simply finishes Black's survival chances.}) 22. e6 $18 g6 (22... h6 23. Ne5 Kd8 24. e7+ $1 Kxe7 25. b3 $1 (25. Ng6+ Kd6 26. Bf4+ Kc6 27. Be4 {is also fine.}) 25... Rxf5 26. Qxf5 {+- is also a lost case for Black.}) 23. Bc2 (23. Be4 c6 24. Nd6+ Ke7 25. Nxb5 Rxf3 26. Bxf3 {is a simple win.}) 23... Qc5 {Black had to take account of the [Ba4] threat.} 24. Bg5 c6 25. Rd1 *

