{Sacrificing the exchange in an endgame, or on the way to it, is less common than in the opening or in the middlegame. This is quite logical, as the rook’s power increases when the material reduces, thus making it more difficult for the minor piece. Still, we have many cases where the exchange sacrifice is embraced and compensated for by various assets. Of course, we will avoid examining very simple or theoretical positions. However, we will still consider the following example, played between the two Laskers, 100 years ago! Knowledge of such specific positions is a key to chess wisdom!} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Endgame Concept"]
[Black "Editor's Note"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463736708402"]

{Editor's Note: I have found an improvement on Grivas's analysis of the game Lasker-Lasker, New York 1924. You will first see Grivas's original annotations, followed by my correction of his oversight. However, I believe Grivas included this game primarily to illustrate the theoretical draw achieved on move 92, which remains highly relevant.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Endgame Concept"]
[Black "Emanuel Lasker – Edward Lasker, New York 1924 (Analysis)"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3r4/8/2k5/pp6/1P2KPP1/4N3/8/8 w - - 0 76"]
[PlyCount "56"]
[GameId "2130463736724787"]

76. bxa5 b4 {A famous and well-known position for the drawing mechanism which appeared... It seems that the black b-pawn is a reliable force and, as the white king cannot approach it, the pride of Black!} 77. a6 $1 {The right method. White will sacrifice his entire pawn army to ensure his king's involvement in the stoppage of the last black pawn.} Kc5 78. a7 b3 79. Nd1 Ra8 80. g5 $1 Rxa7 81. g6 Rd7 82. Nb2 Rd2 {A clever try, but White is on the alert.} 83. Kf3 $1 Rd8 ({Not of course,} 83... Rxb2 $2 84. g7 Rg2 85. Kxg2 b2 86. g8=Q b1=Q 87. Qf8+ {and White wins in 55 moves according to the tablebases!}) 84. Ke4 Rd2 85. Kf3 Rd8 86. Ke4 Kd6 {Nothing else to try...} 87. Kd4 $1 Rc8 88. g7 Ke6 89. g8=Q+ Rxg8 90. Kc4 Rg3 ({There is not much difference for the outcome by protecting the pawn from the file, but there is still a trap to deal with:} 90... Rb8 91. Kc3 Kf5 92. Nc4 $1 {It is important to force the pawn to his last but one rank. (92.Kc4? is losing: 92...Kxf4 93.Kc3 Ke3 94.Nc4+ Ke2 95.Nb2 Ke1! and Black will penetrate via [d2] or [d1], winning )} Kxf4 93. Nd2 b2 94. Kc2 Rb7 95. Nb1 {and the position is drawn, as the black king cannot attack the knight from behind - this is why White had to force the pawn to the second rank.}) 91. Na4 Kf5 92. Kb4 Kxf4 {And here we have a theoretically drawn position, as Black cannot make progress.} 93. Nb2 Ke4 ({Black cannot penetrate via the last rank, as this would take too much time, allowing White to capture the pawn:} 93... Kg4 94. Nc4 Kh3 95. Ka3 Kg2 96. Nd2 {.}) 94. Na4 Kd4 95. Nb2 Rf3 96. Na4 $1 {The only move!} (96. Nc4 {loses to} Rf8 97. Nb2 Rb8+ 98. Ka3 Kc3) ({and} 96. Nd1 {loses to} Kd3 $1 {.}) 96... Re3 97. Nb2 Ke4 98. Na4 Kf3 99. Ka3 Ke4 100. Kb4 Kd4 101. Nb2 Rh3 102. Na4 Kd3 103. Kxb3 Kd4+ 1/2-1/2

