57... Ke6 $2 {In the game, Black decided to play it 'safe'! The obvious 57...c2 was curtains and a 2-2 final result.} 58. g7 $1 Kf7 59. Kd3 Rf3 {Black thought he had an easy win, but obviously he was unaware of the Laskers' game!} 60. Kd4 Kxg7 61. Nc2 $10 {And finally, almost the same position on the c- instead of the b-file is on the board. The drawing mechanism is easy, and White knew what to do, giving the win to his team...} Kf6 62. Kc4 Ke5 63. Nb4 Ke4 64. Nc2 Rh3 65. Nb4 Rg3 66. Nc2 Rf3 67. Nb4 Kf5 68. Nc2 Kg4 69. Nd4 Rg3 70. Kb3 $1 {It is time to win the pawn before it is too late; the black king penetrates from behind!} Re3 71. Nb5 Kf4 72. Nxc3 Ke5 73. Kc4 Rh3 74. Nb5 Rh8 75. Nc3 Rc8+ 76. Kd3 Rd8+ 77. Kc4 Rd4+ 78. Kc5 Rd3 79. Kc4 Rxc3+ 80. Kxc3 1/2-1/2

