{In general, we have various cases where the purpose of an exchange sacrifice is to secure a draw. By the way, there seem to be numerous openings/variations/positions, where we already have quite a good idea of how to achieve a draw! The silicon monster is helpful and ready to load us with data to be exploited!} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Endgame Concept"]
[Black "Efstratios Grivas – Rumiana Gocheva, Kallithea 2007"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "A58"]
[PlyCount "63"]
[GameId "2130463736769850"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 g6 5. Nfd2 Bg7 6. e4 d6 7. cxb5 a6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. bxa6 Nbd7 10. Be2 Bxa6 11. O-O Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Qa5 13. Nc4 Qa6 14. Bd2 Rfb8 15. a4 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Qxe2 17. Nxe2 Nxe4 18. Nc4 Nxd2 19. Nxd2 Rxb2 20. Rad1 Rxa4 21. Nc1 c4 22. Nf3 Ra1 23. Nd4 Rxc1 ({Black could have continued pressurising White with} 23... c3 $1 24. Nde2 c2 {(a monster on the 7th rank!)} 25. Rd3 Rb4 {. The transition into an ending with an exchange less can hardly offer any winning chances.}) 24. Rxc1 Bxd4 25. Rxc4 Rd2 26. Rcc1 $1 Bc5 27. Rfd1 $1 ({White's d-pawn is more important than his f-pawn, as Black will not be able to create a passed pawn:} 27. g3 $6 Rxd5 28. Rc2 Kg7 {⩱ .}) 27... Bxf2+ 28. Kf1 Ra2 29. Ra1 Rb2 30. Rab1 Ra2 31. Rd3 $6 ({Natural was} 31. Ra1 {, with a draw.}) 31... Bh4 32. Rb4 (32. Rb4 {Black should have tried her chances with} Bf6 {, as she is in no position to lose...}) 1/2-1/2

