{Long-term compensation for the exchange sacrifice, doesn’t seem to be a major case in the endgame… Still, there are good games and examples that can prove the opposite.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Endgame Concept"]
[Black "Christopher Lutz – Anatoly Karpov, Dortmund 1993"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "E12"]
[PlyCount "148"]
[GameId "2130463736806718"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Ba6 5. Qc2 Bb7 6. Nc3 c5 7. e4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. Bf4 Nh5 11. Be3 Qb8 ({Here Anatoly Karpov had a bitter experience when he played} 11... Bd6 $2 {and resigned after the double attack} 12. Qd1 {1-0 L. Christiansen – A. Karpov, Wijk aan Zee 1993.}) 12. g3 f5 13. O-O-O Nf6 14. Bd3 Qb7 15. f3 fxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. fxe4 Bd6 18. Rhf1 Be5 19. Bf4 Qb8 20. Qe2 O-O 21. Qh5 {Lutz played the best move. What was Karpov's response?} Rxf4 $1 {An excellent and forced exchange sacrifice.} ({Bad was} 21... Bxf4+ $2 22. gxf4 g6 {(22...Rxf4? 23.e5 +-)} 23. Qg4 {and White is on the attack.}) 22. gxf4 Bxf4+ 23. Kb1 Qe5 $1 {Anatoly Karpov is not even afraid of exchanging queens!} 24. Qxe5 (24. Qe2 {was good too.}) 24... Bxe5 $13 {Time to take stock. Black has sacrificed the exchange and has in return: 1. The bishop pair. 2. A pawn. 3. Full domination on the dark squares. 4. Better pawn structure. 5. No targets for the white rooks.} 25. h3 a5 ({Not bad, but} 25... d6 $1 {with the idea ...[Be8]-[g6] looks fine.}) 26. b3 $6 ({As nearly always, White should consider returning the material with} 26. Rf3 a4 27. Rdf1 Bf6 28. Rxf6 gxf6 29. Rxf6 {.}) 26... d6 $1 27. Rd2 $6 {White is playing without any plan.} ({Not best was} 27. Rde1 Be8 28. Be2 Bg6 29. Bg4 Re8 30. Ka2 {(30.h4 h5 31.Bh3 Bf6)} h5 31. Be2 Kh7 {⩱ ,}) ({but} 27. Kc2 Be8 28. Rb1 Bg6 29. Kd2 Bd4 30. e5 Bxd3 31. Kxd3 Bxe5 32. Rbe1 {∞ looked OK.}) 27... Be8 28. Kc2 Bg6 29. Rdf2 Rc8 $1 {The black rook will get its activity via the 5th rank.} 30. Kd1 Bd4 31. Ra2 $6 ({Obviously better was} 31. Rg2 Bc5 32. Ra2 {⩱ .}) 31... Rc5 {Now the black rook is ready to pose threats.} 32. Rg2 (32. b4 Rg5 {∓ .}) 32... Rh5 33. Rf3 Be8 34. Kc2 g6 35. Be2 Re5 36. Bd3 Kg7 37. Rg4 g5 $1 38. Rf1 ({On} 38. h4 {, Black would have opted for} Bh5 $1 39. Rfg3 Bxg4 40. Rxg4 h5 {(40...Be3 41.hxg5 Bxg5 ∓)} 41. Rxg5+ Rxg5 42. hxg5 h4 {∓ .}) 38... Bc5 39. Kb2 Bg6 (39... Bh5 $1 40. Rg2 Bg6 41. Re2 {⩱ .}) 40. h4 $6 {White got tired of a wait and see policy.} ({But that was the only option and here} 40. Rg3 {⩱ was a must - there was no need to give Black a passed pawn...}) 40... gxh4 41. Rxh4 Rg5 $6 (41... d5 $1 {was quite good:} 42. cxd5 exd5 43. Rff4 h5 44. Bc2 Be7 {∓ .}) 42. Rh2 Rg3 43. Bc2 Bd4+ 44. Kc1 a4 (44... h5 {, with the idea ...[Kh6]-[g5], was quite joyful. It seems that Karpov is not in a hurry...}) 45. bxa4 Rxa3 46. Kd2 Rg3 47. Bd3 Rg5 48. Rfh1 Be5 ({Black doesn't want to allow anything like} 48... Kf6 49. Rxh7 $1 Bxh7 50. Rxh7 {, although he would still stand better:} Rg2+ 51. Be2 Ke5 52. Re7 Bc5 {⩱ .}) 49. Rh3 Bd4 (49... Rg2+ 50. Kd1 Ra2 51. Bc2 {⩱ .}) 50. R3h2 Rg3 51. Rf1 Bf6 52. Rb1 Bg5+ 53. Kc2 Be3 54. Ra1 Bg1 $6 ({Black missed the accurate} 54... d5 $1 55. cxd5 exd5 56. a5 dxe4 57. Bf1 Bd4 58. Ra4 Be5 59. Rh1 Rc3+ 60. Kd1 bxa5 61. Rxa5 Bf4 {⩱ .}) 55. Rd2 Kf6 56. a5 ({Here White had his chance:} 56. e5+ $1 Kxe5 {(56...dxe5 57.Bxg6 hxg6 58.a5 bxa5 59.Rxa5 g5 60.c5 Bd4 61.Rd3 Rg2+ 62.Rd2 Rg3=)} 57. Re1+ Be3 58. Bxg6 hxg6 59. Rd3 Kf4 60. Rxd6 e5 61. Rf6+ Kg5 62. Rxe3 Rxe3 63. Rxb6 Ra3 64. Rb5 Kf4 65. a5 e4 66. c5 e3 67. c6 e2 68. Kd2 Kf3 69. Re5 Ra2+ 70. Kd3 Rxa5 71. Re3+ Kf4 72. Rxe2 {.}) 56... bxa5 57. Rxa5 $6 {A mistake.} ({White should have opted for the above drawing continuation with} 57. e5+ $1 {.}) 57... Bc5 58. Ra1 $6 ({Passive; the active} 58. e5+ {should have been tried:} Kxe5 59. Bxg6 hxg6 60. Re2+ Kf6 61. Ra8 g5 62. Rf8+ Ke7 63. Rg8 g4 {(63...e5 ⩱)} 64. Re4 Rg2+ 65. Kd3 g3 66. Reg4 Bf2 67. R4g7+ Kf6 68. Rg6+ {.}) 58... Ke5 $1 {Now, the white pieces will remain passive, while the black king will join the battle, helping his pieces to finish the job.} 59. Rf1 Bg1 {With the lethal threat ...[h5]-[h4]-[h3].} 60. Rdd1 Be3 61. Rf8 Rg2+ 62. Kb3 Rh2 $1 63. Bb1 Bh5 64. Re1 Bf2 65. Rf1 Bc5 66. Re1 Be2 67. Ba2 Rh3+ 68. Kb2 Ba3+ 69. Ka1 Bd3 70. Bb1 Bb4 $1 71. Rc1 Bd2 72. Rd1 Bc3+ 73. Ka2 Bxc4+ 74. Ka3 Be2 0-1

