{The following two examples of the legendary Vishy Anand are quite instructive:} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Endgame Concept"]
[Black "Viswanathan Anand – Michael Adams, Wijk aan Zee 2005 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E15"]
[PlyCount "35"]
[GameId "2130463736859972"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. b3 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Be7 7. Bg2 c6 8. Bc3 d5 9. Ne5 Nfd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. O-O Nf6 13. e4 b5 14. exd5 cxd5 {Black's last move should be considered a natural recapture, of course, but after White's powerful response, the only justification for Black's play is to accept the exchange and just grin and bear the pressure.} 15. c5 $1 b4 16. Bxb4 Bxf1 17. Bxf1 ({Editor's Note:} 17. Qxf1 {is possibly even stronger, making ...[e5] more difficult to achieve for Black:} e5 18. dxe5 Nd7 19. Bxd5 {±}) 17... e5 18. Bc3 $1 {'Mickey' Adams puts up a fairly stiff defence, at least until the end, and that the best assessment his position can be given is 'very difficult to handle in practice'. Generating activity without creating further weaknesses is very problematic.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Endgame Concept"]
[Black "Anand vs. Adams #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/p3bppp/5n2/2Ppp3/3P4/1PB3P1/P2N1P1P/R2Q1BK1 b - - 0 18"]
[PlyCount "10"]
[GameId "2130463736868165"]

18... a5 {A tough call. White will now have two powerful united passed pawns, but the rooks are crying out for an open file.} 19. a3 $1 Ne4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. b4 $1 axb4 22. axb4 Rxa1 23. Qxa1 $14 {White's bishop pair is rather strong.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Endgame Concept"]
[Black "Anand vs. Adams #3"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3q1rk1/4bppp/8/2P1p3/1P1Pp3/2B3P1/5P1P/Q4BK1 b - - 0 23"]
[PlyCount "38"]
[GameId "2130463736872262"]

23... Qd5 $1 {Again, rightly giving priority to activity.} 24. dxe5 Ra8 25. Qc1 Ra2 26. Qe3 Rc2 27. Qd4 $1 {Going for a clear endgame. Where only White can have winning chances.} Qxd4 28. Bxd4 $14 {White has got two pawns and the bishop pair for the exchange, but the black rook is rather active, so Black should hold, but with 'difficult' moves at certain moments.} Kf8 29. h4 Ke8 30. e6 fxe6 $6 {Although not losing yet, shattering the pawn structure cannot be advisable.} ({Natural was} 30... Bf6 $1 31. exf7+ Kxf7 32. Be3 Ke6 {, when Black should hold.}) 31. Bxg7 Rc1 32. Bd4 Kd7 33. Be3 Rc3 34. Bd4 Rc1 35. Kg2 Kc6 $2 ({Careless! After} 35... Rb1 $1 36. b5 Rc1 37. c6+ Kc7 38. Be3 Rc2 39. Kh3 Bc5 $1 40. Bxc5 Rxc5 {, Black is holding.}) 36. Be3 Rc2 37. Ba6 $2 (37. h5 Rc3 38. Kh3 Kd5 39. Ba6 {± should be accurate.}) 37... Kc7 38. Kh3 Rc3 $2 ({The exchange of the dark-squared bishops seems to be a must in this ending, so Black should opt for} 38... Rb2 $1 39. b5 e5 $1 40. Kg4 Rc2 41. b6+ Kb8 42. Kf5 Bxc5 43. Bxc5 Rxc5 44. Kxe4 Ra5 45. Bd3 Kb7 46. Kf5 e4+ $1 47. Kxe4 Kxb6 {.}) 39. Bd4 $2 ({Natural and strong was} 39. Kg4 Rb3 40. Bc4 Rxb4 41. Bxe6 {± .}) 39... Rb3 $1 40. b5 Rd3 $2 {The decisive mistake.} ({A difficult drawing line could be found in} 40... Kd7 $1 41. Kg4 Rd3 $1 42. c6+ Kc7 43. b6+ {(43.Be3 Rxe3! 44.fxe3 Bc5=)} Kxc6 44. Bxd3 exd3 45. Be3 Bb4 46. Kf3 h5 {.}) 41. b6+ $1 Kc6 42. Bb5+ $1 {A nice deflection to finish the game!} 1-0

