1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 Bg5 12. Nc2 Rb8 13. a4 bxa4 14. Ncb4 Bd7 15. Bxa6 Nxb4 16. cxb4 O-O 17. O-O Bc6 18. Rxa4 Bxa4 19. Qxa4 Qe8 20. Qxe8 Rfxe8 {As always, it is important not just to look at the quality of the minor pieces but also the scope of the rooks. Here they look pretty well under control.} 21. b5 $14 {[%cal Gb5b6,Gb6b7] Everything is simple - the pawn goes to [b7] and it is clear that Black has a difficult defence. Maybe he can hold, but only White can play for a win.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Endgame Concept"]
[Black "Anand vs. Van Wely #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1r2r1k1/5ppp/B2p4/1P1Np1b1/4P3/8/1P3PPP/5RK1 b - - 0 21"]
[PlyCount "4"]
[GameId "2130463736884552"]

21... f5 $1 {Activity is the secret!} (21... Bd8 $6 22. Rc1 {± M. Womacka – Q. Yuan, Internet 2020, looks great for White.}) ({Also bad is} 21... Red8 $6 22. h4 Bxh4 23. Rc1 {± C. Silva Lucena – A. Mercado Larrea, Lucena 2012.}) 22. b6 $1 (22. exf5 e4 23. b6 Re5 24. Bc4 Kf8 {should be OK for Black.}) 22... fxe4 {Vishy Anand demonstrates resources of White's position, but this unexpectedly offers Black concrete possibilities for counterplay. The general idea is to distract the bishop either from [c1] or from [e7] - the knight can sometimes come to [c6] via [e7].} 23. Re1 $14 {This should be preferable, as in M. Wozniak – M. Dubinski, Karpacz 2013.} (23. h4 $6 {was played in the game.}) ({But not} 23. b7 $6 Rf8 $1 24. g3 Rf7 25. h4 Bh6 26. g4 Bf4 27. Re1 Rfxb7 28. Bxb7 Rxb7 {(. This motif ...[Rf8]-[f7xb7], returning the exchange and achieving a more or less equal position, is typical, and we can meet it in several positions in this game.)}) *

