1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O e6 6. Nc3 a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Ng5 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Nc6 11. Qf4 Ra7 12. Rd1 Rd7 13. Be3 Be7 14. Na4 b5 15. cxb5 axb5 16. Nb6 Rb7 17. Rac1 Na7 18. Qd4 h6 19. Nf3 O-O 20. a4 e5 21. Qc3 Rxb6 22. Bxb6 Qxb6 23. Qc7 Nc8 24. Rc6 Qxc7 25. Rxc7 Re8 26. a5 d5 27. Rdc1 Nd6 28. a6 Bf8 29. a7 Ra8 30. Nxe5 Nfe8 {White seems to be on the verge of winning, thanks to his strong, passed a-pawn, which is close to promotion. But he faces some problems with the black defensive pieces.} 31. Nd7 $1 {The exchange sacrifice is the solution! Actually, White sacrifices his [c1]-rook, which is somewhat 'useless' in the game's natural course.} Nxc7 32. Rxc7 {Now the threat is of course, [Nb6].} Nc8 ({The alternative was} 32... Nc4 33. b3 Bd6 34. Rb7 Na5 35. Nb6 $1 Re8 {(35...Nxb7 36.Nxa8 Bc5 37.Nb6 +-)} 36. Rd7 Bc5 37. a8=Q Rxa8 38. Nxa8 {+- .}) 33. Rxc8 $1 Rxc8 34. Nb8 Bd6 35. a8=Q Rxb8 36. Qxd5 $18 {And White went on to win smoothly.} Bf8 37. Qe5 Rb7 38. Qe8 b4 39. b3 Re7 40. Qb5 Re6 41. Qc4 g6 42. e4 Re5 43. Qd4 Ra5 44. e5 Ra6 45. Qd5 h5 46. f4 Ra2+ 47. Kh3 Re2 48. Qd3 Re1 49. Qd2 Rb1 50. Qd3 Re1 51. Qd2 Rb1 52. e6 Rxb3 53. Qd7 1-0

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Passive Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463737048400"]

{In this chapter, we will examine games where the exchange sacrifice was not a desperate last step before resignation, but rather the best option in cramped or inferior positions requiring special measures. " A passive exchange sacrifice, born out of necessity, can be the only way to stay in the game. " Despite being less ‘forceful’ than its active counterpart, it often provides excellent chances, as the compensation – determined by the opponent’s strengths and weaknesses – can offer opportunities to play for a win. This sacrifice is still embraced in modern chess. And who better than Tigran Petrosian to guide us through this topic?} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Passive Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Black "Samuel Reshevsky – Tigran Petrosian, Zurich 1953 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E58"]
[PlyCount "54"]
[GameId "2130463737064785"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 c5 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 b6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bb2 c4 12. Bc2 Bg4 13. Qe1 Ne4 14. Nd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Bh5 16. f3 Bg6 17. e4 Qd7 18. Rae1 dxe4 19. fxe4 Rfe8 20. Qf4 b5 21. Bd1 Re7 22. Bg4 Qe8 23. e5 a5 24. Re3 Rd8 25. Rfe1 {[%cal Rh2h4,Rg4f3,Rd4d5] A famous example. Tigran Petrosian didn't like his position, as White is threatening to continue with [h4], or [Bf3] and [d5], if the [c6]-knight moves.} Re6 $1 {An exchange sacrifice borne out of necessity. Black's compensation will lay on: 1. Extinguishing White's initiative. 2. Taking full control of the light squares. 3. Creating a strong fortress.} 26. a4 (26. h4 Ne7 {is no different. White has to accept the sacrifice.}) 26... Ne7 $1 (26... b4 $2 27. d5 $1 Rxd5 28. Bxe6 fxe6 29. Qxc4 {± .}) 27. Bxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Bd3][%cal Gg6d3]} (27... fxe6 {If} 28. Rf1 {then} Nf5 {.}) *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
