[White "8) The Passive Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Black "Tal vs. Petrosian #1"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3q1rk1/3n1ppp/p2b1r2/P1pPp2P/1pP1P3/1N2BQ2/1P4P1/R4RK1 w - - 0 31"]
[PlyCount "4"]
[GameId "2130463737077075"]

31. Qg4 Rf4 $1 {Suddenly comes the point! As Tigran Petrosian said 25 years later: " My mind worked in some other way then! "} 32. Bxf4 exf4 {[%csl Ya5][%cal Gd7e5,Rh5h6] Let's see what Black achieved by his exchange sacrifice: 1. He no longer has a cramped position. 2. His minor pieces are well-placed and active. 3. The [a5]-pawn is a target for the dark-squared bishop. 4. Full control of the dark squares. 5. An important outpost on the [e5]-square. 6. A somewhat exposed white king. But do not let yourself get carried away by all these positive aspects; White still is an exchange up, so an interesting battle is on the cards.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Passive Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Black "Tal vs. Petrosian #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3q1rk1/3n1ppp/p2b4/P1pPp2P/1pP1PrQ1/1N2B3/1P4P1/R4RK1 w - - 0 32"]
[PlyCount "4"]
[GameId "2130463737085268"]

32. Rxf4 {32.Bxf4 was Tal's move in the game. What to do if the slightly suboptimal 32.Bxf4 is played?} exf4 33. Bxf4 Qf6 $1 {Black has good play against White's weak pawns as compensation for his little sacrificed material.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Passive Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal – Tigran Petrosian, Riga 1958 (Analysis)"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "C97"]
[PlyCount "145"]
[GameId "2130463737089365"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Bd7 13. Nf1 Nc4 14. Ne3 Nxe3 15. Bxe3 Be6 16. Nd2 Rfe8 17. f4 Rad8 18. fxe5 dxe5 19. d5 Bd7 20. c4 Rb8 21. a4 b4 22. a5 Rf8 23. Ba4 Bxa4 24. Rxa4 Rbd8 25. Qf3 {A natural follow-up for Black would be something like ...[Ne8]-[d6], blockading the passed white d-pawn and exchanging the bishop by ...[Bg5] or ...[Bh4]. But, as his position would then be a bit cramped, Petrosian had already worked out a better option in his mind.} Rd6 $1 26. Nb3 Nd7 27. Raa1 Rg6 28. Rf1 Bd6 29. h4 Qd8 30. h5 Rf6 31. Qg4 Rf4 $1 {Suddenly comes the point! As Tigran Petrosian said 25 years later: " My mind worked in some other way then! "} 32. Bxf4 (32. Rxf4 exf4 33. Bxf4 Qf6 $1 {(, intending ...[Ne5] is unclear, as Black has good play against White's weak pawns as compensation for his little sacrificed material.)}) 32... exf4 {Let's see what Black achieved by his exchange sacrifice: 1. He no longer has a cramped position. 2. His minor pieces are well-placed and active. 3. The [a5]-pawn is a target for the dark-squared bishop. 4. Full control of the dark squares. 5. An important outpost on the [e5]-square. 6. A somewhat exposed white king. But do not let yourself get carried away by all these positive aspects; White still is an exchange up, so an interesting battle is on the cards.} 33. Nd2 Ne5 34. Qxf4 ({White could try} 34. Qf5 g6 35. Qh3 Qg5 {∞ .}) 34... Nxc4 35. e5 $1 ({Maybe it is time to acquiesce to splitting the point with} 35. Qf2 Nxd2 36. Qxd2 Qh4 37. Rf3 Re8 38. Re1 Qh2+ 39. Kf1 Qh1+ 40. Kf2 Qh4+ {, but Mikhail Tal was never in a peaceful mood, especially in his younger years.}) 35... Nxe5 $6 {Too optimistic.} ({The natural continuation is} 35... Nxd2 36. exd6 Nxf1 37. Rxf1 h6 38. b3 {⩲ .}) 36. Ne4 $1 h6 37. Rae1 $2 {A serious mistake, returning the favour.} ({Good was} 37. b3 Bb8 38. d6 {± and White is on the top.}) 37... Bb8 $1 38. Rd1 c4 $1 {Now it is Black who has the better chances, as a new, important outpost has appeared on the [d3]-square. White's king is in trouble.} 39. d6 Nd3 40. Qg4 $2 {A mistake that could turn the tables.} ({White had to opt for} 40. Qe3 Qd7 41. Rxd3 cxd3 42. Qxd3 Ba7+ 43. Kh2 Qd8 44. Kh3 Qxa5 45. g4 Qe5 {∞ .}) 40... Ba7+ 41. Kh1 f5 $1 42. Nf6+ ({Or} 42. Rxf5 Rxf5 43. Qxf5 Qh4+ 44. Qh3 Qxe4 {-+ .}) 42... Kh8 $1 (42... Qxf6 $2 43. Qxc4+ Kh7 44. Rxd3 {+- .}) 43. Qxc4 Nxb2 44. Qxa6 Nxd1 45. Qxa7 (45. Rxd1 Bb8 46. Nd5 Qg5 {-+ .}) 45... Qxd6 $1 ({Much better than} 45... Nc3 $2 46. Qe7 gxf6 47. Qe3 $1 Rf7 48. a6 Qxd6 49. a7 Qd8 50. Rxf5 {∞ .}) 46. Qd7 Qxf6 $6 (46... Rd8 $1 47. Qxd6 Rxd6 {-+ would be won for Black.}) 47. Qxd1 Rb8 $2 ({Again,} 47... Qa6 $1 48. Qa1 f4 $1 49. Rf3 Rf5 {-+ would be the end.}) 48. Rf3 $2 (48. Qd3 $1 b3 49. a6 Qh4+ 50. Kg1 Qe7 51. Qd4 Rb4 52. Qf2 Qd7 53. Rb1 Kh7 54. Qc5 Rb5 55. Qf2 {⩱ .}) 48... Ra8 $2 {Another bad mistake in this blunderful series!} ({Good was} 48... Rb5 49. Qe1 Kh7 {-+ .}) 49. Qe1 $1 Rxa5 50. Qxb4 Re5 51. Qf4 {Now Black tried to win for more than 20 moves, but his position no longer provides winning chances.} Kh7 52. Kh2 Rd5 53. Rf1 Qg5 54. Qf3 Re5 55. Kg1 Rc5 56. Qf2 Re5 57. Qf3 Ra5 58. Kh2 Kh8 59. Kg1 Ra2 60. Qd5 $2 (60. Kh2 $1 {would preserve the balance.}) 60... Rc2 $2 (60... Qe3+ $1 61. Kh2 Ra4 $1 62. Rf3 Rh4+ 63. Rh3 Rxh3+ 64. gxh3 Qe2+ 65. Kg1 Qxh5 {-+ .}) 61. Qa8+ Kh7 62. Qf3 Rc1 63. Rxc1 Qxc1+ 64. Kh2 Qc7+ 65. Kh3 Qe5 66. g4 $1 fxg4+ 67. Kxg4 Qg5+ 68. Kh3 Qf6 69. Qe4+ Kg8 70. Qe8+ Qf8 71. Qxf8+ Kxf8 72. Kg4 Kf7 73. Kf5 1/2-1/2

