1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 Be4 11. Qc1 Bb7 12. a3 Qc8 13. b4 Nbd7 14. Bc3 Ne4 15. Nbd2 Bd5 16. Qc2 Nxd2 17. Bxd2 Qb7 18. Rac1 Rac8 19. e4 {White seems to have gained a slight advantage, mostly due to Black's backward c-pawn. But still, this must not be enough as Black's pieces are decently placed and he has control over the important [h1]-[a8] diagonal; or maybe not?} Bxe4 20. Ng5 Bxc2 (20... Bxg2 $2 21. Qxh7# {.}) 21. Bxb7 Bd3 $1 22. Rfe1 Bc4 ({A forced exchange sacrifice, as after} 22... Rb8 23. Rxc7 {, White retains a clear advantage.}) 23. Bxc8 Bxg5 $1 {A useful move. In blocked pawn structures knights are more important than bishops, so Black first exchanges White's important minor piece.} 24. Bxg5 Rxc8 {Time to take stock. Black sacrificed the exchange while forced, M. Carlsen had planned it beforehand, and as compensation, he can present: 1. A pawn. 2. Active minor pieces. 3. Bad white bishop all white pawns are placed on the bishop's colour. 4. No open files for White's rooks. Of course, this is a clear case of a passive exchange sacrifice, aiming mostly to keep the balance.} *

