27. h4 Kf7 28. Kf2 c6 $1 29. Bd6 Bd5 $10 {A 'monster' appeared on the [d5]-square, keeping all of Black's important pawns protected in a hypothetical strong chain.} 30. Bc5 Na4 $1 (30... Nc4 $6 31. Ra1 $1 h5 $6 {(31...Nb2)} 32. Re2 {and White is ready to play [a4].}) 31. g4 Ra8 {Trying to get some activity on the a-file. Of course, Black will never open it if he cannot control it first.} 32. Re2 a5 33. Bd6 ({After} 33. Rce1 $6 Nxc5 34. dxc5 {(34.bxc5 b4)} axb4 35. axb4 e5 {(, only Black can try to win as his pieces are far more active and he can also put pressure on White's weaknesses b4, f3.)}) 33... axb4 34. Bxb4 (34. axb4 Nb6 {and Black controls the only open file.}) 34... Nb6 35. Bc5 {White has no active or concrete plan at his disposal, so he decided to call it a day. A quite correct and interesting game.} Na4 36. Bb4 Nb6 37. Bc5 {And a draw was agreed here.} 1/2-1/2

