1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 cxd4 6. exd4 O-O 7. a3 Be7 8. d5 exd5 9. cxd5 Re8 10. Be3 d6 11. h3 Nbd7 12. Ng3 Bf8 13. Be2 Rxe3 {An interesting exchange sacrifice, aiming to get compensation by controlling the dark squares and the bishop pair.} (13... g6 14. O-O Bg7 15. Bd4 {⩲ was suggested instead, by Garry Kasparov. Editor's Note: This could also be considered an active sacrifice - it's a little ambiguous. The play unfolds slowly afterwards and Black banks on White being unable to capitalize on the open c-file with the extra rook.}) 14. fxe3 g6 15. O-O Qe7 16. Qd4 Bg7 17. Qf4 Ne8 $5 {An interesting regrouping.} ({Natural was} 17... Ne5 18. Rac1 Bd7 19. Nge4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 f5 21. Nf2 {, when White would be ready for [e4]. In general, the unnecessary advance …f5 should be avoided by Black, as it would allow a white [e4] to open files and exchange the backward and weak [e4]-pawn.}) 18. Rac1 Be5 19. Qf2 Ndf6 20. Bd3 h5 21. Nge2 Nh7 {The black knights are placed around their king, trying to find squares and, in a way, waiting for White to show his hands. Black's position is quite stable and not easy to break.} 22. Nf4 Nf8 ({But not} 22... Bd7 $2 23. Nxh5 $1 gxh5 24. Bxh7+ Kxh7 25. Qxf7+ {+- .}) 23. Nb5 a6 24. Nd4 Bd7 25. Rc2 Bg7 26. Qg3 Rb8 $2 {Allowing a strong tactic.} (26... Rc8 27. Rxc8 Bxc8 28. Kh1 {was the correct continuation.}) 27. Re2 $2 ({Quite strong was} 27. Nde6 $1 h4 {(27...fxe6? 28.Nxg6 Nxg6 29.Qxg6 Nf6 30.Rxf6! Qxf6 31.Qh7+ Kf8 32.Rf2 +-)} 28. Qg4 {(28.Qg5 Qxg5 29.Nxg5 Nf6 30.g3 ±)} Nf6 29. Qxh4 Bxe6 30. dxe6 Nxe6 31. Nxe6 Qxe6 32. Kh1 {± .}) 27... Nf6 28. Nf3 Be8 $1 {Square [d7] is needed for the black knights' regrouping.} 29. e4 N6d7 30. Rc2 Ne5 31. Nxe5 Bxe5 {The dark squares are totally controlled by Black, while White finds it difficult to create an aggressive plan.} 32. Qf2 Nd7 $1 33. b4 Qd8 34. Be2 Bg7 35. Nd3 Ne5 36. Nxe5 Bxe5 37. Rfc1 {The only thing left for White is the open c-file. But Black can create enough counterplay to preserve the balance.} Kg7 38. Rc7 Qg5 $2 (38... h4 39. Kh1 Qg5 {was quite OK for Black.}) 39. R1c2 $2 ({White missed the strong} 39. h4 Qd8 40. g4 $1 {, gaining the upper hand.}) 39... h4 $1 40. Bg4 Kh6 $1 41. Kh1 b6 42. Ra7 ({The alternative was} 42. Bd7 Bg3 $1 43. Qf3 Qe5 44. Bxe8 Rxe8 45. Rxf7 Qxe4 46. Rc1 Qe3 $1 47. Ra1 Qxf3 48. Rxf3 Re5 {⩲ .}) 42... Bg3 43. Qd2 Bf4 44. Qd4 Be5 45. Qg1 a5 46. Qc1 Bf4 47. Qa1 Be5 48. Qg1 axb4 49. axb4 Bf4 50. Qa1 Be5 51. Qa3 Kg7 (51... Qf4 52. Qc1 Kg5 53. Be2 Qxc1+ 54. Rxc1 Kf4 {∞ was a necessity.}) 52. Rf2 Bf6 $2 {A bad idea.} ({Black had to opt for} 52... Kh6 $1 {.}) 53. Qd3 Qe5 54. Be6 $1 Kg8 55. Qf3 Kg7 56. Qf4 $2 (56. b5 Rd8 57. Rf1 Qb2 58. Qe3 Rb8 59. Qf4 {+- .}) 56... Qd4 $2 (56... Qxf4 $1 57. Rxf4 Be5 58. Rf1 Kh6 $1 59. Bxf7 Bb5 60. Rc1 Rf8 {∞ .}) 57. Rf1 $6 (57. b5 Be5 58. Qf3 {+- .}) 57... b5 58. Bg4 $1 (58. Rc7 $6 Ra8 {and ...[Ra1], should be fine for Black.}) 58... Rd8 $1 (58... Qxa7 59. Qxf6+ Kg8 60. Qxd6 {+- .}) 59. Rc7 Qb2 $6 (59... Ra8 60. Qxd6 $2 {(60.Bd7 Be5 61.Qf3 Qb6 62.Rc6 Qa7 63.Bxe8 Rxe8 64.Ra6 Qd7 65.Qg4 ±)} Be5 61. Qe7 Bxc7 62. Qxc7 Ra1 63. Rxa1 Qxa1+ 64. Kh2 Qf6 65. Bf3 Bd7 {.}) 60. Rc2 $1 Qd4 61. Rd2 Qe5 (61... Qc3 62. Rd3 $1 Qb2 63. Rdf3 $1 Be5 64. Qg5 Ra8 65. Qe7 {+- .}) 62. Qxe5 Bxe5 63. Rc2 Bd7 64. Be2 $6 (64. Bxd7 Rxd7 65. Rc8 {+- .}) 64... f5 $1 65. Rc7 Kh6 66. Bd3 fxe4 67. Bxe4 Kg5 68. Bd3 Bd4 69. Rb7 (69. Rf3 $1 Bb6 70. Rb7 Bd4 71. Kh2 Be5+ 72. Kg1 Bd4+ 73. Kf1 {+- .}) 69... Bc3 {After many inaccuracies or blunders from both sides, it was time for White to reap his efforts.} 70. Bxb5 $2 {But not like this.} ({Good was} 70. Rb1 Kf6 71. Bxb5 Bf5 72. Rb3 {+- .}) 70... Bf5 71. Be2 Ra8 $1 72. b5 Ra2 73. Bf3 Rb2 74. Rb8 Bd4 {Black's activity especially his rook should preserve the balance. Although White tried, he couldn’t improve his position…} 75. Rd1 Bc5 76. Kh2 Be3 77. Re1 Bf2 78. Rf1 Bc5 79. Re8 Bd4 $1 80. Rd1 Bf2 $1 81. Be2 Bd7 82. Re4 Bf5 83. Re8 Bd7 1/2-1/2

