1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. c3 a5 6. e5 Nd7 7. d4 b6 8. h4 Be7 9. Bb5 Ncb8 10. Nf1 Ba6 11. Bxa6 Rxa6 12. Qd3 h6 13. Ng3 Nf8 14. Nh5 g6 15. Nf4 Qd7 16. h5 g5 17. Ne2 c5 18. Nh2 c4 19. Qc2 Kd8 20. Ng4 Qe8 21. a4 Ra7 22. Rb1 Rc7 23. f4 Nbd7 24. f5 {It seems that something went wrong for Black already, as his position is quite passive, and White enjoys a dangerous initiative on the kingside and especially on the f-file.} f6 $1 {A daring continuation, which includes an exchange sacrifice by force.} ({But the alternative} 24... Kc8 $6 25. O-O {± couldn't be rosy for Black... So, the necessity to survive, 'forced' Black to be creative...}) 25. fxe6 Nxe6 26. exf6 (26. Ne3 {was played in the game, 26.exf6 was the alternative.}) 26... Nxf6 27. Nxf6 Bxf6 28. Qf5 Bg7 $1 (28... Rf8 {is stronger} 29. Qxd5+ Rd7 30. Qa8+ Kc7 31. Qxe8 Rxe8 32. O-O Be7 {.}) 29. Qxd5+ Rd7 {[%cal Rd5a8,Ra8e8,Yd8e7] Black has sufficient counterplay for the pawn. But of course, the move chosen by White is logical; after all, how Black can protect his d-pawn? I am sure that White was aware of the exchange sacrifice to come, but he evaluated his position as better.} *

