26. Ne3 ({The alternative was} 26. exf6 Nxf6 27. Nxf6 Bxf6 28. Qf5 {, but after} Bg7 $1 29. Qxd5+ Rd7 {, Black has sufficient counterplay for the pawn. But of course, the move chosen by White is logical; after all, how Black can protect his d-pawn? I am sure that White was aware of the exchange sacrifice to come, but he evaluated his position as better.}) 26... fxe5 $1 27. Nxd5 exd4 $1 28. Nxc7 Kxc7 ({A far better move than the game's} 28... Nxc7 $6 {.}) 29. cxd4 Bb4+ 30. Kd1 (30. Bd2 Nxd4 31. Qxc4+ Bc5 {∞}) 30... Ne5 $1 31. Rf1 (31. dxe5 Qd7+ 32. Bd2 Rd8 33. Nc3 Nd4 34. e6 $1 Nxe6 {∞}) 31... Rf8 {Black should be happy with his position. As long as both kings are exposed, no side can feel safe...} *

