28. Rg2 $6 {Passive.} ({White should think of} 28. Rf1 $1 Qxd5 29. Rd3 Qe6 30. Qd6 {± .}) 28... Qxd5 {Black now stands great thanks to his healthier pawn structure, safer king and more active pieces. The [h6]-bishop can in no way considered inferior to a white rook, as it has a greater sphere of action and several targets. Even if things don't work out well for Black, and he has to acquiesce to several exchanges queens, one pair of rooks and the queenside pawns, the resulting ending will be drawn. In view of all this, White should have avoided this position, where there is danger lurking and his winning chances are almost non-existent, not to mention his severe time-trouble.} 29. Rb1 Rf7 $1 ({After} 29... Ra8 $6 30. Qb3 $1 Qxb3 31. Rxb3 Rxa5 32. Rg4 $1 Bf4 33. Rxb7 Ra1+ 34. Kg2 g5 $1 {(, Black would just about secure the draw.)}) 30. Qb3 Qe4 $1 {A queen exchange at any moment would relieve White. Instead, Black improves his position by making use of tactics.} 31. Rf1 Kg7 32. Qe6 $1 Bd2 $1 33. Rg4 $6 ({White should have preferred} 33. a6 $1 bxa6 34. Qxa6 Bc3 $1 {and ...[Bd4], with a slight advantage for Black.}) 33... Qe2 34. Rg3 Bf4 35. Rg2 Bd2 $6 ({After the better} 35... Qb5 $1 {, intending ...[Qa4] followed by ...[Rd7]-[d1], White's defences would be stretched to the limit.}) 36. Qa2 $1 e4 37. Qb2+ Kh6 $2 {Quite optimistic!} ({The modest} 37... Kg8 {would preserve the balance. But Black wanted to get advantage of White’s heavy time-trouble…}) 38. Rg3 $1 {Black is now forced to exchange his rook with the 'bad' white rook on [g3], and not the [f1]-rook which is vital for the defence of the first rank.} Rf3 39. Rxf3 exf3 40. Qxb7 $2 {White didn't understand his advantage, so he opted for the secure line.} ({After} 40. Qd4 $1 Bxa5 41. Rd1 {± , Black would be in real trouble...}) 40... Bxa5 41. Qb8 $1 {The white queen returns to the defence in time, securing the position.} Bd2 $2 (41... Qe4 42. Kh1 Bc3 {was accurate.}) 42. Qg3 Bc3 43. Rb1 $2 ({After} 43. Qf4+ $1 {, White would be on the top:} g5 44. Qg4 Bf6 45. h4 $1 gxh4 46. Qf5 {± .}) 43... Qe4 $1 44. Rd1 Be5 45. Qh3+ Kg5 46. Kh1 h5 47. Qe6 $1 Kh4 48. Rc1 $1 Qg4 49. Qxg4+ Kxg4 {The point was shared here.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) The Exchange Sacrifice Fails"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2130463737285990"]

{Many of the exchange sacrifices we have witnessed take the form of a rook directly exchanging itself for a minor piece. There were no issues regarding their acceptance - recapture is forced, the job is done. Again, there is a simple premise to this section. Rooks come strongly into their own as the amount of material on the board diminishes. This is well-known of course - we have seen examples in which a rook tussles quite successfully with two minor pieces in the endgame, so it should be expected to perform very powerfully against one in most cases. To state this, however, is not to deny that there is an important sub-set of positions in which the activity of the rooks can be curtailed to a critical degree even very late in the day. However, beyond these cases there is something of a continuum which it is on occasion worthwhile bearing in mind when making calculations. A stark lesson in building any assumptions into one's calculations is that a sacrifice of this type will necessarily be accepted. This chapter should be seen simply as a reminder of the power of the rook, a recognition that in the presence of open files the degree of compensation required for the exchange should not be underestimated. The possibility of transforming a problematic material advantage back into a positional one in such a way should always be borne in mind. And of course, we have to keep in mind that an exchange sacrifice is not a forced winning asset, but simply an acceptable way of improving our winning chances, or trying to get an advantage over our opponent’s minuses. So, a failure loss or draw is a possibility, an equal one to winning! Nothing is guaranteed in this world, especially when one is material down!} 1. Z0 *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 3: The Exchange Sacrifice"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
