1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bg5 Re8 10. O-O-O Na6 11. Ne1 h6 12. Bh4 Be6 13. Nc2 c6 14. Rd2 Nc5 15. f3 a5 16. b3 h5 17. Bg5 Nfd7 18. Rhd1 f6 19. Be3 Bf8 20. Kb2 Be7 21. Ne1 Kf7 22. Kc2 Rec8 23. Nd3 Nxd3 24. Rxd3 Nc5 25. Bxc5 Bxc5 26. Na4 Bd4 27. c5 Rc7 28. Rxd4 $5 {Black's bishops look strong, while the prospect of the position opening up appears undesirable for White. Thus, White resorts to an exchange sacrifice, winning one pawn and hoping for another one a5 while also assuming the initiative. Meanwhile, Black's rooks seem hardly capable of being activated any time soon.} exd4 29. Rxd4 Re8 $1 {Black must seek activity. The immediate aim is to open lines with the help of ...[f5].} ({Editor's Note::} 29... Ke8 {or 29...Rd7 are seen by the engines as better 30.Rxd7+ Bxd7 'This sort of links back to the previous topic of passive exchange sacrifices.' – Nick_Webb_IRL, tester 31.Nb6 Rd8 .}) 30. Nb6 Kg7 $1 (30... Kg7 {Intending} 31. Z0 f5 32. e5 f4 $1 33. Rxf4 Bf5+ 34. Bd3 Bxd3+ 35. Kxd3 Rxe5 {.}) *

