1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3 6. Qxc3 b6 7. e3 Bb7 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O c5 10. b4 Nbd7 11. Bb2 e5 12. d4 exd4 13. exd4 Re8 14. Rae1 cxd4 15. Qxd4 Ne5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Qxd8 Raxd8 18. Rd1 Rc8 19. Rd6 Ba6 20. Rc1 Rc7 21. f3 Kf8 22. b5 Bc8 23. a4 Nd7 24. Ba3 Nc5 25. a5 Re6 26. Rcd1 Ke7 27. axb6 axb6 {White's control of the d-file and the bishop pair, gives him the upper hand.} 28. Rxb6 $2 {'Understandable', but not ultimately convincing.} ({White should have just regrouped here retaining a huge edge, with} 28. Rd8 {. The tricky bit is to know whether this will be the last chance to 'strike'.}) 28... Rxb6 29. Rd5 Ke6 30. Rxc5 ({Of course, White is under the illusion that he still stands better, so he avoided the drawing line} 30. Bxc5 Rxb5 31. Rd6+ Ke7 32. cxb5 Rxc5 33. Rd2 Rc1+ 34. Kf2 Rb1 {.}) 30... Rxc5 31. Bxc5 Rb8 $1 {As ever there is no more crucial variable than the activity of the rook, which can be achieved by the manoeuvre ...[Ra8]-[a2].} 32. Kf2 ({After} 32. Be3 Ra8 33. c5 Kd5 34. c6 Kd6 {, the white queenside pawn phalanx has been blocked. In the worst case, Black can sac his bishop for these two pawns, achieving an easy draw. This fact proves that White's exchange sacrifice wasn't appropriate.}) 32... Ra8 {Rooks belong to open files; via them, they can be active and create threats...} *

