27... Rb8 (27... b5 $6 {would fail to} 28. Ra3 {+- .}) 28. Bxa6 ({Natural, but the 'calm'} 28. h4 $1 gxh4 29. f4 f5 30. Bd3 fxe4 31. Bxe4 Bf7 32. Rxb7+ Rxb7 33. Bxb7 hxg3 34. f5 Nh4 35. Rxg3 Nxf5 36. Rc3 Nd4 37. Bxa6 {looks decisive.}) 28... Ra8 29. Bb5+ Kd8 30. a3 {And White won the pawn back, having a clear exchange up in the endgame...} h5 (30... Bxh3 31. Bc4 Ne5 32. Bd5 {± doesn't solve Black's problems.}) 31. Bf1 Ra7 32. Rb4 ({Also good is} 32. Rb5 f6 33. h4 Bd7 34. Rd5 Be6 35. Rd2 gxh4 36. gxh4 {± .}) 32... Bc8 33. Kb2 f6 (33... h4 $6 {plays in White's hands:} 34. gxh4 Nxh4 35. e5 {+- . White's task is still far from trivial since he must find a breakthrough and prevent Black's knight from sitting pretty upon an outpost. One technique in such a case is returning the exchange for other gains which here works very efficiently.}) 34. h4 $1 gxh4 35. gxh4 Bd7 ({Easier is} 35... Nxh4 36. e5 Nf5 37. exf6 $1 exf6 {(37...Nxe3? 38.f7 +-)} 38. Re1 h4 39. Bh3 {+- .}) 36. Reb3 Bc8 37. Rb5 Nf4 (37... Nxh4 38. Rxh5 Ng6 39. Rc3 {+- , as the white rooks are dancing on the many open files.}) 38. Bc4 Kc7 39. Bf7 $6 ({Accurate was} 39. Bd5 Ng6 40. Rc3+ Kd8 41. Bf7 {+- .}) 39... Bd7 40. Rc3+ Kd8 41. Rxh5 $1 {Simplification!} Nxh5 42. Bxh5 {White emerged with a clear passed extra pawn and better placed pieces, so Black's fate seems sealed...} e6 43. Bg6 Bc6 44. h5 Ke7 45. f4 $1 Ra8 46. h6 Rh8 47. h7 f5 {A last try for active defence.} 48. exf5 Kf6 49. Rd3 $1 Be4 ({After} 49... d5 50. Rg3 exf5 51. Rg5 Bd7 52. Kc3 {, Black has nothing to hope for.}) 50. Rxd6 Bxf5 51. Bxf5 Kxf5 52. Rd7 $1 b6 (52... Kxf4 {loses to} 53. Rxb7 e5 54. c4 e4 55. Rf7+ Ke5 56. Kc3 {+- .}) 53. Rf7+ Kg6 54. Rb7 Kf5 55. c4 Kxf4 56. Rxb6 e5 (56... Rxh7 57. Rxe6 {loses easily, as the black king is far away from the queenside.}) 57. Rh6 e4 58. Kc2 Ke3 59. Rh2 1-0

