21. Rb3 Nd7 22. Nd5 Rg6 $6 (22... b5 $1 23. Bh4 Bb7 24. Nc7+ Kf8 25. Nxa8 Bxa8 {seems to be equal. Returning the extra material is always a notable option!}) 23. Bd4 {Until this moment, H.Nakamura played all the moves extremely quickly, spending less than 10 minutes altogether and openly showing that this is his home preparation. Only now, for the first time, did the American stop blitzing out, and it took about 15 minutes before continuing. After the game, he revealed that his opening preparation went as far as this:} (23. Nc7+ Kf8 24. Bb2 {(24.Nxa8?! Nxf6 25.Nb6 Be6 ⩱)} Ra7 25. Ba3+ Kg7 26. Ne8+ {(26.Nd5!? Rc6 27.Nxf4= ∞)} Kh7 27. Nd6 Ra8 {(27...Rg8! 28.Rc3 f3! 29.Bd3 Ne5 30.Rxc8 Rxg2+ 31.Kf1 b5 ∞)} 28. Bh5 Rg7 29. Bxf7 {(29.Ne8!? Rg5 30.Bxf7 Nc5 31.Rb6 ⩲)} Ne5 30. Bd5 f3 31. g3 Bh3 32. Bb2 Rf8 33. Nf5 Re7 {(33...Bxf5 34.exf5 Rd7 35.Be6 Rd1+ 36.Kf2 Rd2+ 37.Kf1 Rd1+=)} 34. Bg8+ Kh8 35. Bd5 Kh7 {, with repetition and a draw. All these moves are nearly the best for both sides! There is little to comment on that... Except maybe that chess has become very deep these days indeed and that the homework in opening preparation fully pays off.}) 23... Rc6 *

