27. Kf2 Rd6 $2 ({Here, Hikaru Nakamura missed the chance to set more serious problems for his opponent. After} 27... Nc5 {, White's task would have been more complicated since there are many possibilities but no clear way to achieve equality.}) 28. Rb4 $1 {White is still a clear exchange down, but the strong bishop on [d4], together with weak black pawns, provide White sufficient compensation to keep the balance.} f6 (28... Rc8 {is hardly an improvement:} 29. Nxb5 Bxb5 30. Bxb5 Rc2+ 31. Kf3 Rxa2 32. Kxf4 Rxg2 33. e5 Rdg6 34. Ra4 {, as White gets sufficient counterplay.}) 29. Kf3 Rc8 ({White can defend as well after} 29... Ne5+ 30. Kxf4 Nc6 {, by} 31. Bc5 $1 Rd2 {(31...Nxb4?! 32.Bxd6 Nc6 33.Nd5 ⩲)} 32. Bh5+ Kd7 33. Bg4+ Kd8 34. Rb3 {∞ .}) 30. Nxb5 Bxb5 31. Bxb5 Ke7 (31... Ke7 {After} 32. a4 {, White has nothing to fear, so the players agreed to a draw.}) 1/2-1/2

